yan Guzman]]\n| \"Turn of the Shoe\" \n| colspan=\"3\" {{CNone}} || {{CRecurring|Recurring}} || colspan=\"3\" {{CNone}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[#Arthur Hackett|Arthur Hackett]]\n| John O'Brien\n| \"Know Your Frenemies\" \n| {{CGuest|Guest}} || {{CNone}} || {{CGuest|Guest}} || {{CRecurring|Recurring}} || {{CGuest|Guest}} || {{CNone}} || {{CGuest|Guest}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[#Linda Tanner|Linda Tanner]]\n| [[Roma Maffia]]\n| \"Face Time\" \n| colspan=\"3\" {{CNone}} || {{CGuest|Guest}} || {{CRecurring|Recurring}} || colspan=\"2\" {{CGuest|Guest}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[#Cindy and Mindy|Cindy]]\n| Melanie Moreno\n| rowspan=\"2\" | \"EscApe From New York\" \n| colspan=\"4\" {{CNone}} || {{CRecurring|Recurring}} || {{CGuest|Guest}} || {{CNone}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[#Cindy and Mindy|Mindy]]\n| Monica Moreno\n| colspan=\"4\" {{CNone}} || {{CRecurring|Recurring}} || {{CGuest|Guest}} || {{CNone}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[#Sydney Driscoll|Sydney Driscoll]]\n| [[Chloe Bridges]]\n| \"Surfing the Aftershocks\" \n| colspan=\"4\" {{CNone}} || {{CRecurring|Recurring}} || {{CNone}} || {{CGuest|Guest}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[#Talia Sandoval|Talia Sandoval]]\n| [[Miranda Rae Mayo]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | \"Fresh Meat\" \n| colspan=\"4\" {{CNone}} || {{CRecurring|Recurring}} || colspan=\"2\" {{CNone}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[#Jonny Raymond|Jonny Raymond]]\n| Will Bradley\n| colspan=\"4\" {{CNone}} || {{CRecurring|Recurring}} || colspan=\"2\" {{CNone}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[#Elliott Rollins|Archer Dunhill]]\n| Huw Collins\n| \"Of Late I Think Of Rosewood\" \n| colspan=\"5\" {{CNone}} || colspan=\"2\" {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[#Yvonne Phillips|Yvonne Phillips]]\n| Kara Royster\n| \"New Guys, New Lies\" \n| colspan=\"5\" {{CNone}} || colspan=\"2\" {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[#Sara Harvey|Sara Harvey]]\n| [[Dre Davis]]{{efn|In the third, fourth and fifth seasons, Harvey was portrayed by doubles and stock photos.}}\n| \"Game On, Charles\" \n| colspan=\"5\" {{CNone}} || {{CRecurring|Recurring}} || {{CGuest|Guest}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[#Liam Greene|Liam Greene]]\n| Roberto Aguire\n| \"Charlotte's Web\" \n| colspan=\"5\" {{CNone}} || {{CRecurring|Recurring}} || {{CGuest|Guest}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[#Jordan Hobart|Jordan Hobart]]\n| David Coussins\n| \"Charlotte's Web\" \n| colspan=\"5\" {{CNone}} || {{CRecurring|Recurring}} || {{CGuest|Guest}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[#Nicole Gordon|Nicole Gordon]]\n| [[Rebecca Breeds]]\n| \"No Stone Unturned\" \n| colspan=\"5\" {{CNone}} || {{CRecurring|Recurring}} || {{CGuest|Guest}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[#Lorenzo Calderon|Lorenzo Calderon]]\n| [[Travis Winfrey]]\n| \"Songs of Innocence\" \n| colspan=\"5\" {{CNone}} || {{CRecurring|Recurring}} || {{CNone}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[#Clark Wilkins|Clark Wilkins]]\n| Titus Makin Jr.\n| rowspan=\"2\" | \"Don't Look Now\" \n| colspan=\"5\" {{CNone}} || {{CRecurring|Recurring}} || {{CNone}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[#Sabrina|Sabrina]]\n| [[Lulu Brud]]\n| colspan=\"5\" {{CNone}} || {{CGuest|Guest}} || {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[#Marco Furey|Marco Furey]]\n| [[Nicholas Gonzalez]]\n| \"Hit and Run, Run, Run\" \n| colspan=\"6\" {{CNone}} || {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"10\" style=\"background-color:#ccccff;\" | Guest characters\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[#Dianne Fitzgerald|Dianne Fitzgerald]]\n| [[Mary Page Keller]]\n| \"Stolen Kisses\" \n| colspan=\"2\" {{CNone}} || {{CGuest|Guest}} || colspan=\"3\" {{CNone}} || {{CGuest|Guest}}\n|}\n;Notes\n{{notelist}}\n\n==Main characters==\nThe following list features characters that are considered fundamental to the series' storylines, consisting of the central group deemed as \"the Liars\" and the main antagonist \"A.\"\n\n===Spencer Hastings===\n{{main|Spencer Hastings}}\nConsidered the \"[[de facto]] leader\" of the group, '''Spencer Hastings''', portrayed by [[Troian Bellisario]], is intelligent, extremely ambitious, and strives for perfection in everything she does in an attempt to live up to the high expectations of her parents. Spencer's biggest rival is her older sister, Melissa, and the two are constantly fighting over something. Their relationship is often strained by the fact that Spencer has a habit of crushing on Melissa's boyfriends. In the first season, she begins a relationship with fellow student and strained Rosewood student Toby Cavanaugh. Throughout the series, Spencer is revealed to be the biological daughter of Mary Drake and the sister of Charlotte Drake.\n\n===Aria Montgomery===\n{{main|Aria Montgomery}}\nConsidered the \"alternative\" one of the group, '''Aria Montgomery''', portrayed by [[Lucy Hale]], is more outgoing in fashion and what she sees as acceptable behavior. She moves back to Rosewood with her family after living in Iceland for a year. Before Alison's death, she and Alison discovered that Aria's father was having an affair with one of his former students, Meredith, who became his coworker at Hollis College. Alison encourages Aria to tell her mother the truth, but instead, Aria reluctantly agrees to keep her father's secret. On top of that, she finds herself involved with her high school English teacher, Ezra Fitz, after making out with him in a pub bathroom and discovering he was her English teacher on the first day of school.\n\n===Hanna Marin===\n{{main|Hanna Marin}}\nPretty and fierce, '''Hanna Marin''', portrayed by [[Ashley Benson]], is the diva and \"[[it girl]]\" of the group, having taken Alison's place as the most popular girl at Rosewood High. Prior to Alison's death, Hanna suffered from [[Bulimia nervosa|bulimia]], which Alison frequently teased her over. Since her parents divorced, Hanna permanently lives with her mother. She feels betrayed by her father, who has remarried, and she does not get along well with his new wife and daughter. When Hanna's mother falls upon financial hardship, she steals thousands of dollars from the bank she worked at, which Hanna is forced to keep a secret.\n\n===Emily Fields===\n{{main|Emily Fields}}\nThe \"[[Jock (athlete)|jock]]\" of the group, '''Emily Fields''', portrayed by [[Shay Mitchell]], is a highly competitive swimmer, considered the star of Rosewood's swimming team. She is shown as a sweet and shy young. For a short time, Emily lives with Hanna, after her mother moves to Texas to live with Emily's father, who is stationed in Fort Hood. She begins to question her sexuality because of her feeling for Alison, but later accepts the fact that she is a lesbian and starts to date girls. She eventually begins a relationship with Sara Harvey, until she discovers that she is an ally of the antagonist.\n\n===Alison DiLaurentis===\n{{main|Alison DiLaurentis}}\nThe former \"[[Queen bee (sociology)|queen bee]]\" of her clique, '''Alison DiLaurentis''', portrayed by [[Sasha Pieterse]], used to be the most popular girl in school before her disappearance and alleged death. Although she cared for her friends, she enjoyed using their deepest secrets against them to keep them in line. Charming and manipulative, Alison was skilled at finding ways to blackmail everyone, and many people hated her. She knew everybody's secrets, but since she's been gone her friends are beginning to realize how little they really knew about her. She is revealed to be alive and on the run from \"A.\"\n\n===Mona Vanderwaal===\n{{main|Mona Vanderwaal}}\nA former \"unpopular\" girl at Rosewood, '''Mona Vanderwaal''', portrayed by [[Janel Parrish]], longed to be accepted into Alison's group and was continuously mocked by her. After Alison's disappearance, Mona befriended Hanna and they underwent an \"extreme makeover\" together; as a result, they both became popular students. When \"A\" appears, Mona becomes jealous of Hanna rekindling her friendships with the other Liars. She dislikes Caleb and makes attempts to break Hanna and Caleb up, though to no avail. She becomes romantically involved with Noel, much to Hanna's disapproval, but is later dumped by him for Jenna. When \"A\" begins sending Mona threatening notes, she grows closer to the Liars. In the second-season finale, she is in fact revealed to actually be \"A\" when she and Spencer travel to the Lost Woods Resort to uncover \"A\"'s lair. She is committed to a mental institution, Radley, after being diagnosed with [[borderline personality disorder]].\n\n===\"A\"{{anchor|A|A.D.|Uber A}}===\n{{main|A (Pretty Little Liars)}}\nThe main [[antagonist]], \"'''A'''\" is stalking and torturing the Liars in relentless and creative ways and also threatens their friends and family. In the second-season finale, it is revealed that Mona is \"A\". She is also the one who stalked Alison before her disappearance. However, when she is sent to Radley sanitarium, she is visited by CeCe Drake, who offers her a partnership and takes over the team of \"A's\", known as the A-Team. The team consists of Mona, Toby, Spencer, Sara, Lucas, Melissa, Wilden, Jenna, Noel, and Wren. Five years later, Alex Drake takes over and becomes Uber A, known as \"A.D.\", and forms the A.D. Team, consisting of Jenna, Sydney, Aria, Wren, Mona, and Mary.\n\n==Acquaintances of Aria Montgomery==\nThe following characters are all family members and acquaintances of '''Aria Montgomery''', one of the protagonists of the series.\n\n===Family===\n* {{anchor|Ella Montgomery}}'''Ella Montgomery''' ([[Holly Marie Combs]]) (seasons 1 \u2013 7) is Aria's mother, as well as a teacher at Rosewood High. Ella believes in treating her children as friends, not as property. She has mentioned that she doesn't want to push into Aria's private life, and she thinks that Aria should be allowed to keep secrets. Ella was unaware of her husband's affair with a student until \"A\" sent her a letter. After asking Byron to move out, and his refusal, she left the home. Eventually, Aria found out her parents were secretly getting back together, and Ella decides to move back in. When her son, Mike, is depressed, she doesn't feel he needs medication, and remains somewhat in denial about his illness. She finally receives her wake-up call when he attacks her in his bedroom. When Ella found out Aria was dating Ezra, she was angry, but she believed Aria when she said she had broken it off, and tried to win her back her freedom, which Byron didn't think she deserved. Later, she finds out that Aria and Ezra are still together, and decides she is going to try to understand their relationship. Ella is aware of A, and tries to send Aria to a boarding school to get away. Aria is furious, and blackmails her mother into not going through with it. Ella tearfully tells Aria how ashamed she is, and how she doesn't know how to save their relationship. In season 3, she and Byron have divorced and Ella tries to move on with her life not knowing how. Aria creates a profile for her on a dating website under the nickname \"Hot Mamma.\" Ella is furious at Aria but later she likes the idea and starts dating again. She befriends and starts dating the owner of the brew who is much younger than her. In season 4, she leaves Rosewood so she can go live with her boyfriend in Europe but returns at the end of season 4.\n* {{anchor|Byron Montgomery}}'''Byron Montgomery''' ([[Chad Lowe]]) (seasons 1 \u2013 7) is Aria's father and a history professor at Hollis College. He asked Aria to keep his affair with a student, Meredith, a secret after Aria witnessed them kissing. Regretting the affair and wanting them to be a family again, Byron moves the family to Iceland for a year as a sabbatical. The relationship between Byron and Ella becomes strained after A sends her a letter revealing Byron's affair. After spending some time apart, Ella and Byron slowly begin to rebuild their relationship. When Mike becomes depressed, Byron reveals that his brother Scott, who committed suicide, also suffered from mental illness; Byron feels guilty for not doing anything to help his brother. Byron finds out that Ezra is involved in a relationship with Aria after they tell him and Ella and is furious about it. In an effort to get Ezra away from Aria, Byron recommends him for a job in New Orleans. He also plots to send Aria to an all girls boarding school in Vermont. When Aria threatens to reveal his affair to his boss, he backs off from her but gets Ezra fired from Hollis. In season 3, Byron and Ella have divorced and Ella has moved out of the house. Byron starts seeing Meredith again. He informs Aria that Meredith got a job at Rosewood High, were Aria attends and Ella teaches. In the Halloween episode, it is revealed by Garrett that Byron may have seen Alison on the night she died. Alison told him,\"you know what I'm capable of!\"\n* {{anchor|Mike Montgomery}}'''Mike Montgomery''' ([[Cody Christian]]) (seasons 1\u20132, 4\u20136) is Aria's younger brother. A lacrosse player, he suffers from a mental illness, which causes him to burst into fits of anger and later leads him to break into people's houses for fun, before he begins to shut down emotionally and withdraw completely from his family. He blames Aria for the trouble between their parents. Mike accidentally discovered that Jenna and Garrett knew each other when he stole a pot made Jenna from Garrett's house. Mike reveals to Aria that the only reason he punched Ezra was because after Ezra and Aria announced they are a couple, he feared what Byron would have done to hurt Ezra judging by the look on his face and thought, \"better I do it, than him.\" Throughout the rest of the series he appears to have improved after going to a therapist. It does not tell when or if he was still seeing his therapist. He seemed to forgive Aria and their relationship is better. He stopped being rebellious and more focused of his family's problems and helping them out. He is dating Mona Vanderwaal.\n\n===Friends===\n* {{anchor|Holden Strauss}}'''Holden Strauss''' ([[Shane Coffey]]) (seasons 2\u20133, 7) is a childhood friend of Aria's who returns with his family from a year abroad in Portugal in the middle of Season 2. He asks Aria out on a date, and discovers that she only agreed so she could get out of the house unsupervised and try to meet Ezra. Instead of becoming upset, he suggest that they continue the cover, though he remains secretive about what he does during their fake dates. We later find out that his secret is more serious than it seemed at first when he accidentally reveals a very large bruise on his stomach, but he tells Aria not to worry about it. He eventually tells her that he is doing Tae Kwan Do, a Korean martial art, and that his parents forbid him to keep training, that is why he needs a cover. The situation turns out to be more complicated, though, when Ella tells Aria that Holden has a heart condition that could kill him any time. Aria goes to watch one of Holden's fights and she sees how much he loves to fight. In the sixth episode in season 3, he attends the same church party as Hanna and when Emily arrives, he runs into her and sparks a conversation. When he grabs a cupcake his wrist is exposed revealing a stamp from that night and Noel Kahn's party.\n* {{anchor|Clark Wilkins}}'''Clark Wilkins''' (Titus Makin Jr.) (season 6) is a friend of Aria's whom she met in a photography class at Hollis. Clark is later revealed to be an undercover cop, hired to protect Aria.\n\n===Relationships===\n* {{anchor|Ezra Fitz}}'''Ezra Fitz (Fitzgerald)''' ([[Ian Harding]]) (seasons 1 \u2013 7) is a former English teacher at Rosewood High School and later teaches at Hollis College. He became romantically involved with Aria after the two met at a bar and instantly bonded. When he discovered that Aria was his student, he attempted to break things off, but found himself unable to do so. He broke up with Aria for a little while in order to take time to think about their relationship. He quit his teaching position at Rosewood just before Noel threatened to expose Aria and Ezra's relationship. Ezra later explains to Aria that he was engaged to a girl named Jackie when he was in college, but that she broke it off; Jackie later returns to Rosewood after getting a teaching position at Hollis. Although Ezra loves Aria, he seems to still have some lingering feelings for Jackie, and the two remain close. His relationship with Aria is often strained by the fact that they have to hide that they are together. He confesses to Ella that he loves Aria (though she misunderstands and believes he is talking about Spencer) when he comes to comfort Aria after her arrest. In \"Through Many Danger, Toils, and Snares\" we find out that Aria broke up with Ezra because of Jackie threatening to expose their relationship but they later get back together after Aria explains to Ezra that Jackie was the reason why she broke up with him. Ezra and Aria later tell Byron and Ella that they are a couple which leads him to getting punched by Mike (though it's told he only did it fearing what Byron what would have done instead). Ezra later tells Jackie, who comes into his office trying to convince him it'll never work out for him and Aria due to age difference and the fact she's still a teenager, to get out of his office, saying he will not let her do anything to harm or hurt Aria ever again and that he wants nothing more to do with Jackie herself. Aria continues to attempt to convince her parents to allow her to date Ezra but in the meantime they try to set her up with someone else. When Aria calls Ezra, he tells her not to call him again. The two later rekindle their relationship when Aria leaves him a voice mail telling Ezra that, if he doesn't meet up with her, their relationship is over for good. Ezra turns up at the last minute after a student tells him to 'be bold' and the two kiss in the rain. Aria decides not to tell her friends that the two are back together, hoping that, by keeping it from them, she can also keep it from \"A\". They later have sex in his apartment after Ezra finds out that he has been fired from Hollis. In season 3, Aria and Ezra celebrate their one-year anniversary. Their relationship seems to be going smoothly until Ezra's younger brother Wesley \"Wes\" drops by unexpectedly. Bumps are soon formed in their relationship when Aria learns of Ezra getting his high school girlfriend Maggie pregnant and his mother paying her to disappear from his life, even though he wanted to do the right thing. Aria tracks Maggie down and discovers that she kept the baby, who is now a healthy 7-year-old boy named Malcolm, whom Ezra finds out about from a distraught Spencer. This leads him to leave Rosewood and seek out Maggie and his son; Ezra is back in Rosewood but only one day after he's back he gets a phone call from Maggie; Mrs. Fitzgerald sold Maggie's condo. Maggie asked Ezra if she and Malcolm can stay in Rosewood near him for a couple of days. Later when Spencer is part of the A-team, she picks up Malcolm from his karate class but is actually kidnapping him. Aria frantically tries to find him and when she does he tells her that Aria's friend Alison picked him up. Ezra gets a job at Rosewood High as a substitute teacher. After all the incidents with Malcolm, Aria decides that it is best that her and Ezra break up just after kissing him on the school stairs. In season four Ezra starts teaching full-time at Rosewood High again. After Aria has a dream that Ezra got arrested because of her she decided they should see other people, something Ezra had already suggested. Ezra would still do anything for Aria, as whenever she is having trouble he still steps up to help her. Ezra finds out Malcolm isn't really his son. In the season four summer finale, the Liars find a lair that they believe belongs to \"A\" and we see that Ezra is the owner, leading fans to believe him to be \"A\". However, he reveals in \"Free Fall\" that he is writing a book about Alison. He is also Board Shorts but is not the guy Alison met with at Cape May known as \"Beach Hottie\". He is shot by someone in a black hoodie, whom he claims was Shana, in the season four finale but survives and later rekindles his relationship with Aria and begins helping them out with \"A\". In season 7 Ezra Aria become engaged and get married in the show's finale episode. It is revealed that Aria can't have children so her and Ezra make plans to adopt after their honeymoon.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Biedenharn|first1=Isabella|title=Pretty Little Liars series finale recap: 'Til DeAth Do Us PArt'|url=http://ew.com/recap/pretty-little-liars-series-finale/4/|website=Entertainment Weekly|publisher=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=11 October 2017}}</ref>\n* {{anchor|Noel Kahn}}'''Noel Kahn''' ([[Brant Daugherty]]) (seasons 1\u20135, 7) is a popular jock and friends with Sean and Mike. He has feelings for Aria and briefly dates her, ending things when he discovers that Aria is seeing Ezra. Noel attempts to blackmail Ezra with this information, but ends up getting framed by \"A\" (for apparently stealing mid-term exams). After a suspension, he returns to school and becomes somewhat romantically involved with Mona, but eventually breaks up with her and starts dating Jenna. On the security tape Noel sent Spencer it shows that Jenna was dating Noel. It was revealed in the season four finale that Noel is helping Alison. Noel is revealed to be a member of the A-Team in Season 7 and was the person who poured blood on Spencer in the Dollhouse. He returned to Rosewood to begin working with Jenna, as well as Sara Harvey, to find Charlotte's sister, later revealed as Alex Drake. However, Noel kills Sara when she threatens their operation. He and Jenna trap the Liars and attempt to kill them but he ends up accidentally getting decapitated.\n* {{anchor|Jake}}'''Jake''' ([[Ryan Guzman]]) (season 4) is a martial arts instructor in Rosewood. Aria begins to take private lessons to help protect herself from \"A\". During one of the sessions, Aria kisses him and apologizes. But later, they start to hang out more and go on dates. On one of the dates, he learns about Ezra. With time, Aria and Jake's relationship heads to the next level. When Jake meets Ezra for the first time, he tells him to let Aria move on.\n* {{anchor|Liam Greene}}'''Liam Greene''' ([[Roberto Aguire]]) (season 6 - 7) was Aria's boyfriend during and after the time-jump. He works with her and encourages her to send Ezra to finish his book. Aria later breaks up with him due to not having feelings for him anymore after sleeping with Ezra.\n\n===Other===\n* {{anchor|Meredith Sorenson}}'''Meredith Sorenson''' ([[Amanda Schull]]) (seasons 1\u20133) is a former student at Hollis whom Byron had an affair with. She ignores Aria's pleas for her to stay away from Byron and in an effort to get close to Byron again, attempts to befriend Ella, who was unaware of the affair. In the beginning of season 3, \"A\" forces Aria to reveal a past secret that Aria and Alison trashed Byron's office and framed Meredith for the crime when Aria believes an earring she found proves that Byron and Meredith were still together after Aria found out about the affair. After the incident Byron did end all ties with Meredith because he felt threatened. But when \"A\" forces Aria to confess it was her, it gives now divorced Byron and Meredith another chance at a relationship. When Aria is forced to confess and apologize to Meredith, she returns the earring \"A\" gave her, which was taken from Alison's grave, only to find out the earring is not hers. Meredith became a teacher at Rosewood High. She later was burnt in a fire and led to believe that Aria did it (She's Better Now). In the episode \"Misery Loves Company!\", when Aria is sick, Meredith plays mom by taking care of her, when in reality she drugs Aria's tea to search her house. After Aria becomes suspicious, Meredith lures Aria down to the basement where she falls and becomes unconscious. When Hanna and Emily check on Aria, they too are tricked down into the basement. Byron finds them and Meredith escapes. It is revealed that Byron didn't kill Alison, even though she was blackmailing him about the affair.\n* {{anchor|Jackie Molina}}'''Jackie Molina''' (Paloma Guzman) (seasons 1\u20132, 5) is Ezra's ex-fianc\u00e9e. After getting a teaching job at Hollis, she hints at wanting to reconcile her relationship with Ezra. She discovers that Aria and Ezra are in a relationship, and uses this as leverage when Aria attempts to force her out of Ezra's life by threatening to expose a paper that Jackie plagiarized. Jackie forces Aria to break up with Ezra but the two later get back together and reveal their relationship to her parents when Ezra overhears Jackie threatening Aria. Ezra later tells Jackie to get out of his office when she comes by his office and to stay away from Aria after Jackie makes a comment about his relationship with Aria being \"a terrible mistake\", and that he wants nothing to do with Jackie again.<ref>{{cite web|title=PLL Season 2 Episode 14 Recap Baby We Are BACK|url=https://randomrecaps.wordpress.com/pretty-little-liars/pll-season-2-episode-14-recap-baby-we-are-back/|website=Word Press|publisher=Word Press|accessdate=11 October 2017}}</ref>\n* {{anchor|Zack}}'''Zack''' ([[Steve Talley]]) (seasons 3\u20135) is the former owner of The Brew and used to be engaged to Ella Montgomery.\n* {{anchor|Maggie Cutler}}'''Maggie Cutler''' ([[Larisa Oleynik]]) (seasons 3\u20134) is Ezra's ex, who was impregnated by Ezra after high school. She was paid a large sum of money to disappear from Ezra's life and to take care of his unborn child, whom he doesn't know about. In the eleventh episode, Aria pays her a visit at her school, where she reveals that she has a son named Malcolm. In the summer finale, she pays Ezra a visit, leaving Aria out. At the end of the season 4 summer finale, she reveals Malcolm is not Ezra's son. She soon leaves Rosewood with Malcolm to Seattle.\n* {{anchor|Simone}}'''Simone''' ([[Alona Tal]]) (season 1) is Aria's former babysitter. She comes back to Rosewood to visit her parents and also to help Ella Montgomery with her English class, where she is asked to be a speaker as an experienced freelance writer. She befriends Ezra Fitz thanks to the suggestion of Ella, much to Aria's chagrin. Simone develops a crush on Ezra, much to Aria's horror. Simone is oblivious to Aria's feelings, and the two have coffee together. After that, Ezra picks up on Aria's envying Simone, who is a talented writer and also age appropriate for Ezra. He admits to enjoying the time spent with her, but assures her that it's nothing more than that.\n* {{anchor|Malcolm Cutler}}'''Malcolm Cutler''' (Teo Briones) (season 3-4) is Maggie Cutler's son and was believed to be Ezra Fitz's seven-year-old son. His father is revealed not to be Ezra, but some \"mistake\" made by Maggie with another man.\n\n==Acquaintances of Spencer Hastings==\nThe following characters are all family members and acquaintances of '''Spencer Hastings''', one of the protagonists of the series.\n\n===Family===\n* {{anchor|Melissa Hastings}}'''Melissa Hastings''' ([[Torrey DeVitto]]) (seasons 1 \u2013 7) is Spencer's older sister, who was engaged to Wren at the start of the series, but later returns to Ian. A perfectionist and the favored daughter, she was Spencer's rival for most of their lives. Their competition led to Spencer kissing both Ian and Wren, which culminated in Melissa breaking off her engagement with Wren. After their breakup, Melissa rekindled her relationship with Ian and the two eloped; after which Melissa confided in Spencer that she just wanted the fighting between them to stop. Shortly after marrying Ian, Melissa becomes pregnant, which again causes a rift between her and Spencer, who suspects Melissa is covering for Ian. When Ian goes missing, Melissa refuses to believe Spencer's claims that he is dead, thinking that she is receiving text messages from Ian, who is in hiding. After the discovery of Ian's body, Melissa becomes depressed and apologizes to Spencer for choosing Ian over her. When Melissa finds Ian's phone in Spencer's bag, (although \"A\" put the phone in there), she believes it was Spencer sending the texts to her phone and vows she will never forgive Spencer for this. Melissa discovers that Jason is their half-brother and says that she can't be around their parents because they lied to her and Spencer. She still loiters around the house and Spencer and her friends begin to suspect that Melissa knows more about \"A\" and Ali's disappearance than she is letting on. They find a video taken inside Alison's room the night she disappeared, and Melissa is shown throwing open the door and yelling \"where is she?!\" The Liars also find out that Melissa was sending Ali threatening text messages, and had worked at a law firm that Ali had suspected of assisting \"A\" in messing with her life. Spencer and Melissa's father's gun goes missing, and Spencer fears Melissa took it. Even though Melissa didn't take the gun, her parents still feared that she killed Alison through jealousy, so her mother hired a private investigator to watch her. Toward the end of the second season, Melissa makes some odd statements that implies she knows some secrets about Alison and/or the N.A.T. club. Melissa lost her baby after Ian died. In the third-season finale it is revealed that Melissa is working with Jenna and Shana. In the fourth-season premiere it is revealed that she was the Queen of Hearts that drugged Aria on the Halloween train and put her in a box, along with Wilden. Spencer mentions to Melissa that Wilden was blackmailing her to do so, but Melissa never confirms this suspicion. In the fifth season, it is revealed that Melissa is Bethany Young's killer. She saw Spencer carrying a shovel and then found Bethany's body. She wouldn't look her in the face and assumed that it was Alison whom she thought Spencer had killed. She pushed Bethany into the ground and buried her, unaware that she was still alive, thereby killing her. After telling this to Spencer, Melissa flies back to England and it is revealed that she and Wren are seeing each other again.\n* {{anchor|Peter Hastings}}'''Peter Hastings''' ([[Nolan North]]) (seasons 1\u2013present) is the biological father to Spencer, Melissa, and Jason DiLaurentis. A lawyer who places a great emphasis on winning, he destroys evidence that he fears will indicate Spencer's involvement in Alison's murder. Initially he disapproves of Spencer and Toby dating; he warns Toby after he begins to work for him. Peter strongly dislikes the DiLaurentis family, who he claims are \"always crossing lines\". In Season 2, Episode 19, it is revealed that Peter did have an affair with Jessica DiLaurentis, that he is Jason's father and that Jason, Spencer and Melissa are all half-siblings. He paid a private investigator to look into Ali's disappearance, as he was afraid that Melissa had something to do with it since he found out Melissa had been sending Ali threatening text messages.\n* {{anchor|Veronica Hastings}}'''Veronica Hastings''' ([[Lesley Fera]]) (seasons 1\u2013present) is Spencer's and Melissa's mother. She had a breast cancer scare that she kept a secret from her family, not wanting to worry them. A lawyer, she frequently helps the girls out with legal situations. She dislikes Toby and his relationship with Spencer in the beginning, but she eventually becomes more tolerant of it. In Season 3, she defends Garrett after he gets arrested and eventually gets the judge to allow him to walk free.\n* {{anchor|Alex Drake}}'''[[Alex Drake (Pretty Little Liars)|Alex Drake]]''' ([[Troian Bellisario]]) (season 7) is the twin sister to [[Spencer Hastings]] and the half-sister of [[Charlotte Drake]], [[Melissa Hastings]], and [[Jason DiLaurentis]], as well as the daughter of [[Mary Drake]] and [[Peter Hastings]]. Alex was given up for adoption to a British family by Mary during her birth. Alex grew up in orphanages, not knowing anything of her real family, until the day that Wren Kingston came into her bar and immediately thought she was Spencer. She clarified her real identity and he revealed Spencer and everything to her. Wren introduced Alex to Charlotte and the two of them formed an immediate bond together, spending every moment with each other until Charlotte left to go back to the U.S. to play the game some more. Alex eventually learned of Charlotte's death and decided to avenge her by becoming Uber A. At first, Alex sent the Liars threats, using only Emojis to sign the texts. However, after kidnapping Hanna, Alex begins using the alias \"A.D.\" to sign off her texts. Alex convincingly masquerades as Spencer multiple times to be with Toby and trick the Liars. After the game ends, Alex goes back to London but returns a year later to kidnap Spencer and take her place, along with Mary and Mona's help. Alex explains herself to Spencer and reveals her entire story, also revealing that she has killed Wren to avoid having to break up with him. She also kidnaps Ezra. Spencer and Ezra escape and Alex is detained. However, Mona manages to kidnap both Alex and Mary and locks them away in her own personal dollhouse in France.\n\n===Friends===\n* {{anchor|Andrew Campbell}}'''Andrew Campbell''' ([[Brandon W. Jones]]) (seasons 3\u20136) is a secretary of the Decathlon team of which Spencer is a member. He and the rest of the team vote to remove Spencer from the team following her loss to Mona in a quiz-off, resulting in her not appearing at practices. Spencer challenged him to a strip version of quiz-off in order to get his vote to keep her on the team. In season five, he starts dating Aria, after he had been tutoring her. Later on the season Andrew becomes dark and shady, leading the Liars to assume that he is in fact \"A\". However, he turns out to be innocent after he was apprehended by police and released due to evidence proving he isn't \"A\". He claims that he intended to be the hero and find them after their kidnapping by CeCe Drake.\n* {{anchor|Eddie Lamb}}'''Eddie Lamb''' ([[Reggie Austin (actor)|Reggie Austin]]) (seasons 3\u20135) is a nurse at Radley Sanitarium. Toby used his name as his alias while he was working with Mona.\n\n===Relationships===\n* {{anchor|Ian Thomas}}'''Ian Thomas''' ([[Ryan Merriman]]) (seasons 1\u20132, 4) is Melissa's late husband. He attended high school with Jason and Garrett and was part of their \"N.A.T.\" club (the initials of a Latin phrase meaning \"We See All\"). Ian dated Melissa prior to Alison's death, although he was secretly having an affair with Alison, he also flirted and tried to get with Spencer, who had a crush on him. He returned to Rosewood shortly after Melissa broke off her engagement with Wren; after a small courtship, the two eloped and took up residency in the Hastings' renovated barn while their apartment in Philadelphia was being renovated. He had an uneasy relationship with Spencer, who became suspicious of him and believed he was Alison's killer. It is later revealed that Ian liked to secretly videotape the girls when they were getting undressed, and other videos such as Jenna threatening Toby to sleep with her. When Spencer confronts Ian about Alison's death, he claims he only pushed her, not intended for her to hit her head. After this he approaches Spencer and tries to kill her, stating that he's doing it for Melissa's benefit, but is killed by \"A\", who surprisingly intervenes. His body goes missing and he is presumed to be in hiding. However, his body is eventually discovered with his death staged to look like a suicide; leaving Melissa with his unborn child. \"A\" drops its phone in season 2, and the girls enlist Caleb's help. He finds videos of Ian, Garrett, Jenna, and Melissa in Alison's room that night. He hides the camera and they begin to argue about the videos. In the premiere episode of season 4, Mona reveals that even though she was \"A\", she was not the one who killed Ian, confessing she doesn't know who did. The person who pushed Ian is revealed to be Alison in the season finale of season 4, though she says she wasn't the killer. Carlo Marks who plays Ian in the pilot episode.\n* {{anchor|Wren Kingston}}'''Wren Kingston''' ([[Julian Morris]]) (seasons 1\u20134, 7) is a medical student who was engaged to Melissa. He was attracted to Spencer and later kissed her, which resulted in Melissa calling off their engagement. However, he later returns to Rosewood to help Melissa out with Ian, who at the time, they believe to still be alive. He obtains a job at the hospital in Rosewood, telling Spencer he came back for her, he then asks her if she wants to go out for a coffee but she says 'I have a boyfriend now', they leave it at that and go. He then comforts Spencer after her breakup with Toby, leaving her confused. After Mona is revealed to be \"A\", Wren develops a friendship with Hanna, as he volunteers at Radley Sanitarium where Hanna goes to visit Mona there on a regular basis. Eventually, the board at Radley threatens to transfer Mona to New York, and Wren helps Hanna testify to the board and gets her to remain at Radley. Hanna accidentally kisses Wren from happiness when she finds out Mona will not be transferred based on Hanna's testimony. Wren tends to get an unrequited crush on Hanna after the kiss and tries to woo her at times, but gets rejected. Most likely because he's Spencer's ex and she's secretly dating Caleb again. In Season 4, it is implied he knows about Red Coat. He goes with Melissa to London for unknown reasons. In Season 7, it is revealed that he is on the A-Team and an accomplice to \"A.D.\", who is revealed to be Wren's girlfriend and Spencer's twin sister [[Alex Drake (Pretty Little Liars)|Alex Drake]]. He is murdered by her later on.\n* {{anchor|Alex Santiago}}'''Alex Santiago''' ([[Diego Gonz\u00e1lez (actor)|Diego Boneta]]) (season 1) is an employee of Rosewood's exclusive country club. He meets Spencer after observing her practicing serves, and the two quickly enter into a relationship. Their relationship becomes strained after Melissa plants doubts about Spencer's feelings for him in Alex's mind, leading Alex to think Spencer is using him. Veronica is initially uncomfortable around Alex, which Spencer thinks is because of Alex being of a lower economic class, however, Alex explains that he comforted Veronica after her cancer scare. Alex breaks up with Spencer for good after \"A\" makes him believe Spencer applied for him to go to Europe for a tennis camp after he asked her explicitly not to.\n* {{anchor|Toby Cavanaugh}}'''Toby Cavanaugh ''' ([[Keegan Allen]]) (seasons 1\u20137) is Jenna's stepbrother, who forced him into a physical relationship with her through blackmail, and took the blame for the Liars accidentally blinding Jenna. After he returns to Rosewood, he strikes up a tentative friendship with Emily after saving her from Ben. Spencer disapproves of their friendship, believing that Toby is Alison's murderer. Emily goes to Homecoming with Toby and later confesses to him that she is a lesbian; her openness makes Toby try to confess to her about having a thing with Jenna, which Emily misunderstands, leading to a physical confrontation. Toby drops her off at the hospital before running away; he is later caught by the police, who had been tipped off by Jenna. After witnessing Toby being taunted in the street, Spencer begins to sympathize with him, and they bond even more when they realize they are both being framed for Alison's murder. Despite Spencer's parents distrust and dislike of Toby, they begin to date. After \"A\" threatens Spencer with Toby's safety, she decides to break up with him, not wanting him to get hurt. Later he gets injured, as a result of \"A\"'s tricks and ends up in hospital. He later learns that Wren kissed Spencer and had a one-day fling with her. Back in the hospital he tells Wren that he would beat him up if he tried anything like that again. When he is discharged he begins to act cold towards her. In the season 2 finale he admits that pretending not to love her was the hardest thing he has ever done, she then approaches him and gets ready to slap him but before she has a chance he pulls her close to him and kisses her. In season 3, Spencer and Toby seem to have moved past all the problems that plagued their relationship, seeming happier and more in love than they ever were. In the season 3 summer finale, Toby is revealed to be a member of the \"A\" team. After a while Spencer becomes aware of Toby's affiliation with the \"A\"-Team and she slaps him, as a response to his betrayal. Her mom then arrives home allowing him the moment he needs to sneak away. Spencer had not seen him since, and became quite bitter and broken from the betrayal. Spencer later finds a body and assumes it is Toby from the tattoo. Mona also tells her that it is his body. Later when Spencer joins the \"A\" team she finds out that Toby is alive and that he joined \"A\" team to find out about Red Coat. They go to a motel room together and re-kindle their love for each other. In season 4, Toby learns more information about his late mother. He finds out that she committed suicide at Radley. When Spencer and him go there, there is a long roof that goes around the whole building and Spencer thinks someone may have pushed her and covered it up to make it look like a suicide. Toby talks to his mother's therapist, the one she talked to the day she died. He said for her to stay away from that \"blonde girl\". It is later learned that the blonde may possibly be CeCe Drake. James Neate who plays Toby in the pilot episode.\n* {{anchor|Jonny Raymond}}'''Jonny Raymond''' ([[Will Bradley]]) (season 5) is a painter who Spencer met at The Brew. During 5B, he was staying in Hastings' barn until Veronica kicked him out. He kissed Spencer before his departure.\n* {{anchor|Marco Furey}}'''Marco Furey''' ([[Nicholas Gonzalez]]) (season 7) is a new detective at the Rosewood Police Department who hooks up with Spencer at the Radley Hotel Bar the night he arrives in town.\n\n===Other===\n* {{anchor|Yvonne Phillips}}'''Yvonne Cavanaugh (n\u00e9e Phillips)''' (Kara Royster) (season 6-7) is Toby's fianc\u00e9 and later wife after the five year time jump. She is also the daughter of Kristine Phillips, Veronica Hasting's opponent in the race for Pennsylvania State Senate. She and Toby decide to move out of Rosewood but are in an accident before they get far. After hitting a deer, she and Toby are sent to the hospital and Yvonne is sent into a medically induced coma due to the severity of her injuries. She wakes up from her coma but is still very weak. She accepts Toby's idea that they marry that very day despite her being in the hospital bed. As she and Toby celebrate, they discuss where they want to go for their honeymoon. She tells Toby that she is happy before she breaths her last breath, dropping her flowers in the process and leaving Toby devastated.\n\n==Acquaintances of Hanna Marin==\nThe following characters are all family members and acquaintances of '''Hanna Marin''', one of the protagonists of the series.\n\n===Family===\n* {{anchor|Ashley Marin}}'''Ashley Marin''' ([[Laura Leighton]]) (seasons 1\u20137) is Hanna's mother, who worked at a bank in Rosewood and later for Jessica and Jason DiLaurentis. She is angered by Hanna's shoplifting, and has an affair with Detective Darren Wilden in order to keep Hanna from being charged. After some financial hardship caused by the divorce, Ashley falls behind on her bills and resorts to stealing money from the safety deposit box of a client; the money is later stolen (by \"A\", unbeknownst to Ashley) and Hanna is forced to slowly earn it back by hurting Lucas. Although she is divorced from Tom, Hanna's father, Ashley still has lingering feelings for him; when he comes for a visit, they end up spending the night together. However, she ends the affair when she realizes that Tom will never change. After Emily's parents move to Texas, Ashley invites Emily to come live with her and Hanna. She initially disapproves when Hanna starts dating Caleb, but eventually warms up to him even saying how she sees \"herself\" in him. In season 3, she begins to date a Pastor named Ted. In season 4, Ashley is framed for Detective Wildens murder by \"A\", and is arrested. Spencer tells Hanna that she could spend life in prison...or worse. In season five she has a brief affair with Jason DiLaurentis.\n* {{anchor|Tom Marin}}'''Tom Marin''' ([[Roark Critchlow]]) (seasons 1\u20132, 4\u20135) is Hanna's father. He divorced Hanna's mother, Ashley, after having an affair with Isabel, his current wife. When he comes to Rosewood to visit Hanna, he begins to grow close to Ashley once more, something which is encouraged by Hanna. Tom eventually sleeps with Ashley, but she breaks things off with him when she realizes that he will never change. His wedding to Isabel is interrupted by Hanna, who reveals his affair with Ashley to Isabel. Despite Hanna ruining Tom's wedding to Isabel, Ashley reveals to Hanna that Tom still married her. Tom later reveals that he will be moving back to Rosewood with Isabel and Kate so he can be closer to Hanna.\n* {{anchor|Kate Randall}}'''Kate Randall''' (Natalie Floyd, later [[Natalie Hall]]) (seasons 1\u20132) is Isabel's daughter and Hanna's stepsister. Although Hanna is friendly to Kate at first, she begins to resent her. Kate is shown to possess a malicious streak, with a willingness to use manipulation for her own purposes. Hanna had said some unkind things about Kate, but apologizes to her. Kate pretends to accept the apology, but makes comparisons of how to break in horses and how she would break in Hanna. She humiliates Hanna after getting her drunk at their parents' rehearsal dinner. Even though Hanna stopped Isabel's wedding to her father, Kate still becomes Hanna's stepsister when their parents get married at the courthouse. Tom later moves back to Rosewood with Isabel, and Kate is enrolled at Rosewood High. It appears that Kate actually wants to be friends with Hanna at school, but she was really trying to look like an innocent victim, even sending the school a naked photo of herself and framing Hanna for it. But after finding out the truth, Hanna neutralizes Kate for a time.\n\n===Friends===\n* {{anchor|Lucas Gottesman}}'''Lucas Gottesman''' (Brendan Robinson) (seasons 1\u20133, 5\u20137) was an unpopular student at Rosewood, who harbored an unrequited crush on Hanna, with whom he developed a friendship. Having been frequently tormented by Alison, he often expressed his happiness at her death, going so far as to destroy Alison's memorial, believing her cruelty shouldn't have been forgiven posthumously. Although initially angered by Hanna's rejection of his romantic feelings, he eventually accepts it and even befriends Caleb. He seeks Hanna out for dating advice after he becomes involved with a girl named Danielle, however, it is unclear if any relationship developed between them. Soon afterward, due to a series of misunderstandings and coincidences, the Liars suspect Lucas may be \"A\"'s helper. It is later revealed that Lucas had gambled away thousands of dollars of Caleb's savings. Following this, his friendship with Hanna and Caleb is severely strained, and Lucas grew increasingly more troubled. It was revealed in the third season that he had been visiting Mona at Radley, because she had discovered he was selling test answers and was blackmailing him into working on the A-Team as her personal assistant. He moved away at the end of season 3, out of fear and as a way to start over. Mona soon reveals to the Liars that it was he who gave Emily the massage as \"A\". He returns to Rosewood in season 5 and begins helping Mona to take down Alison. After Mona's supposed death, Lucas begins helping the girls to stop Alison, who they believe killed Mona. Lucas is not seen after this but is revealed to have attended prom with Jenna Marshall.\n* {{anchor|Gabriel Holbrook}}'''Gabriel Holbrook''' ([[Sean Faris]]) (seasons 4\u20135) is a Pennsylvania State Police Officer and the detective assigned to Darren Wilden's murder case.\n\n===Relationships===\n* {{anchor|Sean Ackard}}'''Sean Ackard''' ([[Chuck Hittinger]]) (season 1) was Hanna's boyfriend prior to the beginning of the series. Having crushed on Sean since before Alison's disappearance, motivated by insecurities about her weight, Hanna puts a lot of pressure on their relationship. When Sean refuses to have sex with Hanna, she becomes upset and wrecks his car, though Sean understands and forgives her. However, the mystery surrounding \"A\" and Alison's death begin to take a toll on their relationship and that, combined with Sean's treatment of Lucas as well as his attraction to Aria, leads to their breakup. Afterwards, Sean seeks out Emily's help in pursuing Paige, unaware that Paige is a lesbian.\n* {{anchor|Caleb Rivers}}'''Caleb Rivers''' ([[Tyler Blackburn]]) (seasons 1\u20137, ''[[Ravenswood (TV series)|Ravenswood]]'') is a Rosewood's resident \"[[Bad boy (archetype)|bad boy]]\" who Hanna seeks out for help in hacking Emily's phone so that she can call Maya, her girlfriend at the time. Though initially annoyed and frustrated by Caleb, she becomes more sympathetic towards him when she discovers his poor home life as he is in foster care. The two eventually enter into a relationship. When she discovers that Caleb originally tried to get close to her while working for Jenna, she dumps him, feeling betrayed. He is brought back to Rosewood by Lucas, who wants Hanna and Caleb to make amends and reunite. After Caleb is contacted by his birth mother, he leaves Hanna to stay in California for a while. He returns in time for Tom's marriage to Isabel, accompanying Hanna to the wedding. Caleb then comes back after being in California and helps Hanna and her friends hack \"A\"'s phone without telling him whom the phone belongs to, but it backfires when \"A\" shuts the phone down. His surprise birthday party later gets ruined because Lucas has something to tell Hanna but Hanna takes it the wrong way and they both end up falling out the boat. The Liars (excluding Hanna) let Caleb continue to hack \"A's\" phone and, in order to get him to do it, they tell him about \"A\". The girls try to hide the truth from Hanna but when she finds out she is angry at them but reconciles with them a while later. Meanwhile, Caleb becomes obsessed with finding out who \"A\" is, which causes \"A\" to hack into Caleb's computer and plant secure school files, which lands him in trouble with the police. However, Hanna saves him by deleting the files. Caleb is the first person other than the Liars to help figure out who \"A\" is. Earlier, Lucas has some problems and starts to be a bad boy at school; when he is given a letter to give to his parents he drops it into a bin and sets it on fire. Hanna starts to worry about Lucas so she asks Caleb to talk to him. Later Caleb confronts Lucas and asks him why he nearly set fire to his girlfriend and why he is acting so strange; Lucas says sorry and walks off leaving Caleb wondering. In the third season, Hanna has trouble telling Caleb about what is going on in her life, causing him to break up with her. A couple episodes later it is revealed that they are back together in secret, unable to tell anyone. Caleb promises to help Hanna take down this new \"A\". In the summer finale, he accompanies the Liars to Ali's grave. Right after Emily's confrontation with Nate/Lyndon, he comforts Emily but is shot by the gun that Caleb put down beside the tower light assuming Nate was dead. He survives the gunshot. After some prodding, Hanna convinces him to meet with his actual father who was portraying himself as \"Uncle Jamie\". They hit it off and Hanna manages to get Caleb's father a job at the church so that he could be near his son. It is hinted that he (Caleb's father) stole money from the church as Hanna notices a bill in his wallet with the same red dice as the one she had donated earlier that day. When he returned the church's bell from repair, it turned out to be a much cheaper version. Hanna tells Caleb about this causing Caleb to break off his new relationship with his father, only for \"A\" to later reveal it was all a set-up. When Hanna's mom gets framed for Wilden's murder, Caleb teams up with Toby to search for other suspects. He then soon breaks up with Hanna when he's preparing to leave Rosewood to live in his new life in Ravenswood. He returns to Rosewood in season five.\n* {{anchor|Travis Hobbs}}'''Travis Hobbs''' ([[Luke Kleintank]]) (seasons 4\u20135) first appears giving Hanna money in order to help her mother. Hanna then finds out that Travis was a witness to the confrontation between Hanna's mother and Wilden that landed her mother in jail. Two develop a friendship. After Hanna and Caleb break up, Hanna kisses Travis.\n* {{anchor|Jordan Hobart}}'''Jordan Hobart''' (David Coussins) (season 6\u20137) is Hanna's fianc\u00e9 after the time jump. He is described as a sophisticated-yet-approachable 27-year-old working in the fashion industry.\n\n===Other===\n* {{anchor|Darren Wilden}}'''Darren Wilden''' ([[Bryce Johnson]]) (seasons 1\u20134, 6) was a detective investigating Alison's murder. He is attracted to Hanna's mom, Ashley, whom he once drove home after she had been drinking and asked for a ride, later sleeping with her to make up for not charging Hanna, who was caught shoplifting. He is distrustful of the girls, frequently questioning them beyond normal means, such as when he humiliates Emily by outing her to her friends. The detective returns in season 2 episode 12, when the girls are arrested. Officer Reynolds suggests there could be a raise in this for him, as he had his suspicions of the girls to start with. He reveals to them that he knew the murder weapon all along, and the girls had just been caught with it. He had strong feelings towards them all especially Hanna, and was determined that they would be thrown into jail. The girls are very grateful for Spencer's mom for getting them out of it and landing them with community service. When Ashley begins to worry that someone is still trying to get to her daughter, she goes to Darren for help, asking him if he had anything to do with Hanna's police report being released. Darren says that information could get him fired, and he didn't release the report. The Liars find a picture of Wilden, CeCe, and Alison on his boat in Cape May the Summer Ali died. They think Wilden is the father of Alison's alleged baby. Later, Wilden confronts Ashley and when he reaches for his gun, she hits him with her car and flees the scene. When she returns with Hanna, his body is missing. His car was later found in Hanna's garage and she takes it to the lake and dumps it. In the season 4 premiere, Wilden was killed and his body was found next to his car. Also, it was revealed that he is one of the people dressed as the Queen of Hearts in the Halloween episode \"This Is a Dark Ride\" along with Melissa Hastings. The town believed that Ashley was responsible for the murder, but in the season 4 finale, it was revealed that CeCe Drake was responsible for Wilden's murder. It has been revealed that Wilden helped cover up for CeCe the night she escaped Radley and hit Ali. He was also responsible for the murder of Garrett Reynolds.\n* {{anchor|Ted Wilson}}'''Ted Wilson''' ([[Edward Kerr]]) (seasons 3\u20135, 7) is a priest at the local church in Rosewood. He starts dating Hanna's mom, Ashley. In season 5, they are engaged. In season 7, Hanna and Spencer visits Ted to know if he knows Mary Drake, but he tells the girls that he has never met her. After the girls left, Mary comes out of hiding and asks Ted what the girls want; Ted tells her that he didn't say anything to the girls just like what Mary asked but then asks her why she came to see him. Ted later visits Hanna at Lucas's apartment and tells her that he was hiding Mary and apologizes to her for lying to her about knowing Mary. He reveals to Hanna that he and Mary had met when he was in college but broke up for unknown reasons and reveals to Hanna the real reason why Mary came to visit him; Ted reveals to Hanna that he is Charlotte's biological father and explains that he met her as Charles when he used to worked at the camp for troubled children fifteen years prior, but was unaware that Charles was his son and was also not aware that Charles would later transitioned into Charlotte. After Hanna sees the picture of Ted, Charles and an unknown boy at the camp, she asks him who the other boy is. He tells her that the other boy was Charles's only friend at the camp and tells her that the other boy's name is Lucas. Hanna realizes that the other boy in the picture is Lucas Gottesman.\n* {{anchor|Linda Tanner}}'''Linda Tanner''' ([[Roma Maffia]]) (seasons 4\u20136) is a lieutenant working with state investigator Gabriel Holbrook in Rosewood, Pennsylvania. Lieutenant Tanner is assigned to Darren Wilden's murder case.\n* {{anchor|Janet}}'''Janet''' (Janet Borrus) (season 1) is Caleb's foster mom who takes the money for taking care of Caleb while he lives elsewhere, surviving off his own money.\n\n==Acquaintances of Emily Fields==\nThe following characters are all family members and acquaintances of '''Emily Fields''', one of the protagonists of the series.\n\n===Family===\n* {{anchor|Pam Fields}}'''Pam Fields''' ([[Nia Peeples]]) (seasons 1\u20137) is Emily's mother. Strict and traditional, she expresses great anger and sadness when she learns that Emily is gay. Believing that Maya corrupted her daughter, she holds a grudge against her, eventually discovering [[marijuana]] in Maya's bag and having her sent away. Her relationship with Emily becomes extremely strained after this, but begins to heal when Pam stands up to Paige's father for being homophobic and accusing Emily of getting preferential treatment. For a short time, she moved to Texas to be with her husband, Wayne, eventually returning to Rosewood at the end of season two.\n* {{anchor|Wayne Fields}}'''Wayne Fields''' ([[Eric Steinberg]]) (seasons 1\u20134) is Emily's father and an officer in the military. At the start of the series, he was stationed in Afghanistan, and when he returned home, Emily came out to him. He struggled to accept Emily's homosexuality at first, but took a liking to Maya after she came over for dinner. After a few weeks of being in Rosewood, he was sent to [[Fort Hood, Texas]] to help train new recruits. When Emily was hospitalized after getting an ulcer, he came to visit her, apologizing for pressuring her into getting a swimming scholarship and explaining that he won't mind if Emily gives up on swimming, as long as she is healthy. Near the end of the second season, he is called back to active duty for another tour in Afghanistan. It is later revealed that during the five-year gap in season 6, that he was killed in combat.\n\n===Relationships===\n* {{anchor|Maya St. Germain}}'''Maya St. Germain''' ([[Bianca Lawson]]) (seasons 1\u20133) was Emily's first girlfriend and her first love. When Maya's family moves into the DiLaurentis' former house, the two quickly become friends, and their friendship gradually develops into romance. Though their relationship has a rocky start, Maya eventually helps Emily to come to terms with her sexuality. They are broken up by Pam, who discovers [[marijuana]] in Maya's bag and as a consequence, her family sent away to \"True North,\" a camp for juvenile delinquents. After returning to Rosewood, Maya and Emily attempted to rekindle their relationship, though their new relationship is shaky. Maya fears that her parents might send her back to \"True North\" after finding an ''old'' joint of hers. She is also afraid of being sent back in part due to her \"stalker\" (a boy she dated while at True North who had begun to harass her). Maya plans to run away to San Francisco to live with some friends and she attempts to convince Emily to join her, but to had no luck. When Maya goes missing and stops responding to Emily's calls, texts, and emails, Emily makes attempts to track her down, but is unsuccessful. At the end of the second season, it is revealed that a body had been found, and they think it's Maya's. Garrett is arrested for Alison's murder, and it is assumed he killed Maya too. In the third season, the Liars discover more about Maya's death with help from Mona, who tells them about Maya's video blog site. The Liars find out she was staying at Noel's cabin, and he hands over security camera footage of the night she disappeared. It shows Maya returning her bicycle and being grabbed by someone off-camera. The day is the same as the day Garrett was arrested, and it was after midnight meaning he did not kill her. Her cousin Nate comes to town, and befriends Emily. Later, he takes her away for a trip near a lighthouse and it is revealed that he was Maya's \"stalker-Ex-boyfriend\" from True North, and that his real name is Lyndon James. He attempts to kill Paige in revenge for taking Maya away from him, but Emily escapes to the top of the lighthouse leaving Paige behind. They have a brief struggle with Lyndon trying to stab her, but Emily grabs the knife and kills him in self-defense.\n* {{anchor|Paige McCullers}}'''Paige McCullers''' ([[Lindsey Shaw]]) (season 1\u20135, 7) is a former captain of the swim team and the star swimmer in Emily's absence. Jealous of Emily's perceived ease of accomplishments, she makes homophobic remarks towards Emily and physically threatens her. She later apologizes to Emily, stating that she can understand if Emily hates her, because she hates herself. Later, she also apologizes for her father, who causes problems for Emily at school, as he believes Emily is getting preferential treatment for being gay. She then kisses Emily, revealing herself to be gay. The two begin an on-again, off-again relationship, which suffers due to Paige's fear of being outed. Emily breaks up with Paige after Paige becomes jealous of Samara flirting with Emily. Near the end of the second season, Emily starts hanging out with Paige once more, who has finally come out to her parents. While trying to console Emily, who is upset about Maya's disappearance, Paige tries to kiss Emily, but is rejected. Paige later apologizes and agrees that it's best for the two of them to remain friends. In the third season, Paige and Emily find it hard to remain just friends. Paige confesses to Emily that Emily visited her one evening, and the two shared a drunken kiss. Emily realizes that she wants to move on from Maya's death and rekindles her romance with Paige. When the Liars later suspect Paige of being \"A\", Emily staunchly defends her, causing a rift between herself and the other Liars. However, once it revealed that Paige was being framed by \"A\" to look guilty, the Liars reconcile with Emily and accept Paige. At the beginning of season 4, both declare their love for the other reaffirming their commitment. Their relationship at the end of season 4 however appears to be over due to Paige telling the cops that Ali is alive and thus breaking Emily's trust in her. In season 5, Paige moves to California with her family, and asks Emily to come with her but she refuses. In season 7, Paige returns to Rosewood from California. McCullers becomes the swim coach for the Rosewood High swim team, after an injury tarnishes her chances at the Olympics. Emily and Paige rekindle their romance and Paige is there for Emily since she understands the threat of A.D. After discovering that Emily is going to help raise Alison's child Paige goes to meet Alison. They discuss their years of hatred for each other and their feelings for Emily, both come to a mutual feeling of respect. Paige later ends her relationship with Emily when she sees her true feelings for Alison and realizes that Emily will never love her more than she loves Alison. Paige and Emily tearfully end their relationship and Paige leaves Emily and Rosewood for good.\n* {{anchor|Samara Cook}}'''Samara Cook''' ([[Claire Holt]]) (seasons 1\u20132) is the president of a local private school's [[Gay-straight alliance|GSA]]. Upon meeting her, Emily is initially attracted to Samara because of the fact that she is out, unlike Paige, who Emily was secretly dating at the time. The two date for a short period of time, but Samara states that she does not want to be exclusive, causing Emily to doubt her feelings. After \"A\" blackmails Emily into giving Samara's friend her phone number, Samara thinks Emily is flirting and ends the relationship when Emily doesn't give her an honest answer.\n* {{anchor|Talia Sandoval}}'''Talia Sandoval-Mendoza''' ([[List of Pretty Little Liars characters#Cast|Miranda Rae Mayo]]) (season 5) is Ezra Fitz's new cook at The Brew. A professional chef, she and Emily initially get off on the wrong foot but eventually form a friendship. Soon, Emily begins receiving mixed signals from Talia, despite her previously commenting on Ezra's \"buns\". One night Emily and Talia are both working late and Talia reveals that she has feelings for Emily and only mentioned Ezra to find out Emily's sexual orientation. From then on she and Emily begin a relationship and all is well until Emily sees Talia's file, which lists her surname as Mendoza. Talia had previously introduced herself as Talia Sandoval. Curious, Emily asks Ezra about this and he informs her that Talia's maiden name was Sandoval and her married name is Mendoza. Emily confronts Talia about her marriage but she tells Emily that her husband, Eric, is aware that Talia is interested in woman and that they love each other but no longer in that way. In the following episode, a man comes into The Brew looking for Talia and is revealed to be her husband. He tells Emily that he is okay with Emily and Talia having an experimentation with each other because he knows that he will get to love her forever.\n* {{anchor|Sara Harvey}}'''[[Sara Harvey (character)|Sara Harvey]]''' (Dre Davis) (season 4, 6\u20137) is a young girl from Cortland who went missing around the same time as Alison did. Hanna theorized that Sara may have been the one buried in the place of Alison and contacted her friends to visit them. Nothing was heard about Sara after it was revealed that Bethany Young was the person in the grave, but in the sixth-season premiere, it is made known that Sara is alive and being held in \"A's\" dollhouse, forced to pretend to be Alison. Scared and confused, Sara is rescued by the police and taken to the hospital. Sara told Emily that she ran away from home the night she was taken and was hit over the head. Once she returns home, she runs away again and was living with Emily and her mother for a short period of time before returning home to Cortland to stay with one of her friends so she and Emily could have a real shot at a romantic relationship. Sara shows up at the Rosewood Prom and says that she felt its where she should be. She later travels with the Liars and Mona to the Carissimi Group building and helps the get into \"A's\" secret room, but waits outside the door on them. However, \"A\", who is revealed to be CeCe, reveals that Sara was actually Red Coat and the Black Widow, working alongside her. She was the person who got off the plane, meant to be a decoy, and rescued the Liars during the Thornhill Lodge Fire and went to Wilden's funeral to ensure his fate. The Liars see her, dressed as Red Coat, fixing a bomb inside Radley. Emily and the girls show up and confront her about it, disarming the bomb. Sara attempts to run but Emily grabs her and punches her. When Sara tries to get up she accidentally places her hand on an electrical box, severely damaging her hands. Sara is then diagnosed with Stockholm Syndrome after painting Charlotte in a bad image. Five years later, Sara returns to Rosewood after Charlotte is killed and reveals to Alison that she lied to the Judge and was actually very close with Charlotte, considering them to be like \"sisters\". Sara begins working with Jenna Marshall and they both keep resident at The Radley during their stays in Rosewood. When Noel Khan becomes involved Sara starts to regret her alliance with Jenna. After Sara attempts to warn Emily of the threat of Noel, he shows up to her room and murders Sara when she's in the shower.\n* {{anchor|Sabrina}}'''Sabrina''' (Lulu Brud) (season 6-7) is the manager of The Brew who has been known to dabble with marijuana, though its later revealed this was due to a previous cancer diagnosis. Sabrina and Emily develop a relationship but it is short lived due to Emily being unable to open up to Sabrina about A.D. Complications also grow when Paige returns to Rosewood and rekindles her relationship with Emily. Ezra later informs Emily that Sabrina quit her job at The Brew to move to Atlanta where she got an apprenticeship with an extremely successful baker.\n\n===Friends===\n* {{anchor|Sydney Driscoll}}'''Sydney Driscoll''' ([[Chloe Bridges]]) (season 5, 7) is a member on the Rosewood High Swim Team, having recently transferred schools. She admires Emily and her swimming talent and would like to adapt her style to suit that of Emily's. In the 100th episode, it is revealed that Sydney is in league with Jenna and Mona to take down Alison. When Emily finds out, she tells her that she knew Jenna from when she volunteered at the blind school that Jenna attended prior to season 1. After Mona's death, Sydney and Jenna join Alison, believing she killed Mona and fearing what she would do to them if they opposed her. Sydney returns in Season 7, after the five years forward, and is revealed to be a member of the A-Team. She reveals herself to Aria and claims to be \"A.D.\", the one in charge of the new team, but is discovered to be their helper instead.\n* {{anchor|Lyndon James|Nate St. Germain}}'''Lyndon James'''/'''Nate St. Germain''' (Sterling Sulieman) (season 3) was Maya's stalker. Having met Maya while the two of them were at True North, he was angered after Maya broke off their relationship, and proceeded to harass and stalk her once she returned home and rekindled her relationship with Emily. After Maya's death, while pretending he didn't know she died, he approaches Emily with the intent to befriend and then kill her, assuming the false identity of \"Nate\", Maya's supposed cousin. After being turned down romantically by Emily, Lyndon subsequently kidnaps Paige and tricks Emily into leaving Rosewood with him, planning on killing Paige in front of Emily as \"revenge\" for \"taking\" Maya from him. When Emily attempts to escape, the two get into a physical confrontation which culminates in Emily stabbing Lyndon in self-defense, fatally wounding him, and he dies.\n\n==Acquaintances of Alison DiLaurentis==\nThe following characters are all family members and acquaintances of '''Alison DiLaurentis''', one of the protagonists of the series.\n\n===Family===\n* {{anchor|Jessica DiLaurentis}}'''Jessica DiLaurentis (n\u00e9e Drake)''' (Anne Marie DeLuise, later [[Andrea Parker]]) (seasons 1\u20132, 4\u20137) is Alison, and Jason's mother and Charlotte's adoptive mother, who spearheaded a charity fashion show in Alison's memory. Jessica DiLaurentis had an affair with Peter Hastings which produced Jason. She returns in Season 4, and it is revealed that she was the one that buried Alison in order to protect the identity of the person who hit her with the rock. She is also thought to be one of Big \"A's\" minions, due to the fact that she is protecting them. In the season four finale, she is killed by an unknown person and buried by \"A\". In the season five finale, it is revealed that Mrs. DiLaurentis is actually the mother to Big \"A\", who is named Charles. In season six, it is revealed that Big \"A\" is CeCe Drake, who was born as Charles but allowed by Jessica to transition into Charlotte, despite Kenneth's disapproval. She lied to Kenneth, claiming that Charles died. In the finale, it is revealed that Jessica has a twin sister, named Mary Drake, who was actually Charlotte's biological mother. The DiLaurentis family adopted Charlotte. It is eventually revealed that Mary is the one who killed her.\n* {{anchor|Jason DiLaurentis}}'''Jason DiLaurentis''' (Parker Bagley, later [[Drew Van Acker]]) (seasons 1\u20137) is the half-brother of Alison, Spencer and Melissa. He had an interesting relationship with his late sister; though they often fought, they were both conniving and willing to keep each other's secrets. Jason attended Rosewood High and was friends with Ian and Garrett, who then later formed a club called \"N.A.T\" (initials from a Latin phrase which means \"We See All\"). He revealed to Spencer that Alison blamed the accident where Jenna was blinded on her, though Spencer believes Jason knows this to be a lie. After Ian's death, Jason returns to Rosewood, moving back into his old house and papering up the windows, apparently looking for something that Alison hid. He explains to Aria, whom he has romantic feelings for, that he can't remember what he was doing on the night of Alison's murder and that someone sent him a note afterward with \"I know what you did,\" written on them causing him to fear he might have killed Alison. We later find out that Spencer's father had had an affair with Jason's mother. When Spencer finds this out, she knows something's up, and she looks back on memories. When she remembers Ali telling her weird things on a night when her parents had been fighting about Jason and Melissa kissing, she figures out that Ali had subtly told her about Jason being her half-brother. When she approaches him he confirms her suspicions and they become closer and eventually he lends her $2,000.\n* {{anchor|Kenneth DiLaurentis}}'''Kenneth DiLaurentis''' (Jim Abele) (seasons 3, 5\u20136) is the biological father of Alison and Charlotte DiLaurentis and the legal father of Jason DiLaurentis. He left Rosewood after Alison's disappearance, but returned after Alison was found to be alive.\n* {{anchor|CeCe Drake|Charlotte Drake|Charlotte DiLaurentis}}'''[[CeCe Drake]]''' ([[Vanessa Ray]]) (seasons 3\u20137) is an ex-girlfriend of Jason DiLaurentis, who was also friends with Alison. They spent a summer vacation together in Cape May. It seems that CeCe taught Ali her scheming ways, as both act quite similarly. When CeCe returns to Rosewood in Season 3, the girls immediately notice the similarities between the way she acts and how Ali acted. CeCe also learned a lot about the other girls from Alison. She was with Alison and Detective Wilden in Cape May the summer Ali died. It is hinted that she may be scared of Wilden as he was seen in a heated argument with her before she skipped town. In Season 4, it is revealed CeCe was expelled from college, because apparently Alison pushed that girl down the stairs at the frat party shown in Season 1. CeCe believes the other girls were part of it too. In the episode before the fourth midseason finale, it is revealed she's on \"The A-Team\" and it is revealed she is [[Red Coat (Pretty Little Liars)|Red Coat]]. Aria kicks CeCe in the face, causing her Ali mask to come off. CeCe falls off the railing, and appears to be dead. However, her hand twitches, and her body disappears, meaning she survived the fall. She was taken into police custody where she admits to knowing who killed the girl in Ali's grave and tells them Ali is alive and that she can prove it. Later that night, she escapes and takes a police car. She heads to New York where she asks for Ali's help. It is revealed that Ezra was paying CeCe for information which is why she was in Ravenswood. Ali asked her to wear the Red Coat to distract \"A\" so she could turn off the saw. Alison gives CeCe her plane ticket and CeCe boards a plane to France, under the alias \"Vivian Darkbloom\". In \"Game Over, Charles\", it is revealed that CeCe is actually \"A\" and was born as Charles DiLaurentis. CeCe was admitted to Radley Sanitarium as a child, after a misinterpreted incident involving Alison as a baby. Their parents told Jason that she was imaginary. It is claimed that Charles committed suicide at age 16 so that CeCe could transition into Charlotte DiLaurentis. Mr. DiLaurentis was unaware of CeCe/Charlotte's existence and Charlotte eventually began dating Jason to get closer the family and became CeCe Drake. CeCe/Charlotte was given privileges to leave Radley to attend the University of Pennsylvania, and one night Bethany stole her clothes and escaped to hurt Mrs. DiLaurentis. CeCe stumbled upon Alison and hit her, believing it was Bethany. Later, CeCe made friends with Mona, who told her all about the \"A\" game and the Liars, and CeCe offered her a partnership and she helped CeCe escape, where she became \"A\". Sometime after this, CeCe hired Sara Harvey to become her accomplice by dressing up as Red Coat and The Black Widow. CeCe was also Red Coat, being the one to watch Mona dig up the grave, don the Emily mask and attend the Hoe Down. After declaring game over, Charlotte was admitted to a sanitarium for treatment. Once the Liars discover who she is, she ends the game. Five years later, Alison petitions the court to release Charlotte, asking the girls to testify in her favor. Charlotte is released and brought home to Alison. However, the next morning her body is found, seemingly having jumped from the bell tower, until the police discover that Charlotte was already dead upon \"being thrown\". In the season six finale, it is revealed that Charlotte was actually adopted and is the actual daughter of Mary Drake, Jessica's twin sister. She was revealed to be killed, in self-defense, by [[Mona Vanderwaal]] in season seven.\n* {{anchor|Mary Drake}}'''[[Mary Drake]]''' ([[Andrea Parker]]) (season 4, 6\u20137) is the twin sister of Jessica DiLaurentis and the birth mother of [[Charlotte DiLaurentis]]. She was a patient at Radley Sanitarium, where she gave birth to Charles Drake, but allowed her sister Jessica to adopt Charlotte as a child. Mary's whereabouts after that are unknown but she returns to Rosewood after her daughter's death, where she is working with Elliott Rollins to drive Alison insane and get Charlotte's money. Mary visits Alison in the hospital and pretends to be Jessica, to fool Alison into thinking she is dreaming. She comforts Alison and tells her that Elliott is a good man for her. However, in the next episode, she disguises herself as a deceased Jessica, while Elliott dresses up as Wilden, and together they scare Alison into committing herself into a mental hospital. Mary is also currently the owner of the Lost Woods Resort. It is revealed in season seven that Mary gave birth to a second child while at Radley. In the summer finale, it is revealed that child was Spencer. In the series finale, Mary joins forces with Uber A to kidnap Spencer, after Uber A forces her. Uber A is revealed to be Mary's daughter, Alex Drake, who is Spencer's twin sister.\n\n===Relationships===\n* {{anchor|Lorenzo Calderon}}'''Lorenzo Calderon''' ([[List of Pretty Little Liars characters#Recurring|Travis Winfrey]]) (season 6) is a police officer that works with Toby. He has shown a liking towards Alison and convinced her to be a coach for a soccer youth group for girls. Alison's dad does not approve of her and Lorenzo, so he takes back the binder Alison was going to use to coach the girls' soccer team.\n* {{anchor|Elliott Rollins|Archer Dunhill}}'''Archer Dunhill''', alias '''Elliott Rollins''' ([[List of Pretty Little Liars characters#Recurring|Huw Collins]]) (season 6\u2013present) is Charlotte's psychiatrist, and later, Alison's husband. Dr. Rollins knows the relationship with Ali is unusual, that's why he's always thinking of her wellness before taking a decision. In the season six finale, it is revealed that he is actually working with [[Mary Drake]] to drive Alison insane and take her half of the Carissimi Group funds. It is revealed in the seventh season that he is not actually Elliott Rollins. His real name is Archer Dunhill and he stole the real, deceased Elliott Rollins' identity. He begins torturing Alison inside Welby and takes her out one night as part of his plan. She manages to escape and while he is chasing her down, the Liars accidentally hit him with their car and kill him. After his death, it is revealed that he is also in league with [[Jenna Marshall]].\n\n===Friends===\n* {{anchor|Duncan Albert}}'''Duncan Albert''' ([[Lachlan Buchanan]]) (season 2) was a friend of Alison, when she was using the alias Vivian. When Aria meets him in Brookhaven he explains that he taught Vivian/Alison how to fly a plane, and that he might have loved her if Ian Thomas hadn't been in the way. He didn't know Alison was dead.\n* {{anchor|Shana Fring}}'''Shana Fring''' ([[Aeri\u00e9l Miranda]]) (seasons 3\u20135) is a clerk from the Rosewood Halloween Spooktacular Store. She made her first appearance in ''Pretty Dirty Secrets'', a series of mini webisodes. She was reintroduced when Hanna saw Paige talking to her in a lesbian bar. Paige admitted that she had a thing with Shana during the summertime and that she was trying to find information on who bought the Halloween costumes of the people who attacked them on the train from Shana. It was revealed that Shana was the mysterious person that Jenna Marshall was talking to in the finale of season 2 when she met up with her again in the finale of season 3. As of \"Close Encounters\", she reveals that she is helping Alison and they knew each other since they were kids. In \"EscApe From New York\", Shana is revealed to have been the \"A\" who shot Ezra on the rooftop and admits to setting the Lodge on fire. Her motive is that she wants justice for Jenna after Ali blinded her. She almost kills them until Aria intervenes and knocks her off the theater stage to her death. The Liars believed that she was \"A\" and believed the game to be over, until the real \"A\" returns. Shana's death affected Aria and Jenna majorly, with the former feeling guilt over killing her.\n* {{anchor|Cindy and Mindy|Cindy & Mindy}}'''Cindy and Mindy''' ([[Melanie Moreno|Melanie and]] [[Monica Moreno (actress)|Monica Moreno]]) (seasons 5\u20136) are twin sisters who attend Rosewood High. The two twins are recruited by Mona to join her army against Alison, as they were bullied by her in the past. When Alison returns to Rosewood, she greets Cindy and Mindy, while Emily and the Liars watch from a distance and Emily reveals that Ali used to call them \"Gayrons\" (standing for Gay Morons). After Alison and the Liars become enemies, the Liars ally with Mona. The five of them are in the bathroom discussing their plans when Cindy and Mindy enter. Mona greets them but they ignore her and enter the stalls. As soon as the Liars leave, the twins exit the stalls and exchange devious smiles with each other. It is revealed that they have joined forces with Ali. In \"How the 'A' Stole Christmas\", Ali gives the twins a makeover and they attend the Ice Ball with her, wearing matching (but different colored) dresses. They also dress up as CeCe and Ali, in order to trick the Liars into following them. Cindy and Mindy attend Ali's trial as well. When Ali is ruled as guilty for the murder, Cindy and Mindy stood up in shock, but then began to smile.\n\n==Other characters==\n* {{anchor|Jenna Marshall}}'''[[Jenna Marshall]]''' ([[Tammin Sursok]]) (seasons 1\u20135, 7) is Toby's younger stepsister. Jenna was accidentally blinded after Alison threw a firecracker into Toby's shed, intending to play a prank on him. At the time, Jenna had been in a physical relationship with Toby (it is later discovered that Jenna had forced Toby into the relationship, threatening to tell their parents he had forced himself on her if he did not). Jenna attended a school for the blind in Philadelphia before returning a year later when Alison's body is found. This leads to conflicts with the girls, who feel guilty about what they did to Jenna, and having let Alison pin the blame on Toby. Prior to Alison's death, she and Jenna had been rivals after Jenna turned down Alison's offer of friendship. Jenna was engaged in a power struggle with Alison before her death; after Jenna's accident, Alison visited her and blackmailed Jenna with the knowledge of her affair with Toby. Jenna claims to know \"exactly what kind of person [Alison] really was,\" hinting that she knows things about Alison that the girls did not. Jenna was a part of the N.A.T. club and later became romantically involved with Garrett Reynolds, as they both worked to \"take down\" the Liars. However, Jenna eventually breaks up with Garrett, and enters into a relationship with Noel Kahn. In the second season, Jenna undergoes surgery to fix her eyesight, and subsequently lies about the success of the surgery, leading everyone to believe she is still blind. The Liars discover that Jenna can see after Emily remembers being in Jenna's car, leading them to confront her. The Liars agree to keep her sight a secret; however, Jenna then reveals to everyone that she can \"now\" see. An accidental witness to Lyndon James' kidnapping of Maya, she leaves town after he discovers this. She returns in the Season 3 finale episode. It is then shown that she is in a relationship with Shana, to whom she reveals that her eyesight is getting worse and she will eventually lose her vision again. She is also linked to Melissa and Darren Wilden. In Season 4, it is revealed Melissa ordered Shana and Jenna to go to the lodge to spy on the Liars to see whom they were meeting, and that they didn't start the fire, Wilden did. At Wilden's funeral, she is shown wearing her sunglasses and holding hands with a man. It is revealed that man was a pilot named Nigel Wright, who flew Red Coat the night of the fire. He claims it was CeCe Drake. Later, he is seen making coffee for someone and says he's sorry and that he \"screwed up\". He also refers to this person as \"babe\", and she is revealed to be none other than Jenna, as we see Jenna's glasses and cane. Jenna was nearly drowned by \"A\"/Red Coat at Emily's birthday party. Shana seemed to believe it was CeCe and left town. Jenna returns in the 100th episode where she is revealed to be a part of Mona Vanderwaal's army and is friends with Sydney Driscoll. It is also revealed that Jenna truly cared for Shana. Sydney was volunteering at Jenna's blind school and when Jenna found out that Alison was returning she called Sydney for help. After Mona's supposed death Sydney and Jenna join Ali's army, believing that she was the one who killed Mona and fearing her. Jenna returns to Rosewood after Charlotte DiLaurentis' murder in 2017 and is now working for Uber A, as well working ''with'' Noel, Sydney, and Sara Harvey. It is also revealed that she was a part of the A-Team. She reveals that she was actually friends with Charlotte after her admission to Welby and was helping her track down Mary Drake. Jenna also knew Archer Dunhill and was working with him, as well. Jenna and Noel lure the Liars to a blind school to kill them, but their plan fails when Noel is killed and Jenna is knocked out by Mary Drake. Uber A rescues Jenna and takes her to an unknown lair, where she was assisting them in their final endgame. After the one year time jump, Jenna became a Life Skills Teacher at Rosewood High. She met with Alex Drake (who was pretending to be Spencer) and recognized her smell from when she was working for her. She called Toby and informed him that she didn't think Spencer was Spencer, leading them  to discover the truth about the twins.\n* {{anchor|Garrett Reynolds}}'''Garrett Reynolds''' ([[Yani Gellman]]) (seasons 1\u20133) is a police officer investigating the case of Alison DiLaurentis' death, who is initially assigned to trail Spencer, a suspect in Alison's death. Although he appears to be sympathetic towards the girls, in reality he is secretly dating and in an alliance with Jenna Marshall. He was a member of N.A.T along with Jason and Ian, whom he went to high school with. Garrett and Jenna broke up. Aria and Spencer see Garrett watching them after they talk to the guy who Alison owed money to prior to her murder. Garrett then gets arrested for Alison's murder in front of Melissa. Later in season 3, Garrett is willing to tell Spencer everything he knows and tells her he will leave town right after. As he begins to tell her, they get interrupted. Aria is then seen trapped in a box, next to Garrett's dead body.\n* {{anchor|Anne Sullivan}}'''Anne Sullivan''' ([[Annabeth Gish]]) (seasons 2\u20133, 6) is a therapist whom the girls are forced to see to deal with Alison's death. She is visited by A and attempts to reveal A's identity to the girls; A subsequently finds a way to keep her quiet. She returns once Mona (\"A\") has been caught and explains that Mona threatened the life of her son to get her to disappear. She then is the one to explain Mona's mental issues to the girls in the jail before Mona is put in a mental facility. She returns in season 3, relocating in Rosewood. She still helps the girls when they have problems, such as talking to Spencer when she was in Radley.\n* {{anchor|Barry Maple}}'''Barry Maple''' (Jim Titus) (seasons 1\u20137) is a local police officer who is good friends with the parents of Rosewood. In a deleted scene for \"Game Over, Charles\", it is revealed that Barry actually helped CeCe Drake/\"A\" escape the night she was detained in \"A Is for Answers\". Barry told CeCe to hit him hard and take the car. CeCe suspects that her mother, Jessica, gave Barry an offer \"he couldn't refuse\".\n* {{anchor|Arthur Hackett}}'''Arthur Hackett''' (John O'Brien) (seasons 3\u20135, 7) is the vice principal at Rosewood High. Hackett is reintroduced to the series in the seventh season. He elists Emily to work as a swimming coach.\n* {{anchor|Dianne Fitzgerald}}'''Dianne Fitzgerald''' ([[Mary Page Keller]]) (season 3, 7) is the mother of Ezra and Wesley Fitzgerald. She is a rich and ruthless woman. Due to her controlling attitude, she is estranged from Ezra. On Season 7, Dianne returns to Ezra's wedding with Aria.\n* {{anchor|Carla Grunwald}}'''Carla Grunwald''' ([[Meg Foster]]) (season 4, 5) is a psychic who lives in Ravenswood. First she denies knowing Alison, but later she admits that Alison had been calling her during the summer before she went missing. In season 5 Hanna asks her for help to search for Mona's body.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Novels|Television|United States}}\n* [[List of Pretty Little Liars episodes|List of ''Pretty Little Liars'' episodes]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Pretty Little Liars}}\n\n[[Category:Pretty Little Liars characters| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of American drama television series characters|Pretty Little Liars]]\n", "name_user": "Jamisonedd", "label": "safe", "comment": "Formatting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Pretty_Little_Liars_characters"}
{"title_page": "Omar Suleiman (imam)", "text_new": "{{Infobox religious biography\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Omar Suleiman\n| alt              = \n| image            = Imam Omar Suleiman.jpg\n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = 1986\n| birth_place      = [[New Orleans, Louisiana]], United States<ref name=Solis>{{cite web|last1=Solis|first1=Dianne|title=Irving imam, who has denounced extremism, threatened in ISIS videos|url=http://www.dallasnews.com/news/social-justice-1/2017/03/14/isis-videos-threaten-irving-imam|publisher=Dallas News|accessdate=18 March 2017|date=15 March 2017}}</ref>\n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place      = \n| religion         = [[Islam]\n| nationality      = [[Citizenship of the United States|American]]\n| other_names      = \n| alma_mater       = [[International Islamic University Malaysia]]\n| occupation       = [[Imam]], [[activist]], [[author]]\n| influences       = {{flatlist|\n* [[Malcolm X]]\n* [[Martin Luther King Jr.]]\n* [[Frederick Douglass]]\n }}\n| known_for        = [[Islamic Studies]], [[social justice]]\n| notable_works    = \n| website          = {{url|https://yaqeeninstitute.org}}\n}}\n'''Omar Suleiman''' (born 1986) is an [[American Muslim]] scholar, civil rights leader, writer, and public speaker. He is the Founder and President of Yaqeen Institute for Islamic Research, and an Adjunct Professor of [[Islamic Studies]] at [[Southern Methodist University]]. He is currently the Resident Scholar of the Valley Ranch Islamic Center and the Co-Chair Emeritus of Faith Forward Dallas at [[Thanks-Giving Square]], a multi-faith coalition of clergy for peace and justice.\n\nHis opinion pieces have appeared in ''[[CNN]]'', ''[[USA Today]]'', ''[[The Guardian]]'', ''[[HuffPost]]'', and ''[[The Dallas Morning News]]'' among other outlets.\n\n==Early life and education==\nSuleiman was born to a [[Palestinian people|Palestinian]] family in [[New Orleans]] in 1986.<ref name=Abdelaziz>{{cite web|last1=Abdelaziz|first1=Rowaida|title=Google Search Is Doing Irreparable Harm To Muslims|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/google-search-harming-muslims_us_59415359e4b0d31854867de8|website=[[The Huffington Post]]|accessdate=27 June 2017|date=24 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nHis studies of the Islamic tradition have taken Suleiman across the [[Muslim world]] to countries including [[Jordan]], the [[United Arab Emirates]], and [[Malaysia]]. In addition to receiving [[Ijazah|traditional certifications]] in the Islamic sciences, he received a Bachelor's in Islamic Law, Masters in Islamic Finance and Political History, and is currently completing a doctoral studies in Islamic Thought and Civilization from the [[International Islamic University of Malaysia]].\n\n==Career==\nUpon returning to [[New Orleans]], he served as the [[Imam]] of the Jefferson Muslim Association for 6 years, and as director of the \u201cMuslims for Humanity\u201d [[Hurricane Katrina]] relief effort in late 2005. It was at this time he received national recognition for his community service, interfaith, and social justice efforts. He would go on to co-founded the East Jefferson Interfaith Clergy Association and was awarded for outstanding civic achievement by the Mayor and City Council of New Orleans in 2010.<ref name=dmag>{{cite web|url= https://www.dmagazine.com/publications/d-magazine/2017/july/the-preacher-imam-omar-suleiman/ |title=The Preacher |website= www.dmagazine.com |accessdate=2018-05-26}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Suleiman founded the Muslim [[think-tank]], Yaqeen Institute for Islamic Research.<ref>{{cite document|format=PDF|url=https://1pjhft3ggnei4el40qfi16ch-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/AnnualReport_2017-2018.pdf |title=2017-2018 |website=Yaqeen Institute |accessdate=12 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://yaqeeninstitute.org/team/omar-suleiman |title=Sh. Omar Suleiman |website=Yaqeen Institute |accessdate=2017-03-02}}</ref> He is also the founding director of MUHSEN (Muslims Understanding and Helping Special Education Needs) - a [[non-profit]] umbrella organization that aims to create more inclusive Muslim communities that better cater to the [[disabled|disabilities]] and their families.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://muhsen.org/about/ |title=Founder of Muhsen |website= www.muhsen.org |accessdate=2018-05-26}}</ref>\n\nHe is ({{as of|lc=yes|May 2019}}) Professor of [[Islamic Studies]] at [[Southern Methodist University]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.smu.edu/simmons/Academics/LiberalStudies/MLS/Faculty-and-Students |title=Facult |website=smu.edu |accessdate=12 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe was ({{as of|lc=yes|August 2018}}) Resident Scholar of the Valley Ranch Islamic Center and Co-Chair of Faith Forward Dallas at [[Thanks-Giving Square]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.valleyranchmasjid.org/leadership/ |title=Leadership \u2013 Valley Ranch Islamic Center |website=Valleyranchmasjid.org |date=2014-06-20 |accessdate=2017-03-02|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180813045103/http://www.valleyranchmasjid.org/leadership/|archive-date=13 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thanksgiving.org/faith-forward-dallas/ |title=Faith Forward Dallas &#124; Thanks-Giving Square |website=Thanksgiving.org |accessdate=2017-03-02|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180830020713/http://www.thanksgiving.org/faith-forward-dallas/|archive-date=30 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nOmar Suleiman also starred in the award-winning ''Inspiration Series'' which aimed at imparting moral lessons from the life and example of the [[Prophet Muhammad]] through a drama mini-series. The series was widely viewed globally, and would go on to win the award for Best Movie at the 2016 International Contribution to [[Dawah]] Awards in [[Dubai]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.inspirationseries.org/ |website=Inspiration Series |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://dubaiprnetwork.com/pr.asp?pr=107292 |website=Dubai PR Network |accessdate=29 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Activism==\nSuleiman has engaged in [[social justice]] organizing and activism on a host of [[Progressivism in the United States|progressive causes]]. He states that [[Donald Trump]]'s presidency \"fatigues\" American citizens. He also \"considers [himself] a student of [[Malcolm X]]\" and believes that \"his most important contribution to the [[revolution]] is his idea that the greatest casualty of the subjugation of [[African Americans]] was the loss of black consciousness.\u201d He has expressed that \"America is a work in progress, and the most patriotic Americans are those that demand it live up to its promise.\" He also believes that \"[[Schools of Islamic theology|Muslim theology]] can be a source of liberation.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/jul/25/a-radical-form-of-white-supremacy-deserves-nothing-less-than-a-radical-response|title='A radical form of white supremacy deserves nothing less than a radical response'}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, he marched with demonstrators in Dallas against the killings of [[Shooting of Alton Sterling|Alton Sterling]] and [[Shooting of Philando Castile|Philando Castile]]. These demonstrations would eventually be punctuated by a [[2016 shooting of Dallas police officers|deadly shooting]] in which five police officers were killed in retaliation for [[Police brutality in the United States|police shootings]] of [[African Americans]]. Suleiman recalls \"an eternity of gunshots\" ringing out just as the march came to a close. In the wake of the shooting, Imam Omar Suleiman was invited to lead the invocation at a memorial service for the slain officers attended by President [[Barack Obama]] and former first lady [[Michelle Obama]], Vice President [[Joe Biden]] and his wife [[Jill Biden]], as well as President [[George W. Bush]] and former first lady [[Laura Bush]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pri.org/stories/2016-07-13/imam-louisiana-survived-dallas-shooting-here-are-his-thoughts-race-america |title=This imam from Louisiana survived the Dallas shooting. He doesn't think America can wait to deal with race. &#124; Public Radio International |website=Pri.org |date=2016-07-13 |accessdate=2017-03-02}}</ref>\n\nSince 2015, Suleiman has frequently visited [[Syrian refugee camps]] delivering aid with the Muslim humanitarian relief group, Helping Hand for Relief and Development.<ref>{{cite web|title=Perspective on Syrian Refugees: Imam Omar Suleiman|url=http://www.pbs.org/wnet/religionandethics/2017/02/10/perspective-syrian-refugees-imam-omar-suleiman/34396/|website=[[Religion & Ethics Newsweekly]]|publisher=[[PBS]]|accessdate=28 September 2017|date=10 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nSuleiman led [[Protests against Executive Order 13769|airport demonstrations]] in Dallas in reaction to the [[Trump travel ban]], which has since come to be known as the \u201cMuslim ban\" due to its restricting immigration from 7 predominantly Muslim-majority nations, as well as Trump's call for a temporary ban on Muslim entry into the United States following the [[2015 San Bernardino attack]], and again after the [[Orlando nightclub shooting]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/faith/2017/01/29/prayers-and-protests-as-dallas-faithful-react-to-trump-s-immigration-orders/ |website=The Dallas Morning News |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Omar Suleiman was arrested on [[Capitol Hill]] protesting outside of the office of then-[[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|House Speaker]] [[Paul Ryan|Congressman Paul Ryan]]. He had been participating in [[sit-in]] demonstration calling for [[Immigration reform in the United States|comprehensive immigration reform]]. He later led a group of [[clergy]] to the [[Mexico-United States border|U.S.-Mexico border]] to protest in solidarity with and meet migrants affected by [[Trump administration family separation policy|Trump's family separation policy]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/videos/us/2018/04/06/influential-muslims-imam-omar-suleiman-orig-mss.cnn |website=CNN |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe has also worked to assist families of victims of [[police brutality in the United States|police brutality]], voiced support for the [[Black Lives Matter]] movement, and underscored the importance of [[anti-racism]] work more broadly.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/omarsuleiman504/status/1169359973874327553 |website=Twitter |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.altmuslimah.com/2016/07/american-muslims-black-lives-matter-anti-racism-initiatives/ |website=Alt Muslimah |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/imamomarsuleiman/videos/1204746366212069/ |website=Facebook |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref> \n\nHe is also a proud and active supporter of the <nowiki>[[LGBT]]</nowiki> (lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender) rights movement.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=F2SUAqoMYJ0 |website=YouTube|accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOmar has also expressed support for the [[Muslim Brotherhood]] on his facebook page during the Egyptian revolt during Mubarak's presidency <ref>{{cite web |url=https://https://www.algemeiner.com/2017/07/31/best-friends-linda-sarsour-and-muslim-brotherhood-supporter-omar-suleiman/|website=Algemeiner |accessdate=31 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nOmar is a known passionate critic to governments of some muslim countries like [[KSA]] and has always show support for many other critics like [[Salman al-Ouda]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/omarsuleiman504/status/1037024436795437064?lang=en |website=Twitter |accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref> who has been jailed due to extremism and support for militant groups in Syria. \n\n<br />\n\n===Threat from ISIS===\nIn March 2017, [[ISIS]] called for his assassination, among a number of other prominent Western Muslim faith leaders, in a propaganda film titled \"Kill The Apostate Imams.\" The call was in response to a video Suleiman produced with Pastor Andrew Stoker of First United Methodist Church Dallas titled \"An Imam, a Pastor and a Dream,\u201d in which he calls for unity between [[Christians]] and Muslims in the United States and around the world. Suleiman responded to the threat stating, \"I believe that their venom needs to be condemned. They\u2019ve hijacked my religion.\"<ref name=Jeff>{{cite web|last1=Paul|first1=Jeff|title=ISIS Calls For North Texas Imam\u2019s Assassination|url=http://dfw.cbslocal.com/2017/03/13/isis-calls-for-north-texas-imams-assassination/|publisher=CBS DFW|accessdate=16 March 2017|date=13 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\nImam Omar Suleiman has been noted for his work in the fields of [[community service]], [[interfaith dialogue]], and [[social justice]], and was awarded for outstanding civic achievement by the Mayor and City Council of New Orleans in 2010.<ref name=dmag/>\n\nHe was featured as \u201crising star\u201d in ''Ozy Magazine'' and dubbed \"The Religious Leader Dallas Needs\" by the ''[[D Magazine]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ellin |first=Theo |url=http://www.ozy.com/rising-stars/the-man-trying-to-turn-mosques-into-places-of-sanctuary/75559 |title=The Man Trying to Turn Mosques Into Places of Sanctuary &#124; Rising Stars |publisher=OZY |date=2017-02-07 |accessdate=2017-03-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Macon |first=Alex |url=http://www.dmagazine.com/frontburner/2017/02/omar-suleiman-is-the-religious-leader-dallas-needs-right-now/ |title=Omar Suleiman is the Religious Leader Dallas Needs Right Now |publisher=D Magazine |date= |accessdate=2017-03-02}}</ref>\n\nSuleiman was also the subject of a ''[[BBC]]'' documentary in 2016 highlighting the experience of Muslims in Texas facing rising [[Islamophobia]], and a 2017 ''[[PBS]]'' documentary showcasing his work with [[Syrian refugees]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/proginfo/2016/21/united-states-of-hate |website=BBC |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/wnet/religionandethics/2017/02/10/perspective-syrian-refugees-imam-omar-suleiman/34396/ |website=PBS |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn May 9, 2019, Suleiman served as the congressional [[Chaplain of the United States House of Representatives|guest chaplain]] upon the invitation of [[Eddie Bernice Johnson|Rep. Eddie Bernice Johnson]] and delivered the day's opening [[invocation]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.congress.gov/116/crec/2019/05/09/CREC-2019-05-09-pt1-PgE566-3.pdf |website=Congress.gov |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to being recognized by ''[[CNN]]'' as one of 25 [[Muslim American]] change-makers, Suleiman was also included in ''[[The 500 Most Influential Muslims|The Muslim 500]]'' - an annual ranking of the world's most influential Muslims compiled by the [[Royal Islamic Strategic Studies Centre]] in [[Amman]], [[Jordan]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/interactive/2018/05/us/influential-muslims/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.themuslim500.com/profiles/omar-suleiman/ |website=CNN |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe also serves in an ethical advisory capacity within Muslim financial groups including the investment and wealth management firm, ShariaPortfolio, as well as A Continuous Charity - an organization aimed at promoting [[Islamic banking and finance|interest-free student loans]] for Muslims across North America.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.acceducate.org/our-team/ |website=A Continuous Charity |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://shariaportfolio.com/omar-suleiman-named-ethical-advisor/ |website=ShariaPortfolio |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn observation of [[Frederick Douglass]]' bicentennial, the Antiracist Research and Policy Center at [[American University]] and Frederick Douglass Family Initiatives recognized Omar Suleiman among 200 honorees whose work was deemed to best embody the legacy of the [[Abolitionism|abolitionist]]\u2019s commitment to social change.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/jul/25/a-radical-form-of-white-supremacy-deserves-nothing-less-than-a-radical-response |website=The Guardian |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n*''All-American : 45 American men on being Muslim'', 2012. <small>Contributed with the chapter \"Towards a compassionate and accepting orthodoxy\".</small>\n*''Prayers of the Pious'', 2019.\n*''Allah Loves...'', 2020.\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n*{{cite web|last1=Suleiman|first1=Omar|title=My Islam: Not Dogmatic Secularism Nor Religious Fanaticism|url=http://muslimmatters.org/2017/02/27/my-islam-not-dogmatic-secularism-nor-religious-fanaticism-sh-omar-sulieman/|publisher=Muslim Matters|date=27 February 2017}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Suleiman, Omar (imam)}}\n[[Category:21st-century Muslim scholars of Islam]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American Sunni Muslim scholars of Islam]]\n[[Category:American imams]]\n[[Category:People from New Orleans]]\n[[Category:American people of Palestinian descent]]\n[[Category:People in interfaith dialogue]]\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox religious biography\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Omar Suleiman\n| alt              = \n| image            = Imam Omar Suleiman.jpg\n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = 1986\n| birth_place      = [[New Orleans, Louisiana]], United States<ref name=Solis>{{cite web|last1=Solis|first1=Dianne|title=Irving imam, who has denounced extremism, threatened in ISIS videos|url=http://www.dallasnews.com/news/social-justice-1/2017/03/14/isis-videos-threaten-irving-imam|publisher=Dallas News|accessdate=18 March 2017|date=15 March 2017}}</ref>\n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place      = \n| religion         = [[Islam]]\n| denomination     = [[Sunni]]\n| nationality      = [[Citizenship of the United States|American]]\n| other_names      = \n| alma_mater       = [[International Islamic University Malaysia]]\n| occupation       = [[Imam]], [[activist]], [[author]]\n| influences       = {{flatlist|\n* [[Malcolm X]]\n* [[Martin Luther King Jr.]]\n* [[Frederick Douglass]]\n }}\n| known_for        = [[Islamic Studies]], [[social justice]]\n| notable_works    = \n| website          = {{url|https://yaqeeninstitute.org}}\n}}\n'''Omar Suleiman''' (born 1986) is an [[American Muslim]] scholar, civil rights leader, writer, and public speaker. He is the Founder and President of Yaqeen Institute for Islamic Research, and an Adjunct Professor of [[Islamic Studies]] at [[Southern Methodist University]]. He is currently the Resident Scholar of the Valley Ranch Islamic Center and the Co-Chair Emeritus of Faith Forward Dallas at [[Thanks-Giving Square]], a multi-faith coalition of clergy for peace and justice.\n\nHis opinion pieces have appeared in ''[[CNN]]'', ''[[USA Today]]'', ''[[The Guardian]]'', ''[[HuffPost]]'', and ''[[The Dallas Morning News]]'' among other outlets.\n\n==Early life and education==\nSuleiman was born to a [[Palestinian people|Palestinian]] family in [[New Orleans]] in 1986.<ref name=Abdelaziz>{{cite web|last1=Abdelaziz|first1=Rowaida|title=Google Search Is Doing Irreparable Harm To Muslims|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/google-search-harming-muslims_us_59415359e4b0d31854867de8|website=[[The Huffington Post]]|accessdate=27 June 2017|date=24 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nHis studies of the Islamic tradition have taken Suleiman across the [[Muslim world]] to countries including [[Jordan]], the [[United Arab Emirates]], and [[Malaysia]]. In addition to receiving [[Ijazah|traditional certifications]] in the Islamic sciences, he received a Bachelor's in Islamic Law, Masters in Islamic Finance and Political History, and is currently completing a doctoral studies in Islamic Thought and Civilization from the [[International Islamic University of Malaysia]].\n\n==Career==\nUpon returning to [[New Orleans]], he served as the [[Imam]] of the Jefferson Muslim Association for 6 years, and as director of the \u201cMuslims for Humanity\u201d [[Hurricane Katrina]] relief effort in late 2005. It was at this time he received national recognition for his community service, interfaith, and social justice efforts. He would go on to co-founded the East Jefferson Interfaith Clergy Association and was awarded for outstanding civic achievement by the Mayor and City Council of New Orleans in 2010.<ref name=dmag>{{cite web|url= https://www.dmagazine.com/publications/d-magazine/2017/july/the-preacher-imam-omar-suleiman/ |title=The Preacher |website= www.dmagazine.com |accessdate=2018-05-26}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Suleiman founded the Muslim [[think-tank]], Yaqeen Institute for Islamic Research.<ref>{{cite document|format=PDF|url=https://1pjhft3ggnei4el40qfi16ch-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/AnnualReport_2017-2018.pdf |title=2017-2018 |website=Yaqeen Institute |accessdate=12 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://yaqeeninstitute.org/team/omar-suleiman |title=Sh. Omar Suleiman |website=Yaqeen Institute |accessdate=2017-03-02}}</ref> He is also the founding director of MUHSEN (Muslims Understanding and Helping Special Education Needs) - a [[non-profit]] umbrella organization that aims to create more inclusive Muslim communities that better cater to the [[disabled|disabilities]] and their families.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://muhsen.org/about/ |title=Founder of Muhsen |website= www.muhsen.org |accessdate=2018-05-26}}</ref>\n\nHe is ({{as of|lc=yes|May 2019}}) Professor of [[Islamic Studies]] at [[Southern Methodist University]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.smu.edu/simmons/Academics/LiberalStudies/MLS/Faculty-and-Students |title=Facult |website=smu.edu |accessdate=12 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe was ({{as of|lc=yes|August 2018}}) Resident Scholar of the Valley Ranch Islamic Center and Co-Chair of Faith Forward Dallas at [[Thanks-Giving Square]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.valleyranchmasjid.org/leadership/ |title=Leadership \u2013 Valley Ranch Islamic Center |website=Valleyranchmasjid.org |date=2014-06-20 |accessdate=2017-03-02|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180813045103/http://www.valleyranchmasjid.org/leadership/|archive-date=13 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thanksgiving.org/faith-forward-dallas/ |title=Faith Forward Dallas &#124; Thanks-Giving Square |website=Thanksgiving.org |accessdate=2017-03-02|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180830020713/http://www.thanksgiving.org/faith-forward-dallas/|archive-date=30 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nOmar Suleiman also starred in the award-winning ''Inspiration Series'' which aimed at imparting moral lessons from the life and example of the [[Prophet Muhammad]] through a drama mini-series. The series was widely viewed globally, and would go on to win the award for Best Movie at the 2016 International Contribution to [[Dawah]] Awards in [[Dubai]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.inspirationseries.org/ |website=Inspiration Series |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://dubaiprnetwork.com/pr.asp?pr=107292 |website=Dubai PR Network |accessdate=29 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Activism==\nSuleiman has engaged in [[social justice]] organizing and activism on a host of [[Progressivism in the United States|progressive causes]]. He states that [[Donald Trump]]'s presidency \"fatigues\" American citizens. He also \"considers [himself] a student of [[Malcolm X]]\" and believes that \"his most important contribution to the [[revolution]] is his idea that the greatest casualty of the subjugation of [[African Americans]] was the loss of black consciousness.\u201d He has expressed that \"America is a work in progress, and the most patriotic Americans are those that demand it live up to its promise.\" He also believes that \"[[Schools of Islamic theology|Muslim theology]] can be a source of liberation.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/jul/25/a-radical-form-of-white-supremacy-deserves-nothing-less-than-a-radical-response|title='A radical form of white supremacy deserves nothing less than a radical response'}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, he marched with demonstrators in Dallas against the killings of [[Shooting of Alton Sterling|Alton Sterling]] and [[Shooting of Philando Castile|Philando Castile]]. These demonstrations would eventually be punctuated by a [[2016 shooting of Dallas police officers|deadly shooting]] in which five police officers were killed in retaliation for [[Police brutality in the United States|police shootings]] of [[African Americans]]. Suleiman recalls \"an eternity of gunshots\" ringing out just as the march came to a close. In the wake of the shooting, Imam Omar Suleiman was invited to lead the invocation at a memorial service for the slain officers attended by President [[Barack Obama]] and former first lady [[Michelle Obama]], Vice President [[Joe Biden]] and his wife [[Jill Biden]], as well as President [[George W. Bush]] and former first lady [[Laura Bush]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pri.org/stories/2016-07-13/imam-louisiana-survived-dallas-shooting-here-are-his-thoughts-race-america |title=This imam from Louisiana survived the Dallas shooting. He doesn't think America can wait to deal with race. &#124; Public Radio International |website=Pri.org |date=2016-07-13 |accessdate=2017-03-02}}</ref>\n\nSince 2015, Suleiman has frequently visited [[Syrian refugee camps]] delivering aid with the Muslim humanitarian relief group, Helping Hand for Relief and Development.<ref>{{cite web|title=Perspective on Syrian Refugees: Imam Omar Suleiman|url=http://www.pbs.org/wnet/religionandethics/2017/02/10/perspective-syrian-refugees-imam-omar-suleiman/34396/|website=[[Religion & Ethics Newsweekly]]|publisher=[[PBS]]|accessdate=28 September 2017|date=10 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nSuleiman led [[Protests against Executive Order 13769|airport demonstrations]] in Dallas in reaction to the [[Trump travel ban]], which has since come to be known as the \u201cMuslim ban\" due to its restricting immigration from 7 predominantly Muslim-majority nations, as well as Trump's call for a temporary ban on Muslim entry into the United States following the [[2015 San Bernardino attack]], and again after the [[Orlando nightclub shooting]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/faith/2017/01/29/prayers-and-protests-as-dallas-faithful-react-to-trump-s-immigration-orders/ |website=The Dallas Morning News |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Omar Suleiman was arrested on [[Capitol Hill]] protesting outside of the office of then-[[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|House Speaker]] [[Paul Ryan|Congressman Paul Ryan]]. He had been participating in [[sit-in]] demonstration calling for [[Immigration reform in the United States|comprehensive immigration reform]]. He later led a group of [[clergy]] to the [[Mexico-United States border|U.S.-Mexico border]] to protest in solidarity with and meet migrants affected by [[Trump administration family separation policy|Trump's family separation policy]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/videos/us/2018/04/06/influential-muslims-imam-omar-suleiman-orig-mss.cnn |website=CNN |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe has also worked to assist families of victims of [[police brutality in the United States|police brutality]], voiced support for the [[Black Lives Matter]] movement, and underscored the importance of [[anti-racism]] work more broadly.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/omarsuleiman504/status/1169359973874327553 |website=Twitter |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.altmuslimah.com/2016/07/american-muslims-black-lives-matter-anti-racism-initiatives/ |website=Alt Muslimah |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/imamomarsuleiman/videos/1204746366212069/ |website=Facebook |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Threat from ISIS===\nIn March 2017, [[ISIS]] called for his assassination, among a number of other prominent Western Muslim faith leaders, in a propaganda film titled \"Kill The Apostate Imams.\" The call was in response to a video Suleiman produced with Pastor Andrew Stoker of First United Methodist Church Dallas titled \"An Imam, a Pastor and a Dream,\u201d in which he calls for unity between [[Christians]] and Muslims in the United States and around the world. Suleiman responded to the threat stating, \"I believe that their venom needs to be condemned. They\u2019ve hijacked my religion.\"<ref name=Jeff>{{cite web|last1=Paul|first1=Jeff|title=ISIS Calls For North Texas Imam\u2019s Assassination|url=http://dfw.cbslocal.com/2017/03/13/isis-calls-for-north-texas-imams-assassination/|publisher=CBS DFW|accessdate=16 March 2017|date=13 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\nImam Omar Suleiman has been noted for his work in the fields of [[community service]], [[interfaith dialogue]], and [[social justice]], and was awarded for outstanding civic achievement by the Mayor and City Council of New Orleans in 2010.<ref name=dmag/>\n\nHe was featured as \u201crising star\u201d in ''Ozy Magazine'' and dubbed \"The Religious Leader Dallas Needs\" by the ''[[D Magazine]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ellin |first=Theo |url=http://www.ozy.com/rising-stars/the-man-trying-to-turn-mosques-into-places-of-sanctuary/75559 |title=The Man Trying to Turn Mosques Into Places of Sanctuary &#124; Rising Stars |publisher=OZY |date=2017-02-07 |accessdate=2017-03-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Macon |first=Alex |url=http://www.dmagazine.com/frontburner/2017/02/omar-suleiman-is-the-religious-leader-dallas-needs-right-now/ |title=Omar Suleiman is the Religious Leader Dallas Needs Right Now |publisher=D Magazine |date= |accessdate=2017-03-02}}</ref>\n\nSuleiman was also the subject of a ''[[BBC]]'' documentary in 2016 highlighting the experience of Muslims in Texas facing rising [[Islamophobia]], and a 2017 ''[[PBS]]'' documentary showcasing his work with [[Syrian refugees]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/proginfo/2016/21/united-states-of-hate |website=BBC |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/wnet/religionandethics/2017/02/10/perspective-syrian-refugees-imam-omar-suleiman/34396/ |website=PBS |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn May 9, 2019, Suleiman served as the congressional [[Chaplain of the United States House of Representatives|guest chaplain]] upon the invitation of [[Eddie Bernice Johnson|Rep. Eddie Bernice Johnson]] and delivered the day's opening [[invocation]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.congress.gov/116/crec/2019/05/09/CREC-2019-05-09-pt1-PgE566-3.pdf |website=Congress.gov |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to being recognized by ''[[CNN]]'' as one of 25 [[Muslim American]] change-makers, Suleiman was also included in ''[[The 500 Most Influential Muslims|The Muslim 500]]'' - an annual ranking of the world's most influential Muslims compiled by the [[Royal Islamic Strategic Studies Centre]] in [[Amman]], [[Jordan]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/interactive/2018/05/us/influential-muslims/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.themuslim500.com/profiles/omar-suleiman/ |website=CNN |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe also serves in an ethical advisory capacity within Muslim financial groups including the investment and wealth management firm, ShariaPortfolio, as well as A Continuous Charity - an organization aimed at promoting [[Islamic banking and finance|interest-free student loans]] for Muslims across North America.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.acceducate.org/our-team/ |website=A Continuous Charity |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://shariaportfolio.com/omar-suleiman-named-ethical-advisor/ |website=ShariaPortfolio |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn observation of [[Frederick Douglass]]' bicentennial, the Antiracist Research and Policy Center at [[American University]] and Frederick Douglass Family Initiatives recognized Omar Suleiman among 200 honorees whose work was deemed to best embody the legacy of the [[Abolitionism|abolitionist]]\u2019s commitment to social change.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/jul/25/a-radical-form-of-white-supremacy-deserves-nothing-less-than-a-radical-response |website=The Guardian |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n*''All-American : 45 American men on being Muslim'', 2012. <small>Contributed with the chapter \"Towards a compassionate and accepting orthodoxy\".</small>\n*''Prayers of the Pious'', 2019.\n*''Allah Loves...'', 2020.\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n*{{cite web|last1=Suleiman|first1=Omar|title=My Islam: Not Dogmatic Secularism Nor Religious Fanaticism|url=http://muslimmatters.org/2017/02/27/my-islam-not-dogmatic-secularism-nor-religious-fanaticism-sh-omar-sulieman/|publisher=Muslim Matters|date=27 February 2017}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Suleiman, Omar (imam)}}\n[[Category:21st-century Muslim scholars of Islam]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American Sunni Muslim scholars of Islam]]\n[[Category:American imams]]\n[[Category:People from New Orleans]]\n[[Category:American people of Palestinian descent]]\n[[Category:People in interfaith dialogue]]\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n", "name_user": "Zia1415", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Removed an unimportant label)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Omar_Suleiman_(imam)"}
{"title_page": "Brendan Eich", "text_new": "{{short description|American computer programmer and technologist}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Brendan Eich\n|image       = Brendan Eich Mozilla Foundation official photo.jpg\n|caption     = Brendan Eich, official Mozilla Foundation photograph, August 21, 2012\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1961|07|04}}\n|birth_place = [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| residence = San Francisco Bay Area\n|other_names = \n|alma_mater  = [[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign]]<br/>[[Santa Clara University]]\n|known_for   = [[JavaScript]]\n|website     = {{URL|https://brendaneich.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Brendan Eich''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|a\u026a|k}}; born July 4, 1961)<ref name=\"NYT_1997_09_09\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/09/09/business/part-artist-part-hacker-and-full-time-programmer.html|title=Part Artist, Part Hacker And Full-Time Programmer|last=Lohr|first=Steve|date=1996-09-09|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-06-29|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref> is an American technologist and creator of the [[JavaScript]] [[programming language]]. He co-founded the [[Mozilla]] project,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Business/mozilla-ceo-resigns-calif-gay-marriage-ban-campaign/story?id=23181711|title=Mozilla CEO Resigns After Calif. Gay Marriage Ban Campaign Donation - ABC News|author=ABC News|work=ABC News}}</ref> the [[Mozilla Foundation]] and the [[Mozilla Corporation]], and served as the Mozilla Corporation's [[chief technical officer]] and briefly, as its [[chief executive officer]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Swisher|first=Kara|title=Mozilla Co-Founder Brendan Eich Resigns as CEO, Leaves Foundation Board|url=http://recode.net/2014/04/03/mozilla-co-founder-brendan-eich-resigns-as-ceo-and-also-from-foundation-board|publisher=Recode|accessdate=April 3, 2014}}</ref> He is the CEO of [[Brave (web browser)|Brave Software]].<ref name=\"cnet.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cnet.com/au/news/mystery-startup-from-ex-mozilla-ceo-aims-to-go-where-tech-titans-wont/|title=Mystery startup from ex-Mozilla CEO aims to go where tech titans won't|date=17 November 2015|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=CNET}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBrendan Eich grew up in Pittsburgh; Gaithersburg, Maryland; and [[Palo Alto]],<ref name=\"NYT_1997_09_09\" /> and he attended [[Ellwood P. Cubberley High School]], graduating in the class of 1979. Eich received his [[bachelor's degree]] in mathematics and computer science at [[Santa Clara University]].<ref name=\"NYT_1997_09_09\"/> He received his [[master's degree]] in 1985 from the [[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign]].<ref name=\"NYT_1997_09_09\" />\n\nEich started his career at [[Silicon Graphics]], working for seven years on [[operating system]] and network code.<ref name=\"aboutcom\">{{Citation|contribution-url=http://inventors.about.com/library/inventors/bl_javascript.htm|contribution=Brendan Eich and JavaScript|title=Inventors|publisher=About}}.</ref> He then worked for three years at [[MicroUnity|MicroUnity Systems Engineering]] writing [[kernel (computer science)|microkernel]] and [[digital signal processor|DSP]] code, and doing the first [[MIPS architecture|MIPS]] [[R4000]] port of [[GNU Compiler Collection|GCC]].<ref name=\"aboutcom\"/>\n\n==Netscape and JavaScript==\nHe started work at [[Netscape Communications Corporation]] in April 1995. Eich originally joined intending to put [[Scheme (programming language)|Scheme]] \"in the browser\",<ref name=\"Saternos2014\">{{cite book|last=Saternos|first=Casimir|title=Client-Server Web Apps with JavaScript and Java|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3b40AwAAQBAJ&pg=PT32|accessdate=4 April 2014|date=2014-03-28|publisher=O'Reilly Media|isbn=9781449369293|pages=32\u2013}}</ref> but his Netscape superiors insisted that the language\u2019s syntax resemble that of [[Java (programming language)|Java]]. The result was a language that had much of the functionality of Scheme, the object orientation of [[Self (programming language)|Self]], and the syntax of Java. The first version was completed in ten days in order to accommodate the Navigator 2.0 Beta release schedule,<ref name=Saternos2014/><ref name=\"Severance\">{{cite news|url=http://www.computer.org/csdl/mags/co/2012/02/mco2012020007.pdf|title=JavaScript: Designing a Language in 10 Days|last=Severance|first=Charles|date=February 2012|work=[[Computer (magazine)|Computer]]|accessdate=April 4, 2014}}</ref> and was called Mocha, but renamed LiveScript in September 1995 and later JavaScript in December.<ref name=\"quirks\">{{cite web|url=http://www.quirksmode.org/js/intro.html|title=JavaScript: General introduction|accessdate= 2011-02-12}}</ref> Eich continued to oversee the development of [[SpiderMonkey (JavaScript engine)|SpiderMonkey]], the specific implementation of JavaScript in Navigator.<ref name=BE201106>{{cite web|url=http://brendaneich.com/2011/06/new-javascript-engine-module-owner|title=New JavaScript Engine Module Owner|date=June 21, 2011|first=Brendan|last=Eich|publisher=BrendanEich.com}}</ref>\n\n==Mozilla==\nIn early 1998, Eich co-founded the [[Mozilla]] project with [[Jamie Zawinski]] and others, creating the mozilla.org website, which was meant to manage open-source contributions to the Netscape source code. He served as Mozilla's chief [[Systems architect|architect]].<ref name=\"Seibel2009\">{{cite book|last=Seibel|first=Peter|title=Coders at Work: Reflections on the Craft of Programming|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nneBa6-mWfgC&pg=PA132|accessdate=4 April 2014|date=2009-09-16|publisher=Apress|isbn=9781430219484|pages=132\u2013}}</ref> [[America Online|AOL]] bought Netscape in 1999. After AOL shut down the Netscape browser unit in July 2003, Eich helped spin out the [[Mozilla Foundation]].<ref name=\"mozilla-press-2005-08-03\"/>\n\nIn August 2005, after serving as lead technologist and as a member of the board of directors of the Mozilla Foundation, Eich became [[chief technical officer]] of the newly founded [[Mozilla Corporation]], meant to be the Mozilla Foundation's for-profit arm.<ref name=\"mozilla-press-2005-08-03\">{{cite web|url=https://www-archive.mozilla.org/press/mozilla-2005-08-03.html|title=Mozilla Foundation Forms New Organization to Further the Creation of Free, Open Source Internet Software, Including the Award-Winning Mozilla Firefox Browser|date=2005-08-03|publisher=[[Mozilla Foundation]]|quote= Brendan Eich, a co-founder and long-time technical leader of the Mozilla project, will become the chief technical officer of the Mozilla Corporation.|accessdate=2011-02-12}}</ref> Eich continued to \"own\" the Mozilla SpiderMonkey module, its JavaScript engine, until he passed on the ownership of it in 2011.<ref name=BE201106/>\n\nOn March 24, 2014, Eich was promoted to CEO of Mozilla Corporation.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Mozilla|title=Leadership Changes|date=March 24, 2014|url=https://blog.mozilla.org/blog/2014/03/24/mozilla-leadership-changes|type=blog|accessdate=March 24, 2014}}</ref> [[Gary Kovacs]], [[John Lilly (computer scientist)|John Lilly]], and [[Ellen Siminoff]] resigned from the Mozilla board prior to the appointment,<ref name=wsj>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/digits/2014/03/28/three-mozilla-board-members-resign-over-choice-of-new-ceo/|title=Three Mozilla Board Members Resign over Choice of New CEO|author=Alistair Barr|work=WSJ}}</ref> some anonymously expressing disagreements with Eich's strategy and their desire for a CEO with experience in the mobile industry.<ref>\"On mobile devices, however, Firefox ranks 13th, with less than 0.1% share, according to Net Applications\" Note Net Applications rated Firefox on mobile at [https://web.archive.org/web/20131112112801/http://marketshare.hitslink.com/browser-market-share.aspx?qprid=0&qpcustomd=1 0.01% in Nov 2013] and [https://web.archive.org/web/20140715042405/http://marketshare.hitslink.com/browser-market-share.aspx?qprid=0&qpcustomd=1 0.68% in Jul 2014]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/business/2014/03/three-mozilla-board-members-including-two-former-ceos-step-down/|title=Three Mozilla board members\u2014including former CEOs\u2014step down [Updated]|last=Machkovech|first=Sam|date=March 28, 2014|work=Ars Technica}}</ref>\n\nSome employees of Mozilla Foundation (a separate organization from Mozilla Corporation) tweeted calls for his resignation, with reference to his donation of $1,000 to [[California Proposition 8 (2008)|California Proposition 8]], which called for the banning of [[same-sex marriage in California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.mozilla.org/blog/2014/04/03/brendan-eich-steps-down-as-mozilla-ceo|title=Brendan Eich Steps Down as Mozilla CEO|last=Baker|first=Mitchell|date=April 3, 2014|publisher=The Mozilla Blog}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.mozilla.org/blog/2014/04/05/faq-on-ceo-resignation|title=FAQ on CEO Resignation|publisher=Mozilla|date=April 5, 2014|accessdate=April 6, 2014}}</ref> This donation had first made international news in 2012.<ref name=pinknews>https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2012/04/04/javascript-inventor-gave-1000-to-support-californias-gay-marriage-ban/</ref> Eich stood by his decision to fund the campaign, but wrote on his blog that he was sorry for \"causing pain\" and pledged to promote equality at Mozilla.<ref name=wsj/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://brendaneich.com/2014/03/inclusiveness-at-mozilla/|title=Brendan Eich|work=brendaneich.com}}</ref> Some of the activists created an online campaign{{cn|date=December 2019}} against Eich, with online dating site [[OkCupid]] automatically displaying a message to Firefox users with information about Eich's donation, and suggesting that users switch to a different browser (although giving them a link to continue with Firefox).<ref name=\"latimes-donation\">{{cite news|first=Deborah|last=Netburn|title=Brendan Eich's Prop. 8 contribution gets Twittersphere buzzing|publisher=[[LA Times]]|date=2012-04-04|url=http://www.latimes.com/business/technology/la-fi-tn-brendan-eich-prop-8-contribution-20120404,0,6341761.story|accessdate=2012-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url = https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/online-dating-site-okcupid-calls-for-firefox-boycott-to-protest-at-antigay-marriage-boss-9226904.html|title = OkCupid calls for Firefox boycott to protest anti-gay marriage CEO Brendan Eich|last = Johnston|first = Ian|date = April 1, 2014|work = Independent|accessdate = June 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.advocate.com/business/technology/2014/03/26/mozilla-ceo-responds-antigay-allegations|title = OkCupid calls for Firefox boycott to protest anti-gay marriage CEO Brendan Eich|last=Byrdum|first=Sunnivie|date = March 26, 2014|work = The Advocate|accessdate = }}</ref> Others at the Mozilla Corporation spoke out on their blogs in his favor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/business/2014/03/mozilla-employees-to-brendan-eich-step-down|title=Mozilla employees tell Brendan Eich he needs to \"step down\"|work=Ars Technica|date=March 27, 2014|accessdate=March 28, 2014|first=Sam|last=Machkovech}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://subfictional.com/2014/03/24/on-brendan-eich-as-ceo-of-mozilla|title=On Brendan Eich as CEO of Mozilla|work=Subfictional Studios|date=March 24, 2014|accessdate=April 7, 2014|first=Christie|last=Koehler}}</ref> Board members wanted him to stay in the company in a different role.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url = https://www.theregister.co.uk/Print/2014/04/08/mozilla_anti_gay_marriage_boycott/|title = Gay marriage foes outraged at Mozilla CEO flap, call for boycott|last = McAllister|first = Neil|date = April 8, 2014|work = The Register|accessdate = June 5, 2014}}</ref> On April 3, 2014, Eich resigned as CEO and left Mozilla; in his personal blog, he posted, \"under the present circumstances, I cannot be an effective leader\".<ref name=Kim1>{{cite news|last=Kim|first=Susana|title=Mozilla CEO Brendan Eich Resigns After Protests from Gay Marriage Supporters|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Business/mozilla-ceo-resigns-calif-gay-marriage-ban-campaign/story?id=23181711|accessdate=April 3, 2014|newspaper=ABC News|date=April 3, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"eichblog\">{{Cite web|title=Brendan Eich steps down as Mozilla CEO|date=April 3, 2014|url=https://blog.mozilla.org/blog/2014/04/03/brendan-eich-steps-down-as-mozilla-ceo|publisher=blog.mozilla.org|accessdate=April 8, 2014}}</ref> The resignation also made international news, and was viewed as due to Eich's opposition to same-sex marriage.<ref name=standard>https://www.standard.co.uk/news/techandgadgets/mozilla-boss-brendan-eich-quits-in-row-over-his-opposition-to-gay-marriage-9237701.html</ref><ref name=bbc>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-26868536</ref><ref name=reuters>https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mozilla-ceo-resignation/mozilla-ceo-resigns-opposition-to-gay-marriage-drew-fire-idUSBREA321Y320140403</ref>\n\nWhile some media reports have pegged Eich's resignation directly to controversies surrounding his donation to supporters of Proposition 8,<ref name=Kim1/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Lee |first1=Dave |title=Mozilla boss Brendan Eich resigns after gay marriage storm |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-26868536 |accessdate=December 28, 2019 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=April 4, 2014}}</ref> others who worked at Mozilla Corporation at the time said there were other factors surrounding Eich's departure.<ref name=\"CNETEichResign\">{{cite news |last1=Shankland |first1=Stephen |title=Mozilla under fire: Inside the 9-day reign of fallen CEO Brendan Eich |url=https://www.cnet.com/g00/news/mozilla-under-fire-inside-the-9-day-reign-of-fallen-ceo-brendan-eich/?i10c.ua=4&i10c.encReferrer=aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29vZ2xlLmNvbS8%3d&i10c.dv=15 |accessdate=December 28, 2019 |work=[[CNET]] |date=June 13, 2014}}</ref>  They say Eich faced doubts over his leadership and managerial ability from board members during the CEO selection process, with some saying he is better suited in a science role within the organization.<ref name=\"CNETEichResign\"/> They also asserted that Eich failed to defuse the donation controversy when it surfaced, which further inflamed the situation.<ref name=\"CNETEichResign\"/>\n\n==Brave Software==\nEich is the CEO of Brave Software, an Internet browser platform company that raised $2.5 million in early funding from [[angel investor]]s.<ref name=\"cnet.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/prnewswire/press_releases/2015/11/17/SF59778|title=Brave Software Raises $2.5 Million And Expands Technical Team|work=The Business Journals}}</ref> On January 20, 2016, the company released developer versions of its open-source [[Brave (web browser)|Brave web browser]], which blocks ads and trackers, and includes a [[micropayment]]s system to offer users a choice between viewing selected ads or paying websites not to display them.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brave.com/blogpost_1.html|title=Building a Better Web|website=Brave Software|accessdate=29 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nAt Brave Software, Eich co-created the Basic Attention Token (BAT), a cryptocurrency designed for use in the Brave browser. BAT launched its [[Initial coin offering|ICO]] on May 31, 2017 and raised $35 million.<ref>https://techcrunch.com/2017/06/01/brave-ico-35-million-30-seconds-brendan-eich/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Brendan Eich}}\n*{{official}}\n\n{{Netscape}}\n{{Mozilla}}\n{{ECMAScript}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Gary Kovacs]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=CEO of [[Mozilla Corporation]]\n|years=24 March 2014 \u2013 3 April 2014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Chris Beard (executive)|Chris Beard]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eich, Brendan}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:American chief technology officers]]\n[[Category:American computer programmers]]\n[[Category:2008 California Proposition 8]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mozilla developers]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Pittsburgh]]\n[[Category:Silicon Graphics people]]\n[[Category:Santa Clara University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign alumni]]\n[[Category:Netscape people]]\n[[Category:Computer programmers]]\n[[Category:Web developers]]\n[[Category:American technology chief executives]]\n[[Category:People associated with JavaScript]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American computer programmer and technologist}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Brendan Eich\n|image       = Brendan Eich Mozilla Foundation official photo.jpg\n|caption     = Brendan Eich, official Mozilla Foundation photograph, August 21, 2012\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1961|07|04}}\n|birth_place = [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| residence = San Francisco Bay Area\n|other_names = \n|alma_mater  = [[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign]]<br/>[[Santa Clara University]]\n|known_for   = [[JavaScript]], opposition to [[same-sex marriage]]<ref name=pinknews/><ref name=standard/><ref name=Kim1/><ref name=reuters/>\n|website     = {{URL|https://brendaneich.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Brendan Eich''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|a\u026a|k}}; born July 4, 1961)<ref name=\"NYT_1997_09_09\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/09/09/business/part-artist-part-hacker-and-full-time-programmer.html|title=Part Artist, Part Hacker And Full-Time Programmer|last=Lohr|first=Steve|date=1996-09-09|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-06-29|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref> is an American technologist and creator of the [[JavaScript]] [[programming language]]. He co-founded the [[Mozilla]] project,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Business/mozilla-ceo-resigns-calif-gay-marriage-ban-campaign/story?id=23181711|title=Mozilla CEO Resigns After Calif. Gay Marriage Ban Campaign Donation - ABC News|author=ABC News|work=ABC News}}</ref> the [[Mozilla Foundation]] and the [[Mozilla Corporation]], and served as the Mozilla Corporation's [[chief technical officer]] and briefly, as its [[chief executive officer]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Swisher|first=Kara|title=Mozilla Co-Founder Brendan Eich Resigns as CEO, Leaves Foundation Board|url=http://recode.net/2014/04/03/mozilla-co-founder-brendan-eich-resigns-as-ceo-and-also-from-foundation-board|publisher=Recode|accessdate=April 3, 2014}}</ref> He is the CEO of [[Brave (web browser)|Brave Software]].<ref name=\"cnet.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cnet.com/au/news/mystery-startup-from-ex-mozilla-ceo-aims-to-go-where-tech-titans-wont/|title=Mystery startup from ex-Mozilla CEO aims to go where tech titans won't|date=17 November 2015|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=CNET}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBrendan Eich grew up in Pittsburgh; Gaithersburg, Maryland; and [[Palo Alto]],<ref name=\"NYT_1997_09_09\" /> and he attended [[Ellwood P. Cubberley High School]], graduating in the class of 1979. Eich received his [[bachelor's degree]] in mathematics and computer science at [[Santa Clara University]].<ref name=\"NYT_1997_09_09\"/> He received his [[master's degree]] in 1985 from the [[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign]].<ref name=\"NYT_1997_09_09\" />\n\nEich started his career at [[Silicon Graphics]], working for seven years on [[operating system]] and network code.<ref name=\"aboutcom\">{{Citation|contribution-url=http://inventors.about.com/library/inventors/bl_javascript.htm|contribution=Brendan Eich and JavaScript|title=Inventors|publisher=About}}.</ref> He then worked for three years at [[MicroUnity|MicroUnity Systems Engineering]] writing [[kernel (computer science)|microkernel]] and [[digital signal processor|DSP]] code, and doing the first [[MIPS architecture|MIPS]] [[R4000]] port of [[GNU Compiler Collection|GCC]].<ref name=\"aboutcom\"/>\n\n==Netscape and JavaScript==\nHe started work at [[Netscape Communications Corporation]] in April 1995. Eich originally joined intending to put [[Scheme (programming language)|Scheme]] \"in the browser\",<ref name=\"Saternos2014\">{{cite book|last=Saternos|first=Casimir|title=Client-Server Web Apps with JavaScript and Java|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3b40AwAAQBAJ&pg=PT32|accessdate=4 April 2014|date=2014-03-28|publisher=O'Reilly Media|isbn=9781449369293|pages=32\u2013}}</ref> but his Netscape superiors insisted that the language\u2019s syntax resemble that of [[Java (programming language)|Java]]. The result was a language that had much of the functionality of Scheme, the object orientation of [[Self (programming language)|Self]], and the syntax of Java. The first version was completed in ten days in order to accommodate the Navigator 2.0 Beta release schedule,<ref name=Saternos2014/><ref name=\"Severance\">{{cite news|url=http://www.computer.org/csdl/mags/co/2012/02/mco2012020007.pdf|title=JavaScript: Designing a Language in 10 Days|last=Severance|first=Charles|date=February 2012|work=[[Computer (magazine)|Computer]]|accessdate=April 4, 2014}}</ref> and was called Mocha, but renamed LiveScript in September 1995 and later JavaScript in December.<ref name=\"quirks\">{{cite web|url=http://www.quirksmode.org/js/intro.html|title=JavaScript: General introduction|accessdate= 2011-02-12}}</ref> Eich continued to oversee the development of [[SpiderMonkey (JavaScript engine)|SpiderMonkey]], the specific implementation of JavaScript in Navigator.<ref name=BE201106>{{cite web|url=http://brendaneich.com/2011/06/new-javascript-engine-module-owner|title=New JavaScript Engine Module Owner|date=June 21, 2011|first=Brendan|last=Eich|publisher=BrendanEich.com}}</ref>\n\n==Mozilla==\nIn early 1998, Eich co-founded the [[Mozilla]] project with [[Jamie Zawinski]] and others, creating the mozilla.org website, which was meant to manage open-source contributions to the Netscape source code. He served as Mozilla's chief [[Systems architect|architect]].<ref name=\"Seibel2009\">{{cite book|last=Seibel|first=Peter|title=Coders at Work: Reflections on the Craft of Programming|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nneBa6-mWfgC&pg=PA132|accessdate=4 April 2014|date=2009-09-16|publisher=Apress|isbn=9781430219484|pages=132\u2013}}</ref> [[America Online|AOL]] bought Netscape in 1999. After AOL shut down the Netscape browser unit in July 2003, Eich helped spin out the [[Mozilla Foundation]].<ref name=\"mozilla-press-2005-08-03\"/>\n\nIn August 2005, after serving as lead technologist and as a member of the board of directors of the Mozilla Foundation, Eich became [[chief technical officer]] of the newly founded [[Mozilla Corporation]], meant to be the Mozilla Foundation's for-profit arm.<ref name=\"mozilla-press-2005-08-03\">{{cite web|url=https://www-archive.mozilla.org/press/mozilla-2005-08-03.html|title=Mozilla Foundation Forms New Organization to Further the Creation of Free, Open Source Internet Software, Including the Award-Winning Mozilla Firefox Browser|date=2005-08-03|publisher=[[Mozilla Foundation]]|quote= Brendan Eich, a co-founder and long-time technical leader of the Mozilla project, will become the chief technical officer of the Mozilla Corporation.|accessdate=2011-02-12}}</ref> Eich continued to \"own\" the Mozilla SpiderMonkey module, its JavaScript engine, until he passed on the ownership of it in 2011.<ref name=BE201106/>\n\nOn March 24, 2014, Eich was promoted to CEO of Mozilla Corporation.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Mozilla|title=Leadership Changes|date=March 24, 2014|url=https://blog.mozilla.org/blog/2014/03/24/mozilla-leadership-changes|type=blog|accessdate=March 24, 2014}}</ref> [[Gary Kovacs]], [[John Lilly (computer scientist)|John Lilly]], and [[Ellen Siminoff]] resigned from the Mozilla board prior to the appointment,<ref name=wsj>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/digits/2014/03/28/three-mozilla-board-members-resign-over-choice-of-new-ceo/|title=Three Mozilla Board Members Resign over Choice of New CEO|author=Alistair Barr|work=WSJ}}</ref> some anonymously expressing disagreements with Eich's strategy and their desire for a CEO with experience in the mobile industry.<ref>\"On mobile devices, however, Firefox ranks 13th, with less than 0.1% share, according to Net Applications\" Note Net Applications rated Firefox on mobile at [https://web.archive.org/web/20131112112801/http://marketshare.hitslink.com/browser-market-share.aspx?qprid=0&qpcustomd=1 0.01% in Nov 2013] and [https://web.archive.org/web/20140715042405/http://marketshare.hitslink.com/browser-market-share.aspx?qprid=0&qpcustomd=1 0.68% in Jul 2014]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/business/2014/03/three-mozilla-board-members-including-two-former-ceos-step-down/|title=Three Mozilla board members\u2014including former CEOs\u2014step down [Updated]|last=Machkovech|first=Sam|date=March 28, 2014|work=Ars Technica}}</ref>\n\nSome employees of Mozilla Foundation (a separate organization from Mozilla Corporation) tweeted calls for his resignation, with reference to his donation of $1,000 to [[California Proposition 8 (2008)|California Proposition 8]], which called for the banning of [[same-sex marriage in California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.mozilla.org/blog/2014/04/03/brendan-eich-steps-down-as-mozilla-ceo|title=Brendan Eich Steps Down as Mozilla CEO|last=Baker|first=Mitchell|date=April 3, 2014|publisher=The Mozilla Blog}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.mozilla.org/blog/2014/04/05/faq-on-ceo-resignation|title=FAQ on CEO Resignation|publisher=Mozilla|date=April 5, 2014|accessdate=April 6, 2014}}</ref> This donation had first made international news in 2012.<ref name=pinknews>https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2012/04/04/javascript-inventor-gave-1000-to-support-californias-gay-marriage-ban/</ref> Eich stood by his decision to fund the campaign, but wrote on his blog that he was sorry for \"causing pain\" and pledged to promote equality at Mozilla.<ref name=wsj/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://brendaneich.com/2014/03/inclusiveness-at-mozilla/|title=Brendan Eich|work=brendaneich.com}}</ref> Some of the activists created an online campaign{{cn|date=December 2019}} against Eich, with online dating site [[OkCupid]] automatically displaying a message to Firefox users with information about Eich's donation, and suggesting that users switch to a different browser (although giving them a link to continue with Firefox).<ref name=\"latimes-donation\">{{cite news|first=Deborah|last=Netburn|title=Brendan Eich's Prop. 8 contribution gets Twittersphere buzzing|publisher=[[LA Times]]|date=2012-04-04|url=http://www.latimes.com/business/technology/la-fi-tn-brendan-eich-prop-8-contribution-20120404,0,6341761.story|accessdate=2012-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url = https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/online-dating-site-okcupid-calls-for-firefox-boycott-to-protest-at-antigay-marriage-boss-9226904.html|title = OkCupid calls for Firefox boycott to protest anti-gay marriage CEO Brendan Eich|last = Johnston|first = Ian|date = April 1, 2014|work = Independent|accessdate = June 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.advocate.com/business/technology/2014/03/26/mozilla-ceo-responds-antigay-allegations|title = OkCupid calls for Firefox boycott to protest anti-gay marriage CEO Brendan Eich|last=Byrdum|first=Sunnivie|date = March 26, 2014|work = The Advocate|accessdate = }}</ref> Others at the Mozilla Corporation spoke out on their blogs in his favor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/business/2014/03/mozilla-employees-to-brendan-eich-step-down|title=Mozilla employees tell Brendan Eich he needs to \"step down\"|work=Ars Technica|date=March 27, 2014|accessdate=March 28, 2014|first=Sam|last=Machkovech}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://subfictional.com/2014/03/24/on-brendan-eich-as-ceo-of-mozilla|title=On Brendan Eich as CEO of Mozilla|work=Subfictional Studios|date=March 24, 2014|accessdate=April 7, 2014|first=Christie|last=Koehler}}</ref> Board members wanted him to stay in the company in a different role.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url = https://www.theregister.co.uk/Print/2014/04/08/mozilla_anti_gay_marriage_boycott/|title = Gay marriage foes outraged at Mozilla CEO flap, call for boycott|last = McAllister|first = Neil|date = April 8, 2014|work = The Register|accessdate = June 5, 2014}}</ref> On April 3, 2014, Eich resigned as CEO and left Mozilla; in his personal blog, he posted, \"under the present circumstances, I cannot be an effective leader\".<ref name=Kim1>{{cite news|last=Kim|first=Susana|title=Mozilla CEO Brendan Eich Resigns After Protests from Gay Marriage Supporters|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Business/mozilla-ceo-resigns-calif-gay-marriage-ban-campaign/story?id=23181711|accessdate=April 3, 2014|newspaper=ABC News|date=April 3, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"eichblog\">{{Cite web|title=Brendan Eich steps down as Mozilla CEO|date=April 3, 2014|url=https://blog.mozilla.org/blog/2014/04/03/brendan-eich-steps-down-as-mozilla-ceo|publisher=blog.mozilla.org|accessdate=April 8, 2014}}</ref> The resignation also made international news, and was viewed as due to Eich's opposition to same-sex marriage.<ref name=standard>https://www.standard.co.uk/news/techandgadgets/mozilla-boss-brendan-eich-quits-in-row-over-his-opposition-to-gay-marriage-9237701.html</ref><ref name=bbc>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-26868536</ref><ref name=reuters>https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mozilla-ceo-resignation/mozilla-ceo-resigns-opposition-to-gay-marriage-drew-fire-idUSBREA321Y320140403</ref>\n\nWhile some media reports have pegged Eich's resignation directly to controversies surrounding his donation to supporters of Proposition 8,<ref name=Kim1/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Lee |first1=Dave |title=Mozilla boss Brendan Eich resigns after gay marriage storm |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-26868536 |accessdate=December 28, 2019 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=April 4, 2014}}</ref> others who worked at Mozilla Corporation at the time said there were other factors surrounding Eich's departure.<ref name=\"CNETEichResign\">{{cite news |last1=Shankland |first1=Stephen |title=Mozilla under fire: Inside the 9-day reign of fallen CEO Brendan Eich |url=https://www.cnet.com/g00/news/mozilla-under-fire-inside-the-9-day-reign-of-fallen-ceo-brendan-eich/?i10c.ua=4&i10c.encReferrer=aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29vZ2xlLmNvbS8%3d&i10c.dv=15 |accessdate=December 28, 2019 |work=[[CNET]] |date=June 13, 2014}}</ref>  They say Eich faced doubts over his leadership and managerial ability from board members during the CEO selection process, with some saying he is better suited in a science role within the organization.<ref name=\"CNETEichResign\"/> They also asserted that Eich failed to defuse the donation controversy when it surfaced, which further inflamed the situation.<ref name=\"CNETEichResign\"/>\n\n==Brave Software==\nEich is the CEO of Brave Software, an Internet browser platform company that raised $2.5 million in early funding from [[angel investor]]s.<ref name=\"cnet.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/prnewswire/press_releases/2015/11/17/SF59778|title=Brave Software Raises $2.5 Million And Expands Technical Team|work=The Business Journals}}</ref> On January 20, 2016, the company released developer versions of its open-source [[Brave (web browser)|Brave web browser]], which blocks ads and trackers, and includes a [[micropayment]]s system to offer users a choice between viewing selected ads or paying websites not to display them.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brave.com/blogpost_1.html|title=Building a Better Web|website=Brave Software|accessdate=29 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nAt Brave Software, Eich co-created the Basic Attention Token (BAT), a cryptocurrency designed for use in the Brave browser. BAT launched its [[Initial coin offering|ICO]] on May 31, 2017 and raised $35 million.<ref>https://techcrunch.com/2017/06/01/brave-ico-35-million-30-seconds-brendan-eich/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Brendan Eich}}\n*{{official}}\n\n{{Netscape}}\n{{Mozilla}}\n{{ECMAScript}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Gary Kovacs]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=CEO of [[Mozilla Corporation]]\n|years=24 March 2014 \u2013 3 April 2014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Chris Beard (executive)|Chris Beard]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eich, Brendan}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:American chief technology officers]]\n[[Category:American computer programmers]]\n[[Category:2008 California Proposition 8]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mozilla developers]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Pittsburgh]]\n[[Category:Silicon Graphics people]]\n[[Category:Santa Clara University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign alumni]]\n[[Category:Netscape people]]\n[[Category:Computer programmers]]\n[[Category:Web developers]]\n[[Category:American technology chief executives]]\n[[Category:People associated with JavaScript]]\n", "name_user": "72.137.100.211", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Removed Known for Opposition to gay marriage. This is irrelevant and ideological.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brendan_Eich"}
{"title_page": "Greenhouse gas emissions by Turkey", "text_new": "{{About|gases from the Eurasian country which contribute to global warming, and their mitigation|the effects of global warming and adaptation to it|Climate change in Turkey}}\n{{short description|Climate-changing gases from the Eurasian country}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n\n'''Greenhouse gas emissions by Turkey''' are the [[Greenhouse gas inventory|contributions]] within [[Turkey]] to the emission of [[greenhouse gasses]] such as [[carbon dioxide]] or [[ hydrofluorocarbons]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ipcc.ch/report/2019-refinement-to-the-2006-ipcc-guidelines-for-national-greenhouse-gas-inventories/|title=2019 Refinement to the 2006 IPCC Guidelines for National Greenhouse Gas Inventories \u2014 IPCC|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> Turkey's human contributions to emissions can be segmented by sector, such as looking specifically at [[List of power stations in Turkey|Turkey's power stations]] or transport. In addition, the natural and [[Agriculture in Turkey|agricultural landscape of Turkey]] contribute to its national greenhouse gas emissions, with methane and [[N2O|N<sub>2</sub>O]] from agriculture more than offset by carbon dioxide trapped in forests, thus slightly reducing Turkey's overall emissions. [[Energy policy of Turkey|Turkey's policies on energy]], industry, and its explicit policies on climate change affect its level of emissions, and these policies are shaped by the relationship between emissions and economic activity. Finally, media, academic, and individual figures have provided commentary on Turkey's policies and levels of emissions. \n\nCoal, cars and cows vent half the greenhouse gas, but a fifth is absorbed by trees. Turks emit about 1% of the world's total greenhouse gases,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/tr/ekonomi/turkiyede-sera-gazi-emisyonu-azaldi/1786460|title=T\u00fcrkiye'de sera gaz\u0131 emisyonu azald\u0131|website=www.aa.com.tr|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /> averaging over six tonnes each,<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/life/environment/turkeys-greenhouse-gas-emissions-fall-for-second-year-in-a-row|title=Turkey's greenhouse gas emissions fall for second year in a row|date=2020-03-31|publisher=[[Daily Sabah]]}}</ref> somewhat worse than the [[List of countries by greenhouse gas emissions per capita|global average per person]] of five tonnes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wri.org/blog/2019/12/co2-emissions-climb-all-time-high-again-2019-6-takeaways-latest-climate-data|title=CO2 Emissions Climb to an All-Time High (Again) in 2019: 6 Takeaways from the Latest Climate Data|date=2019-12-03|website=World Resources Institute|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> Burning fossil fuels for electricity, heat and [[transport in Turkey]], emitted over 70% of greenhouse gasses in 2018 and industry and agriculture emitted over 10% each;<ref name=\":3\" /> whereas forests and reforestation together absorbed about 20%.  Coal, which is used to generate electricity for heating and by industry, accounts for most of Turkey's fossil fuel {{nowrap|{{chem2|CO2}}}} emissions; followed by natural gas, which is also used for heating and electricity generation; and [[petroleum products]] used for transport. \n\n[[File:Ghg pie chart Turkey.svg|Sources of 2017 greenhouse gas emissions|thumb|upright=1.4]]\n\nAlthough [[climate change in Turkey]] is forecast to have severe impacts,<ref name=\"3rd BR\">{{cite book |title=Turkey's Seventh National Communication and Third Biennial Report to United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change |publisher=Republic of Turkey Ministry of Environment and Urbanization |url=http://unfccc.int/files/national_reports/biennial_reports_and_iar/submitted_biennial_reports/application/pdf/1428795_turkey-br3-1-tur.br3.english.pdf |page=4}}</ref> the country's plans to limit emissions have been described as \"critically insufficient\".<ref name=\"CAT\">{{cite web|url=https://climateactiontracker.org/countries/turkey/|title=Turkey|publisher=Climate Action Tracker|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614203500/https://climateactiontracker.org/countries/turkey/|archive-date=14 June 2018|accessdate=1 October 2018}}</ref> Turkey has signed but not ratified global agreements on reducing greenhouse gas emissions: the country has not yet ratified the [[Kigali accord]] to regulate hydrofluorocarbons, and is one of the few [[List of parties to the Paris Agreement#Signatories|countries that have not ratified the Paris agreement on climate change]]. One of the main reason for Turkey's high rate of emissions is that [[List of coal fired power stations in Turkey|coal-fired power stations in Turkey]] are subsidized. The country was one of those contributing most to the growth in global emissions between 2008 and 2018,<ref>{{cite news |title=Cars and coal help drive 'strong' CO2 rise in 2018 |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-46447459 |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=5 December 2018 |access-date=18 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181219014056/https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-46447459 |archive-date=19 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> but is now investing in energy efficiency and [[renewable energy in Turkey]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/turkey/2019/04/12/turkeys-greenhouse-gas-emissions-hit-over-526-million-tons|title=Turkey's greenhouse gas emissions hit over 526 million tons|website=DailySabah|access-date=2019-09-18}}</ref> and is likely to meet the \u201cunambitious\u201d [[Intended Nationally Determined Contribution]] (INDC) it has submitted to the [[United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change]] (UNFCCC).<ref name=\"Climate Transparency 2018\">{{cite web |title=BROWN TO GREEN: THE G20 TRANSITION TO A LOW-CARBON ECONOMY |date=2018 |url=https://www.climate-transparency.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/BROWN-TO-GREEN_2018_Turkey_FINAL.pdf |publisher=Climate Transparency |accessdate=1 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302090520/https://www.climate-transparency.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/BROWN-TO-GREEN_2018_Turkey_FINAL.pdf |archive-date=2 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==2030 target==\nTurkey submitted its [[Intended Nationally Determined Contributions]] goals to the [[UNFCCC]] in 2015. This 2030 target would result in an overall increase in emissions compared to the 2010s.{{sfnp|4th biennial report|2019|p=7}}{{sfnp|New Climate Institute|2019|p=109}} On a per-capita basis, this target would also mean an emissions rate of 10 tonnes per person in 2030. However, {{As of|2019|lc=y}}, an increase to 8 tonnes per capita by 2030 is considered more likely.{{sfnp|New Climate Institute|2019|p=111}} However, if suitable policies were implemented for electricity supply, land transport and residential buildings a decrease would be possible.<ref name=\"Climate Action Tracker 2019 p. 63\">Climate Action Tracker (2019), p. 63</ref> The [[OECD]] says Turkey needs to integrate climate and energy objectives, and that its National Climate Change Strategy and Action Plan should break down emissions reduction goals by sector, and include regular monitoring and evaluation.<ref name=\"OECD 2019, executive summary\"/>\n\nIn 2019, the [[OECD]] recommended that [[climate change mitigation]] efforts be increased<ref name=\"OECD 2019, page 38\">OECD (2019), page 38</ref> as the national strategy and action plan only partly covers mitigation and only for the short-term.<ref name=\"European Commission 2019 page 94\" /> Turkey's [[Intended Nationally Determined Contributions]] (INDC), submitted in 2015, are up to 21 percent reduction in GHG emissions from the Business as Usual (BAU) level by 2030.<ref name=\"INDC\">{{cite web|url=http://www4.unfccc.int/submissions/INDC/Published%20Documents/Turkey/1/The_INDC_of_TURKEY_v.15.19.30.pdf|title=REPUBLIC OF TURKEY INTENDED NATIONALLY DETERMINED CONTRIBUTION|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920155826/http://www4.unfccc.int/submissions/INDC/Published%20Documents/Turkey/1/The_INDC_of_TURKEY_v.15.19.30.pdf|archive-date=20 September 2018|access-date=24 February 2019}}</ref> However that would result in a large rise in emissions,<ref>[https://wedocs.unep.org/bitstream/handle/20.500.11822/22070/EGR_2017.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y \"The Emissions Gap Report 2017 page 9\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190129125722/https://wedocs.unep.org/bitstream/handle/20.500.11822/22070/EGR_2017.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y|date=29 January 2019}} United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP)</ref> and has been described as \u201ccritically insufficient\u201d.<ref name=\"CAT\" /> Turkey's GHG per person is slightly below the EU average but GHG per unit GDP a little above.<ref>EEA (2019), p. 161</ref> In southern Europe solar power can compete without subsidies<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.evwind.es/2019/09/21/wind-power-and-solar-energy-already-compete-without-subsidies/70999|title=Wind power and solar energy already compete without subsidies {{!}} REVE News of the wind sector in Spain and in the world|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref> and neighbouring [[Greece]] plans to close all its coal-fired power stations<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://balkangreenenergynews.com/greece-seeks-to-phase-out-coal-by-2028-ptolemaida-v-prospects-unclear/|title=Greece seeks to phase out coal by 2028, Ptolemaida V prospects unclear|date=2019-09-25|website=Balkan Green Energy News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref> by 2028, starting in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/environment/un-chief-urges-leaders-to-avoid-new-coal-after-2020/1592627|title=UN chief urges leaders to avoid 'new coal' after 2020|website=www.aa.com.tr|access-date=2019-10-03}}</ref> [[Portugal]], which has regions with similar solar potential, aims to be [[carbon neutral]] by 2050.<ref>{{cite news |title=Portuguese Government Launches Climate Plan With Ambitious Carbon-Neutral Target |url=https://www.southeusummit.com/europe/portugal/portuguese-government-launches-climate-plan-with-ambitious-carbon-neutral-target/ |work=South EU Summit |date=24 December 2018 |access-date=28 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190301013405/https://www.southeusummit.com/europe/portugal/portuguese-government-launches-climate-plan-with-ambitious-carbon-neutral-target/ |archive-date=1 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Greenhouse gas sources==\n[[File:Ghg bar chart Turkey.svg|thumb|upright=1.4|Greenhouse gas emissions and absorption in Turkey in 2017{{sfnp|Turkstat report|2019|p=iv}}]]\n\n526 Mt of {{CO2}} was emitted in 2017,<ref name=\"TurkStat\">{{cite web |title=Greenhouse Gas Emissions Statistics, 1990-2017 |url=http://www.turkstat.gov.tr/PreHaberBultenleri.do?id=30627 |publisher=Turkish Statistical Institute |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref> mostly by fossil fuels, but around 100 Mt was reabsorbed by [[land use, land-use change, and forestry]] (LULUCF),<ref name=\"GHGsummary\">{{cite web |title=Summary of GHG Emissions for Turkey |url=http://di.unfccc.int/ghg_profiles/annexOne/TUR/TUR_ghg_profile.pdf |publisher=[[UNFCCC]] |accessdate=8 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181108184410/http://di.unfccc.int/ghg_profiles/annexOne/TUR/TUR_ghg_profile.pdf |archive-date=8 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{efn|1=vertical bars show uncertainty, which for 2017 without LULUCF was 5.3%, but as LULUCF uncertainty as shown was very large with LULUCF was 13.8%{{sfnp|Turkstat report|2019|p=22}} }} mostly by forests. The amount removed by forests is very uncertain (as shown by the vertical bar on the chart above it could be anything from 50 Mt to 150 Mt) but is expected to be clarified in 2020.{{sfnp|Turkstat report|2019|p=489}}\n\n[[File:CO2 by fossil fuel Turkey.svg|thumb|upright=1.4|CO<sub>2</sub> emitted by fossil fuels burnt in Turkey in 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iea.org//statistics/|title=Statistics|website=www.iea.org|access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref>]]\nIn 2017 [[coal in Turkey]] emitted the most, followed by oil then natural gas.\n\nWith a population of 80 million Turkey's emissions are above the world average, which is 5 tonnes per person per year. The government agency [[Turkish Statistical Institute]] (Turkstat) follows [[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change]] (IPCC) guidelines and uses [[Greenhouse gas emissions accounting#Production-based accounting|production based greenhouse gas emissions accounting]] to compile Turkey's [[emission inventory]]. Being listed as a developed country (Annex 1), Turkey must submit its inventory of 2018 emissions to the UNFCCC by 15 April 2020, and so on for each calendar year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://unfccc.int/process-and-meetings/transparency-and-reporting/reporting-and-review-under-the-convention/greenhouse-gas-inventories-annex-i-parties/reporting-requirements|title=Reporting requirements {{!}} UNFCCC|website=unfccc.int|access-date=2019-10-08}}</ref> The UNFCCC reviews countries' inventories and makes recommendations for improvement: many recommendations to Turkey have been resolved or will be resolved by the next inventory, but many have been outstanding for over 3 years.{{sfnp|Inventory review|2019|p=21}} The UNFCCC has asked for much more detail to be provided, so that emissions projections provided by Turkey for various government policies and [[Shared Socioeconomic Pathways]] can be understood, for example details of the [[Integrated assessment modelling|integrated assessment model]] developed by [[I\u015f\u0131k University]] and [[Bosphorus University]].{{sfnp|Tech review 3rd report|2019|p=15}}{{efn|1=As \"national communications\" are required every 4 years the 5th biennial report and 8th national communication may be combined as the same document, as was the case previously.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://unfccc.int/process/transparency-and-reporting/reporting-and-review-under-the-convention/support-for-developing-countries/modalities--procedures-and-guidelines#eq-2|title=Preparation of NCs and BRs {{!}} UNFCCC|website=unfccc.int|access-date=2019-10-31}}</ref>}}  These are used for non-energy emissions.{{sfnp|4th biennial report|2019|p=33}}\n\n===Burning fossil fuels for heat and power===\n{{See also|Energy policy of Turkey}}\nIn 2018 Turkey's energy sector, which under IPCC guidelines includes fuel for transport, emitted almost three quarters of the country's greenhouse gases, whereas [[Industrial Processes]] and Product Use (IPPU) and agriculture each emitted an eighth.<ref name=\":3\" /> The largest emitters are energy industries\u2014mainly electricity generation\u2014followed by transport.{{sfnp|Turkstat report|2019|p=43}} [[Carbon capture and storage]] barely exists in Turkey's energy sector; it is not economically viable as Turkey has no [[carbon emission trading]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Esmaeili |first1=Danial |date=June 2018 |title=Carbon Capture, Utilization and Storage in the Context of Turkish Energy Market |publisher=[[Sabanc\u0131 University]] |url=http://research.sabanciuniv.edu/36807/1/1806_IICECE%26CPaperCCUSinTurkey_0.pdf |access-date=14 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514155754/http://research.sabanciuniv.edu/36807/1/1806_IICECE%26CPaperCCUSinTurkey_0.pdf |archive-date=14 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Energy emissions are modelled by [[Energy modeling#MARKAL/TIMES|TIMES]].{{sfnp|4th biennial report|2019|p=33}}\n\n====Power stations====\n[[List of power stations in Turkey|Power stations in Turkey]] emitted 145 Mt CO<sub>2eq</sub> in 2017,{{sfnp|Turkstat tables|2019|loc=table 1s1 cell B10}} mostly from burning coal. Turkey's emissions from electricity generation could rise to 200 Mt by 2021.<ref>{{cite journal |last=\u015eahin |first=Utkucan |title=Forecasting of Turkey's electricity generation and CO2 emissions in estimating capacity factor |journal=American Institute of Chemical Engineers Environ Prog. |volume=38 |pages=56\u201365 |date=2 November 2018 |doi=10.1002/ep.13076 }}</ref> {{efn|In 2017, the carbon content([[tonne|t]]/[[Terajoule|TJ]]), oxidation factor and CO<sub>2</sub> emission intensity (t/TJ [[Heat of combustion#Lower heating value|NCV]]) of the main fossil fuels burnt in Turkish power stations were:{{sfnp|Turkstat report|2019|pp=50 & 51, table 3.5, 3.6, 3.7}}\n\n[[Lignite]]  30,  0.973,  107\n[[Bituminous coal|Hardcoal]]    26,  0.975,  95\n[[Natural gas]]  15,  1,  56\n\nThe CO<sub>2</sub> emission intensity (or emission factor) shown above is the mass of CO<sub>2</sub> emitted for each unit of ''heat'' produced by burning a fuel. In contrast the ''grid'' [[emission intensity]] is the mass of CO<sub>2eq</sub> produced per unit of ''electricity'' supplied to the [[electrical grid]]. Because [[thermal power station]]s generally convert less than half of the heat energy into electrical energy, their numbers for grid emission intensity are much greater than those shown above.\n}}\n\nAlmost all coal burnt in power stations is either local [[lignite]] or imported hardcoal. [[Coal assay|Coal analysis]] of Turkish lignite compared to other lignites shows it to have a lot of ash and moisture, a low [[energy value of coal]] and high emission intensity: in other words Turkish lignite emits more CO<sub>2</sub> than typical lignites per unit energy produced when burnt.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.powerengineeringint.com/articles/print/volume-25/issue-11/features/cfb-in-turkey-the-right-timing-for-the-right-technology.html|title=CFB in Turkey: The right timing for the right technology|website=www.powerengineeringint.com|access-date=2019-09-08}}</ref> However although imported hardcoal has a slightly lower emission intensity when burnt, the lifecycle greenhouse gas emissions take account of transportation so are similar.<ref name=\"Atilgan et al 2016, p. 177\">Atilgan et al (2016), p. 177</ref>\n\nDespite considerable potential for expansion of [[renewable energy in Turkey]], which except for geothermal emits little CO<sub>2eq</sub>, Turkey averages a grid emission intensity over 460 gCO<sub>2eq</sub>/kWh (over 125 t/TJ),<ref name=AVTrans2018>{{cite web|title=Towards Decarbonising Transport|url=https://www.agora-verkehrswende.de/fileadmin/Projekte/2017/Verkehr_und_Klima_in_den_G20_Laendern/15_G20_WEB.pdf|publisher=Agora Verkehrswende|access-date=6 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107015851/https://www.agora-verkehrswende.de/fileadmin/Projekte/2017/Verkehr_und_Klima_in_den_G20_Laendern/15_G20_WEB.pdf|archive-date=7 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> similar to that of natural gas. Both grid intensity and carbon emissions per person are worse than the global average.<ref>{{cite web |title=Energy Revolution: A Global Outlook |url=https://www.drax.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Energy-Revolution-Global-Outlook-Report-Final-Dec-2018-COP24.pdf |publisher=Drax |accessdate=7 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190209123738/https://www.drax.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Energy-Revolution-Global-Outlook-Report-Final-Dec-2018-COP24.pdf |archive-date=9 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=====Coal fired power stations=====\n[[File:Yenik\u00f6y Power Plant Milas Mu\u011fla Turkey.jpg|thumb|[[Yenik\u00f6y power station]] and two others pollute [[Mu\u011fla]]<ref>{{cite web |title=THE REAL COSTS OF COAL: MU\u011eLA |url=http://www.caneurope.org/docman/coal-phase-out/3552-the-real-costs-of-coal-mugla/file |website=CAN Europe}}</ref>]]\n[[List of coal fired power stations in Turkey|Coal fired power stations in Turkey]] emitted 98 Mt CO<sub>2eq</sub> in 2017:{{sfnp|Turkstat tables|2019|loc=table 1.A(a)s1 cell G26 \"solid fuels\"}} and, if operated at the targeted [[capacity factor]], planned new [[Af\u015fin-Elbistan power stations|units at Af\u015fin Elbistan]] would add over 61 Mt each year, according to the [http://eced.csb.gov.tr/ced/jsp/ek1/23019# Af\u015fin-Elbistan C environmental impact report].<ref>\u00c7\u0131nar (2019), p. 280</ref>{{efn|1=Somewhat over a million tonnes of CO<sub>2</sub> is emitted for every [[TWh]] of electricity generated in Turkey by coal-fired power stations. According to page xix of [http://eced.csb.gov.tr/ced/jsp/ek1/23019# the Af\u015fin-Elbistan C environmental impact report] it is aimed to generate just over 12.5 TWh (gross) per year, so why the CO2 emissions are predicted to be so high is unclear. According to the calculation at the end of page 280 of the September 2019 version of the EIA 6.16X10<sup>10</sup> tCO2/year would be emitted, but that is a unit error as according to the inputs it would be 6.16X10<sup>7</sup> tCO2/year which is the figure quoted above.}}\n\n[[Coal in Turkey]] is the largest source of the nation's greenhouse gases. Over a million tonnes of CO<sub>2</sub> is emitted for every [[TWh]] of electricity generated in Turkey by coal-fired power stations.<ref name=\"Atilgan et al 2016, p. 177\"/> Once emissions from coal burnt for industry and heating buildings, and [[methane emissions]] from [[coal mining]] are added to those from the almost 100 TWh coal-fired electricity generated annually,<ref name=\"MinCoal\">{{cite web |title=Coal |url=http://www.enerji.gov.tr/en-US/Pages/Coal |publisher=Republic of Turkey Ministry of Energy and Natural Resources |accessdate=17 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180917110843/http://www.enerji.gov.tr/en-US/Pages/Coal |archive-date=17 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> about one third of Turkey's emissions come from coal.<ref>\u015eahin (2016), p. 7</ref> In 2017 coal combustion emitted over 150 Mt CO<sub>2eq</sub>.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iea.org/statistics/?country=TUR&isISO=true|title=Statistics for Turkey|last=|first=|date=|website=[[International Energy Agency]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-07}}</ref> {{As of|2016}}, however, methane emissions from coal mining was the largest uncertainty in Turkey's total gross emissions.<ref name=\"Urbanization 2016 p. 95\">Ministry of Environment and Urbanization (2016), p. 95</ref> Eren Holding, via Eren Enerji's coal-fired [[ZETES power stations]], emits over 2% of Turkey's greenhouse gases; and \u0130\u00c7DA\u015e emits over 1% via its Bekirli coal-fired power stations.<ref>{{cite web|title=Global coal power map|url=https://www.carbonbrief.org/mapped-worlds-coal-power-plants|accessdate=27 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181228173255/https://www.carbonbrief.org/mapped-worlds-coal-power-plants|archive-date=28 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Ministry of Energy and Natural Resources (Turkey)|Energy Minister]] Fatih D\u00f6nmez favors coal<ref>{{cite news |title=New Turkish energy minister bullish for coal -- but lira weakness limits market |url=https://www.platts.kr/latest-news/coal/london/analysis-new-turkish-energy-minister-bullish-26988555 |publisher=Platts |date=12 July 2018 |access-date=28 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180917105121/https://www.platts.kr/latest-news/coal/london/analysis-new-turkish-energy-minister-bullish-26988555 |archive-date=17 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> and [[Ministry of Environment and Urban Planning (Turkey)|Environment Minister]] Murat Kurum is making plans for adaptation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/economy/turkey-must-move-towards-clean-energy-expert/1534088|title=Turkey must move towards clean energy: Expert|website=www.aa.com.tr|access-date=2019-11-12}}</ref> The 2 proposed coal power plants are mainly financed by governments, the Chinese funded [[Emba Hunutlu power station]] and  [[Turkey Wealth Fund]] backed [[Af\u015fin-Elbistan C power station|Af\u015fin-Elbistan C]], and may or may not actually complete construction,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.icis.com/explore/resources/news/2020/03/20/10484952/see-turkey-braced-for-falling-demand-bankruptcies-amid-emergency-measures-fallout|title=SEE, Turkey braced for falling demand, bankruptcies amid emergency measures fallout|last=Sabadus|first=Aura|website=Icis|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> despite government guarantee to purchase electricity from lignite-fired power stations until 2024 at an inflation-linked price.<ref>{{cite web |title=2017/11070 |url=http://www.resmigazete.gov.tr/eskiler/2017/12/20171202-9.pdf |publisher=Resmi Gazete |access-date=28 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171215140139/http://www.resmigazete.gov.tr/eskiler/2017/12/20171202-9.pdf |archive-date=15 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=TETA\u015e's Purchase of Electricity from Domestic Coal Fired Power Plants |url=http://www.cakmak.av.tr/articles/Power/113951311_2.pdf |publisher=\u00c7akmak Avukatl\u0131k Ortakl\u0131\u011f\u0131 |accessdate=17 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180917181641/http://www.cakmak.av.tr/articles/Power/113951311_2.pdf |archive-date=17 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Turkey's climate change policy includes an increase in the economic life of coal reserves.<ref>{{cite book |title=REPUBLIC OF TURKEY CLIMATE CHANGE ACTION PLAN 2011 - 2023 |date=2012 |publisher=Ministry of Environment and Urbanization General Directorate of Environmental Management Climate Change Department |page=28 |url=http://webdosya.csb.gov.tr/db/iklim/editordosya/file/eylem%20planlari/iklim_degisikligi_eylem_plani_EN_2014.pdf |access-date=28 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180917105525/http://webdosya.csb.gov.tr/db/iklim/editordosya/file/eylem%20planlari/iklim_degisikligi_eylem_plani_EN_2014.pdf |archive-date=17 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> {{As of|2019}} the government aims to keep the share of coal in the energy portfolio at around the same level in the medium to long term.{{sfnp|Tech review 7th communication|2019|p=20}}\n\n=====Gas fired power stations=====\n[[File:Ta\u015fk\u0131s\u0131\u011f\u0131 K\u00f6y\u00fc.JPG|thumb|Ta\u015fk\u0131s\u0131\u011f\u0131 K\u00f6y\u00fc gas-fired power station: natural gas is cleaner than coal but costs money to import and also emits greenhouse gases]]\n\n[[List of power stations in Turkey#Natural Gas|Gas fired power stations in Turkey]] emitted 45 Mt CO<sub>2eq</sub> in 2017.{{sfnp|Turkstat tables|2019|loc=table 1.A(a)s1 cell G27}} {{As of|2019}}, however, some power utilities, including at least three gas-fired plants, were struggling to repay their foreign currency debts after the depreciation of the [[Turkish lira|lira]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-09-05/turkey-working-on-plan-to-clear-some-bad-energy-loans-from-banks|title=Turkey Wants Banks to Write Off $1.9 Billion to Boost Credit|last=|first=|date=|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Subsidies are being reduced in 2020.<ref>{{cite news |title=Outlook 2019: Turkish natural gas market set for potential 'de-liberalization' in 2019 |url=https://www.spglobal.com/platts/en/market-insights/latest-news/natural-gas/122718-outlook-2019-turkish-natural-gas-market-set-for-potential-de-liberalization-in-2019 |work=Platts |publisher=S & P Global |date=27 December 2018 |access-date=19 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190219130303/https://www.spglobal.com/platts/en/market-insights/latest-news/natural-gas/122718-outlook-2019-turkish-natural-gas-market-set-for-potential-de-liberalization-in-2019 |archive-date=19 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n====Transport fuel====\n[[File:Traffic jam in Istanbul's road.JPG|thumb|[[Istanbul]] is one of the few major European cities without a low-emission zone]]\n\n[[Transport in Turkey]] is road-dominated<ref name=\"OECD 2019, section 1\">OECD (2019), section 1.</ref> and emitted 85 Mt of CO<sub>2eq</sub> in 2017, 16% of the nation's total. 79 Mt came from roads followed by 4 Mt from domestic aviation.{{sfnp|Turkstat report|2019|p=118}} Emissions from air transport were expected to grow rapidly following the opening of the large [[Istanbul Airport]] in 2019.<ref>{{cite news |title=Climate change is no joke |url=https://www.dailysabah.com/columns/alkin-kerem/2018/10/20/climate-change-is-no-joke |work=Daily Sabah |date=19 October 2018 |access-date=24 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024192148/https://www.dailysabah.com/columns/alkin-kerem/2018/10/20/climate-change-is-no-joke |archive-date=24 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Although Turkey has joined the [[Carbon Offsetting and Reduction Scheme for International Aviation]], emissions from domestic aviation are not taxed. International journeys are not included in a country's emissions total but the UNFCCC has asked for fuel sales for international aviation and shipping to be reported, separately.{{sfnp|Tech review 3rd report|2019|p=15}}\n\nMore than three quarters of Turkey's road transport emissions come from diesel.{{sfnp|Turkstat report|2019|p=133}} Although gasoline and diesel (except possibly agricultural diesel) prices are above the [[G20]] average and electricity is subsidized, the country has a tiny proportion of [[charging station]]s and [[electric car]]s.<ref name=AVTrans2018/> {{As of|2020||df=}}, there were no [[low-emission zone]]s in any Turkish cities, although enabling regulations were introduced in 2019.<ref>{{cite news |title=Low-emission zones for Turkish cities in the works |url=https://www.dailysabah.com/turkey/2019/05/03/low-emission-zones-for-turkish-cities-in-the-works |work=Daily Sabah |date=3 May 2019 |access-date=3 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190503151329/https://www.dailysabah.com/turkey/2019/05/03/low-emission-zones-for-turkish-cities-in-the-works |archive-date=3 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The rate of the special consumption tax\u2014a sales tax on luxuries such as private cars\u2014and the annual motor-vehicle tax is lower for electric cars than for fossil fuel cars, but batteries are taxed by weight.<ref>{{cite news |title=Meclis'ten Elektrikli Otomobile bir darbe daha geldi! |url=http://tehad.org/2018/12/31/meclisten-elektrikli-otomobile-bir-darbe-daha-geldi/ |work=T\u00fcrkiye Elektrikli ve Hibrid Ara\u00e7lar Platformu (TEHAD) |date=31 December 2018 |access-date=6 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107072153/http://tehad.org/2018/12/31/meclisten-elektrikli-otomobile-bir-darbe-daha-geldi/ |archive-date=7 January 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Electric buses<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/business/2019/10/21/local-bus-manufacturers-take-stage-at-busworld-europe-fair|title=Local bus manufacturers take stage at Busworld Europe fair|website=DailySabah|access-date=2019-11-12}}</ref> and hybrid cars are manufactured locally, but none of Turkey's car factories yet produce purely electric cars.<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkey determined to boost hybrid, electric car sales |url=https://www.yenisafak.com/en/world/turkey-determined-to-boost-hybrid-electric-car-sales-3473176 |work=Yeni \u015eafak |date=29 January 2019 |access-date=19 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190129114408/https://www.yenisafak.com/en/world/turkey-determined-to-boost-hybrid-electric-car-sales-3473176 |archive-date=29 January 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2019, 0.1% of cars sold were hybrid or electric.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/economy/2020/02/02/number-of-electric-hybrid-cars-in-turkey-triples-in-2019|title=Number of electric, hybrid cars in Turkey triples in 2019|website=DailySabah|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref> Increasing Turkey's proportion of electric cars in use to 10% by 2030 would have many benefits.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.shura.org.tr/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Transport-sector-transformation.Integrating-electric-vehicles-into-Turkey%E2%80%99s-distribution-grids.pdf|title=Transport sector transformation: Integrating electric vehicles into Turkey\u2019s distribution grids|url-status=live}}</ref> Very few foreign-made electric cars are sold;<ref>{{cite web |title=T\u00fcrkiye Elektrikli ve Hibrid Otomobil Pazar\u0131 / Marka ve Modeller |url=http://tehad.org/2019/01/17/turkiye-elektrikli-ve-hibrid-otomobil-pazari-marka-ve-modeller/ |accessdate=19 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190219130331/http://tehad.org/2019/01/17/turkiye-elektrikli-ve-hibrid-otomobil-pazari-marka-ve-modeller/ |archive-date=19 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> those from American manufacturers, such as [[Tesla, Inc.|Tesla]], are unavailable due to a 120% tariff.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tesla reportedly pulls out of Turkish expansion plan due to new Trump trade war tariffs |url=https://electrek.co/2018/10/31/tesla-turkey-expansion-trump-trade-war-tariffs/ |work=Electrek |date=31 October 2018 |access-date=19 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190220002727/https://electrek.co/2018/10/31/tesla-turkey-expansion-trump-trade-war-tariffs/ |archive-date=20 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2018}}, Turkey lacks any measures to reduce the [[Life-cycle assessment#Well-to-wheel|well to wheel]] impact of petrol and diesel vehicles.<ref>{{cite web |title=EU Fuel Quality Directive Preliminary Regulatory Impact Assessment (Pre-RIA) |url=http://www.lowcarbonturkey.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Annex-1-FQD-RIA-eng.pdf |access-date=30 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430091730/http://www.lowcarbonturkey.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Annex-1-FQD-RIA-eng.pdf |archive-date=30 April 2019 |url-status=live |page=15 }}</ref> {{As of|2019}}, fuel quality and emissions standards for new cars do not meet [[European Union]] (EU) standards.<ref name=\"European Commission 2019 page 94\">European Commission (2019), page 94</ref> [[Turkish Airlines]] did not respond to the 2018 [[Carbon Disclosure Project]] questionnaire<ref>{{cite web |title=CDP Turkey Climate Change and Water Report 2018 |url=https://cdpturkey.sabanciuniv.edu/en/content/cdp-turkey-climate-change-and-water-report-2018 |publisher=[[Carbon Disclosure Project]] |access-date=17 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417090544/https://cdpturkey.sabanciuniv.edu/en/content/cdp-turkey-climate-change-and-water-report-2018 |archive-date=17 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and in 2019, the airline was named as one of those with the weakest plans to cut emissions.<ref>{{cite news |title=Leading airlines failing to plan for long haul on climate, warns influential investor initiative |url=http://www.lse.ac.uk/GranthamInstitute/tpi/leading-airlines-failing-to-plan-for-long-haul-on-climate-warns-influential-investor-initiative/ |publisher=London School of Economics\u2019 Grantham Research Institute |date=5 March 2019 |access-date=7 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190523022530/http://www.lse.ac.uk/GranthamInstitute/tpi/leading-airlines-failing-to-plan-for-long-haul-on-climate-warns-influential-investor-initiative/ |archive-date=23 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n====Burning fuel to heat buildings and cook====\n[[File:Air Pollution in Ankara.jpg|thumb|Pollution over [[Ankara]]: coal is still burnt to heat older buildings in cities]]\n\nResidential fuel such as natural gas, coal and wood contributed 43 Mt CO<sub>2eq</sub> in 2017.{{sfnp|Turkstat report|2019|p=150}} {{As of|2017}} the end-user price of natural gas is subsidized.<ref name=\":1\" /> Subsidies for poor families to use coal for heating produce [[black carbon]], a contributor to climate change,<ref name=\"OECD 2019, section 1\"/> and other [[air pollution in Turkey|local air pollution]].\n\nBurning fuel, such as coal and natural gas, for commercial and industrial buildings emitted 21 Mt CO<sub>2eq</sub> in 2017.{{sfnp|Turkstat report|2019|p=148}}\n\n===Industry===\nIn 2018, [[Economy of Turkey#Industrial sector|Turkey's industrial sector]] emitted an eighth of its greenhouse gases.<ref name=\":3\" /> Iron, steel and cement manufacturing account for 40% of [[primary energy]] consumed by industry; those industries are making efforts to become more environmentally friendly.<ref>Ministry of Environment and Urbanization (2016), pages 45,115</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=MRV IN TURKEY: FROM THEORY TO PRACTICE CEMENT SECTOR EXPERIENCE |url=http://www.tcma.org.tr/images/file/COP%2023%20sunum.pdf |publisher=Turkish Cement Manufacturers\u2019 Association |accessdate=17 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180917181649/http://www.tcma.org.tr/images/file/COP%2023%20sunum.pdf |archive-date=17 September 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> {{As of|2019}}, estimates of the effects of government policy on the sector's emissions are lacking.{{sfnp|Tech review 7th communication|2019|pages=28}} Some business people are concerned that in future the [[European Green Deal]] might include a carbon border tax which Turkey would be outside.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eureporter.co/frontpage/2020/01/13/europeangreendeal-could-re-energize-eu-relations-with-turkey/|title=#EuropeanGreenDeal could re-energize EU relations with #Turkey|date=2020-01-13|website=EU Reporter|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> In 2017, [[Economy of Turkey#Steel-Iron industry|Turkey's iron and steel production]] emitted 21 Mt of CO<sub>2eq</sub>.{{sfnp|Turkstat report|2019|p=229}} The European steel-making industry has complained that imports from Turkey are unfair competition because they are not subject to a carbon tax.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/turkeys-steel-imports-into-europe-a-problem-for-the-industry-says-liberty-house-boss-11814316|title=Turkey's steel imports into Europe a 'problem' for the industry, says Liberty House boss|website=Sky News|language=en|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref>\n\n====Cement====\n[[File:Ata\u015fehir'de y\u00fckselen yeni binalar.2.jpg|thumb|The [[Turkish construction and contracting industry]] was very active until 2018]]\nTurkey is the 4th largest [[cement]] producer in the world<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/business/2019/07/05/turkish-cement-sector-exports-surge-46-percent-in-first-half|title=Turkish cement sector exports surge 46 percent in first half|website=DailySabah|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> and in 2017 cement production emitted 7% of the countries total GHG.{{sfnp|4th biennial report|2019|p=23}} However, Turkey's construction sector contracted considerably at the end of 2018<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkey's economy tips into recession as lira crisis bites |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-turkey-economy-gdp/turkeys-economy-tips-into-recession-as-lira-crisis-bites-idUSKBN1QS0MT |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=11 March 2019 |access-date=21 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321155249/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-turkey-economy-gdp/turkeys-economy-tips-into-recession-as-lira-crisis-bites-idUSKBN1QS0MT |archive-date=21 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> thus using less cement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://think.ing.com/snaps/turkey-a-small-correction-in-january-ip/|title=Turkish industrial production grows 7.9%|last=Mercan|first=Muhammet|date=|website=ING Think|language=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-05|quote=cement production ....... shows the extent of activity in construction}}</ref> More [[cross-laminated timber]] could be used for building, instead of concrete.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thegef.org/sites/default/files/web-documents/10090_PIFReviewSheet.pdf|title=Promoting Low Cost Energy Efficient Wooden Buildings in Turkey|last=|first=|date=|website=Global Environment Facility|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe biggest reduction in emissions from cement production could be made by reducing its [[Clinker (cement)|clinker]] content<ref name=IEAcement2018>{{cite book |title=Technology Roadmap: Low-Carbon Transition in the Cement Industry |date=2018 |url=https://www.iea.org/publications/freepublications/publication/TechnologyRoadmapLowCarbonTransitionintheCementIndustry.pdf |access-date=21 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321070300/https://www.iea.org/publications/freepublications/publication/TechnologyRoadmapLowCarbonTransitionintheCementIndustry.pdf |archive-date=21 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> from the current 87%, for example by making [[Limestone Calcined Clay Cement|LC<sup>3</sup> cement]], which is only half clinker; the second-biggest reduction could be made by switching half of the fuel from [[hard coal]] and [[petcoke]] to a mixture of rubber from waste tires, [[refuse-derived fuel]] and [[biomass]].<ref name=\"Cementis2018\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cementis.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Turkey-GHG-from-Cement.pdf|title=Abstract on the potential GHG emissions reduction in Turkey through the cement industry|publisher=Cementis GmbH|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321063407/http://www.cementis.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Turkey-GHG-from-Cement.pdf|archive-date=21 March 2019|accessdate=21 March 2019}}</ref> The country has plenty of these materials and some cement plants already use them.{{sfnp|Turkstat report|2019|p=99}}\n\nFurther decarbonization of cement production would depend heavily on [[carbon capture and storage]] (CCS).<ref>{{cite web |title=Decarbonization of industrial sectors: the next frontier |url=https://www.mckinsey.com/~/media/McKinsey/Business%20Functions/Sustainability%20and%20Resource%20Productivity/Our%20Insights/How%20industry%20can%20move%20toward%20a%20low%20carbon%20future/Decarbonization-of-industrial-sectors-The-next-frontier.ashx |publisher=[[McKinsey & Company|McKinsey]] |accessdate=17 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180728015756/https://www.mckinsey.com/~/media/mckinsey/business%20functions/sustainability%20and%20resource%20productivity/our%20insights/how%20industry%20can%20move%20toward%20a%20low%20carbon%20future/decarbonization-of-industrial-sectors-the-next-frontier.ashx |archive-date=28 July 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Despite the earthquake risk from the [[geology of Turkey]], CCS may be technically feasible in a [[salt dome]] near [[Lake Tuz]]<ref>{{cite web |title=EU Carbon Capture and Storage Directive Preliminary Regulatory Impact Assessment (Pre-RIA) |url=http://www.lowcarbonturkey.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Annex-2-CCS-RIA-eng.pdf |access-date=30 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430111238/http://www.lowcarbonturkey.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Annex-2-CCS-RIA-eng.pdf |archive-date=30 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> or in [[Diyarbak\u0131r Province|Diyarbak\u0131r]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=FIRTINA ERT\u0130\u015e|first=\u0130rem|date=|title=APPLICATION OF MULTI-CRITERIA DECISION MAKING FOR GEOLOGICAL CARBON DIOXIDE STORAGE AREA IN TURKEY|url=https://dergipark.org.tr/download/article-file/491521|journal=Anadolu University Journal of Science and Technology A- Applied Sciences and Engineering|volume=|pages=|via=|access-date=17 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430074142/https://dergipark.org.tr/download/article-file/491521|archive-date=30 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> However CCS is not currently financially viable because, {{As of|2019|lc=y}}, the country has no carbon price.<ref name=\"European Commission 2019 page 94\"/>\n\n===Agriculture and waste===\n[[File:Jersey cattle in Sisda\u011f\u0131 04.jpg|thumb|Reducing beef and dairy consumption would also reduce imports<ref>{{cite report|title=Turkey Livestock Annual Report 2018|date=2018-08-31|series=GQIN Report|id=TR8027|publisher=[[USDA]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920171601/https://gain.fas.usda.gov/Recent%20GAIN%20Publications/Livestock%20and%20Products%20Annual_Ankara_Turkey_9-7-2018.pdf|archive-date=20 September 2018|url-status=live|url=https://gain.fas.usda.gov/Recent%20GAIN%20Publications/Livestock%20and%20Products%20Annual_Ankara_Turkey_9-7-2018.pdf|access-date=4 April 2019}}</ref>]]\n\nIn 2018, agriculture emitted an eighth of Turkey's greenhouse gases,<ref name=\":3\" /> mainly due to [[enteric fermentation]], agricultural soils, and fertilizer management.<ref>{{cite web |title=Strategies Regarding Mitigation of Greenhouse Gas Emissions from Agriculture Sector in Turkey |url=http://ipc.sabanciuniv.edu/publication/turkiyede-tarim-sektorunden-kaynaklanan-sera-gazi-emisyonlarinin-azaltilmasina-yonelik-stratejiler/?lang=en |access-date=28 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180917143354/http://ipc.sabanciuniv.edu/publication/turkiyede-tarim-sektorunden-kaynaklanan-sera-gazi-emisyonlarinin-azaltilmasina-yonelik-stratejiler/?lang=en |archive-date=17 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The amount of [[nitrous oxide]] emitted by agricultural soils, however, is uncertain.<ref name=\"Urbanization 2016 p. 95\"/> About one million live cattle were imported in 2018, and cattle<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gain.fas.usda.gov/Recent%20GAIN%20Publications/Livestock%20and%20Products%20Annual_Ankara_Turkey_8-29-2019.pdf|title=Livestock and Products Annual 2019|last=|first=|date=|website=USDA|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and fuel for agriculture is subsidized.<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkey increases agricultural subsidies |url=http://www.blackseagrain.net/novosti/turkey-increases-agricultural-subsidies |publisher=UkrAgroConsult |date=10 April 2018 |access-date=28 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180917215559/http://www.blackseagrain.net/novosti/turkey-increases-agricultural-subsidies |archive-date=17 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Some sugar factories such as those owned by T\u00fcrk\u015feker burn coal<ref>{{cite news |title=45.000 ton k\u00f6m\u00fcr alacak |url=https://www.enerjiekonomisi.com/45-000-ton-komur-alacak/2343/ |work=Enerji Ekonomisi |date=3 July 2018 |access-date=23 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190323072408/https://www.enerjiekonomisi.com/45-000-ton-komur-alacak/2343/ |archive-date=23 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and some run small, coal-fired power plants.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Algedik |first1=\u00d6nder |title=Coal & Climate Change - 2017 |url=http://www.onderalgedik.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/Coal-and-Climate-Change-2017.pdf |access-date=28 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180918012206/http://www.onderalgedik.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/Coal-and-Climate-Change-2017.pdf |archive-date=18 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2018, Turkey's agriculture minister said that sugar is a strategic product.<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkish Agriculture Ministry may bid for some privatized sugar plants: Minister |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkish-agriculture-ministry-may-bid-for-some-privatized-sugar-plants-minister-128678 |work=H\u00fcrriyet Daily News |date=13 March 2018 |access-date=28 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180917215509/http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkish-agriculture-ministry-may-bid-for-some-privatized-sugar-plants-minister-128678 |archive-date=17 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> {{As of|2019}} estimates of the affects of government policy on the sector's emissions are lacking.{{sfnp|Tech review 7th communication|2019|pages=28}}\n\nIn 2018, waste emitted 3.4% of the country's greenhouse gases.<ref name=\":3\" /> Turkey is working to improve sustainable waste and resource management.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://unfccc.int/sites/default/files/resource/ndc.spotlight%2012.6.19%20Enhancing%20Climate%20Action%20in%20Turkey%20-%20Zero%20Waste%20Programme.pdf|title=Enhancing Climate Action in Turkey: Zero Waste Programme|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In particular because organic waste sent to landfill emits methane, Turkey plans to separate more of it for [[compost]]ing.<ref>{{cite news |title=Zero-waste town to be built in Turkey |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/zero-waste-town-to-be-built-in-turkey-141256 |work=H\u00fcrriyet Daily News |date=15 February 2019 |access-date=1 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302024544/http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/zero-waste-town-to-be-built-in-turkey-141256 |archive-date=2 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Climate change mitigation ==\n=== Reducing greenhouse gas emissions ===\nPolicy for a [[Just Transition|just transition]] away from carbon-intensive assets such as coal is lacking.<ref>{{cite web |title=Transition Policy for Climate Change Mitigation: Who, What, Why and How |url=https://coaltransitions.files.wordpress.com/2018/08/transition-policy-for-climate-change-mitigation.pdf |publisher=CCEP Working Paper 1807 |accessdate=24 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181124162710/https://coaltransitions.files.wordpress.com/2018/08/transition-policy-for-climate-change-mitigation.pdf |archive-date=24 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2019 ratification<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kigali-amendment.openclimatedata.net/|title=Kigali Amendment|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210095237/http://kigali-amendment.openclimatedata.net/|archive-date=10 February 2019|access-date=1 March 2019}}</ref> of the [[Montreal Protocol#Hydrofluorocarbons (HFCs)|Kigali amendment to the Montreal Protocol]] reducing emissions of [[hydrofluorocarbons]] <ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mondaq.com/turkey/x/666522/Climate+Change/Turkey+Announces+Rules+For+Use+Of+Fluorinated+Greenhouse+Gases+Listed+In+Kyoto+Protocol|title=Turkey Announces Rules For Use Of Fluorinated Greenhouse Gases Listed In Kyoto Protocol|date=23 January 2018|access-date=1 March 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302024631/http://www.mondaq.com/turkey/x/666522/Climate+Change/Turkey+Announces+Rules+For+Use+Of+Fluorinated+Greenhouse+Gases+Listed+In+Kyoto+Protocol|archive-date=2 March 2019|publisher=Mondaq}}</ref> was under consideration by parliament<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=https://webdosya.csb.gov.tr/db/cygm/haberler/s-de-event-sunumlar-20191211093159.pdf|title=Setting up a new F-gas legislation in Turkey|last1=Kleinschmidt|first1=Julia|year=2019|publisher=[[Ministry of Environment and Urban Planning (Turkey)|Ministry of Environment and Urban Planning]]}}</ref> and awaiting presidential approval.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.diken.com.tr/turkiye-emisyonlari-azaltmayi-hedefleyen-kigali-degisikligini-onayliyor/|title=T\u00fcrkiye emisyonlar\u0131 azaltmay\u0131 hedefleyen 'Kigali De\u011fi\u015fikli\u011fi'ni onayl\u0131yor|date=2019-05-16|website=Diken|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190531155456/http://www.diken.com.tr/turkiye-emisyonlari-azaltmayi-hedefleyen-kigali-degisikligini-onayliyor/|archive-date=31 May 2019|access-date=2019-05-31}}</ref> {{As of|2020}} it had not been ratified but there are some restrictions<ref>{{Cite book|last=T\u00dcM\u00d6Z G\u00dcND\u00dcZ|first=\u00d6zge|url=http://www.ozonactionmeetings.org/system/files/13_tur_ods_f-gas_regulation_in_turkey_the_link_of_the_kigali_amendment_ozge_son.pdf|title=ODS and F-gas Regulation in Turkey and the Link to the Kigali Amendment|publisher=[[Ministry of Environment and Urban Planning (Turkey)|Ministry of Environment and Urban Planning]]|year=2019|pages=}}</ref> and revision of the 2018 regulation is being considered<ref name=\":4\" /> (see also [[Registration,_Evaluation,_Authorisation_and_Restriction_of_Chemicals#In_non-EU_countries|Registration, Evaluation, Authorisation and Restriction of Chemicals]]). Turkey's Energy Efficiency Action Act, which came into force in 2018, commits nearly 11bn USD to efficiency and could significantly limit emissions.<ref>{{cite web |title=Current Policy Projections |url=https://climateactiontracker.org/countries/turkey/current-policy-projections/ |publisher=Climate Action Tracker |accessdate=28 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190301074408/https://climateactiontracker.org/countries/turkey/current-policy-projections/ |archive-date=1 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> {{As of|2019}}, however, policies had yet to be translated into measurable targets and implementation measures.<ref name=\"OECD 2019, executive summary\">OECD (2019), executive summary</ref> The [[European Bank for Reconstruction and Development]] (EBRD) is investing in energy efficiency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/energy/2019/10/02/ebrd-to-introduce-new-energy-efficiency-finance-model|title=EBRD to introduce new energy efficiency finance model|website=DailySabah|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref>\n\n==== Energy ====\n{{As of|2019}}, high interest rates are an obstacle to the construction of solar power plants,<ref>{{cite journal |first=Mert|last=G\u00fcrt\u00fcrk|title=Economic feasibility of solar power plants based on PV module with levelized cost analysis |journal=Energy|volume=171|date=15 March 2019|pages=866\u2013878|doi=10.1016/j.energy.2019.01.090}}</ref> but a solar panel factory is expected to start production in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/energy/2019/08/16/solar-panel-plant-to-boost-turkeys-role-in-renewables|title=Solar panel plant to boost Turkey's role in renewables|website=DailySabah|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref> As Turkey has plenty of water (for the moment), wind and sunshine it would be relatively easy for the country to escape from carbon lock-in<ref>\u015eahin (2018), p. 5</ref> if [[energy policy of Turkey|Turkey's energy policy]] was changed to remove the US$1.6 billion<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.shura.org.tr/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/raporweb_ENG.pdf|title=Energy pricing and non-market flows in Turkey\u2019s energy sector|last=|first=|date=|website=SHURA Energy Transition Center|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> annual fossil fuel subsidies. Experimentation with hydrogen distribution is planned for 2021:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/energy/2020/01/15/hydrogen-to-enter-fuel-energy-distribution-network-next-year|title=Hydrogen to enter fuel, energy distribution network next year|website=DailySabah|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> moving towards a [[hydrogen economy]],<ref>{{cite web |title=National Hydrogen Association (Turkey) |url=http://hidrojenteknolojileri.org/eng/ |publisher=NATIONAL HYDROGEN ASSOCIATION |accessdate=6 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190106153512/http://hidrojenteknolojileri.org/eng/ |archive-date=6 January 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> for example for heating, could reduce dependence on imported natural gas. Alternatively in rural areas without a piped gas supply [[heat pump]]s might be used.\n\nNational and international investments in renewable energy and energy efficiency are being made; for example, the [[EBRD]]. [[Smart meter]]s are being installed at a slow pace.<ref>{{cite news |title=Analysis: Smart energy investments in Turkey |url=https://www.smart-energy.com/features-analysis/analysis-turkey-energy-market/ |work=Smart Energy International |date=29 August 2017 |access-date=24 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181002141748/https://www.smart-energy.com/features-analysis/analysis-turkey-energy-market/ |archive-date=2 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==== Buildings ====\nBuilding standards in Turkey do not take into account the climate differences across the country and the existing 2005 Environment Act, Energy Efficiency Regulation and green building certificates are often not properly implemented. Academics have suggested adopting the EU standard (2018/844/EU amending the [[Directive on the energy performance of buildings]]) to increase the proportion of passive houses.<ref>A\u015f\u0131c\u0131 (2017), pages 8 and 30</ref> At the [[2019 UN Climate Action Summit]] on Turkey promised all new buildings to be [[Zero-energy building|zero carbon buildings]] by 2030 and existing buildings by 2050.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/climate-change-summit-idUKL5N26E5P0|title=FACTBOX-12 global initiatives to beat back climate threats|date=2019-09-23|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-09-27|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/op-ed/2019/10/18/climate-crisis-in-the-wake-of-a-critical-summit-1571347020|title=Climate crisis: In the wake of a critical summit|website=DailySabah|access-date=2019-10-28}}</ref> Building codes need improvement to ensure that if parking spaces are provided they have enough [[charging point]]<nowiki/>s.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==== Transport ====\nFor the [[2019 UN Climate Action Summit]] on [[carbon neutrality]] by 2050, Turkey worked on decarbonization of land transport.<ref name=UN2019>{{Cite web|url=https://www.un.org/sustainabledevelopment/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/WP-Infrastructures-Cities-and-Local-Action.pdf|title=Track #7: Infrastructure, Cities and Local Action|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Although there are several [[List of electric bus makers and models|manufacturers of electric buses]] and many are exported,<ref>{{cite news |title=Vilnius signs contract to buy its first electric buses |url=https://www.baltictimes.com/vilnius_signs_contract_to_buy_its_first_electric_buses/ |work=Baltic Times |date=27 March 2019 |access-date=27 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327165040/https://www.baltictimes.com/vilnius_signs_contract_to_buy_its_first_electric_buses/ |archive-date=27 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> {{as of|2018|lc=y}}, fewer than 100 are in use within the country.<ref>{{cite news |title=First ever self-driving e-bus in Istanbul, e-buses in provinces |url=https://balkangreenenergynews.com/first-ever-self-driving-e-bus-istanbul-e-buses-streets-provinces/ |work=Balkan Green Energy News |date=23 April 2018 |access-date=27 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327165040/https://balkangreenenergynews.com/first-ever-self-driving-e-bus-istanbul-e-buses-streets-provinces/ |archive-date=27 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Cities could be improved to make local journeys by bicycle safer.<ref>A\u015f\u0131c\u0131 (2017), page 32</ref> The world's first all-electric [[Tugboat|tug]] is due to start work in Istanbul harbor in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ship-technology.com/news/corvus-energy-provide-battery-navteks-first-electric-tug/|title=Corvus Energy to provide energy storage system for Navtek's first all-electric tug|date=2018-07-13|website=Ship Technology|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-06-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190714080541/https://www.ship-technology.com/news/corvus-energy-provide-battery-navteks-first-electric-tug/|archive-date=14 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bairdmaritime.com/work-boat-world/tug-and-salvage-world/feature-innovation-drives-rapidly-evolving-tug-and-salvage-industries/|title=FEATURE {{!}} Innovation drives rapidly evolving tug and salvage industries|last=McCready|first=John|date=2019-11-12|website=Baird Maritime|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> [[Automotive industry in Turkey|Turkey's automotive industry]] plans to make [[TOGG Turkish national car|a national electric car]] from 2022<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkey plans to create domestic car with electric engine |url=https://www.azernews.az/region/147695.html |work=Azernews |date=23 March 2019 |access-date=27 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327174036/https://www.azernews.az/region/147695.html |archive-date=27 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and has estimated that doing so would save the country 7 billion lira over 15 years, in part due to savings on oil imports.<ref>{{cite news |title=Indigenous automobile to add 50B euros to Turkish economy in 15 years |url=https://www.dailysabah.com/automotive/2019/03/25/indigenous-automobile-to-add-50b-euros-to-turkish-economy-in-15-years |work=Daily Sabah |date=25 March 2019 |access-date=27 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327173204/https://www.dailysabah.com/automotive/2019/03/25/indigenous-automobile-to-add-50b-euros-to-turkish-economy-in-15-years |archive-date=27 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Legality of ridesharing companies by jurisdiction#Turkey|legality of ridesharing companies]] is unclear,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.menabytes.com/careem-exits-turkey/|title=After Oman, Careem exits Turkey too|last=|first=|date=2020-01-23|website=MENAbytes|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-24|last3=Discovery|first3=A. Career|last4=Linkedin|first4=development platform for millennials in MENA He can be reached on|last5=zubairmenabytescom|first5=Twitter or}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newmobility.global/future-transportation/bcap-invests-turkish-rideshare-company-scotty/|title=BCAP invests in Turkish rideshare company Scotty|last=Alex|date=2020-01-16|website=New Mobility|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> and taxis could be better integrated with public transport.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dijitalle\u015fme taksi sekt\u00f6r\u00fcn\u00fc nas\u0131l etkiliyor? |url=http://www.yesillojistikciler.com/haber/dijitallesme-taksi-sektorunu-nasil-etkiliyor-16123.html |publisher=Ye\u015fil Lojistik\u00e7iler |accessdate=20 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020142208/http://www.yesillojistikciler.com/haber/dijitallesme-taksi-sektorunu-nasil-etkiliyor-16123.html |archive-date=20 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> {{As of|2019}}, fuel quality and emissions standards for new cars do not meet European Union standards.<ref name=\"European Commission 2019 page 94\" /> {{As of|2018}}, most of the country has no fast charging stations.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/energy/2018/10/11/zorlu-energy-poised-to-establish-fast-charging-stations-at-200-different-locations-in-turkey|title=Zorlu Energy poised to establish fast charging stations at 200 different locations in Turkey|date=11 October 2018|work=Daily Sabah|access-date=24 February 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327183753/https://www.dailysabah.com/energy/2018/10/11/zorlu-energy-poised-to-establish-fast-charging-stations-at-200-different-locations-in-turkey|archive-date=27 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Increasing greenhouse gas absorption by forests and soils===\n\n[[Carbon sink]]s, which in Turkey consist mainly of forests, offset about 20% of national emissions in 2017.<ref name=GHGsummary/> This figure is uncertain{{sfnp|Turkstat report|2019|p=489}} but {{As of|2019|alt=as of 2109}}, a new assessment is being made with the help of satellites and new soil measurements. Better information should be available in 2020.{{sfnp|Turkstat report|2019}}[[File:Reforestation Zone Doganbey Seferihisar Izmir Turkey.JPG|thumb|[[Do\u011fanbey, Seferihisar]] being [[reforestation#Turkey|reforested]]: but [[LULUCF]] can only reabsorb a small part of fossil fuel emissions]]\n\n[[Reforestation#Turkey|Reforestation in Turkey]] and changes in land use may offset 10% to 15% of fossil fuel emissions<ref>Ministry of Environment and Urbanization (2016), p. 18</ref> but this figure is a rough estimate<ref name=\"CarbonBrief\">{{cite web |title=The Carbon Brief Profile: Turkey |url=https://www.carbonbrief.org/carbon-brief-profile-turkey |website=Carbon Brief |accessdate=1 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181001142447/https://www.carbonbrief.org/carbon-brief-profile-turkey |archive-date=1 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> as warmer and drier air in the south and west may make it difficult to sustain the present forest cover.<ref>{{cite web |title=PROVINCE BASED FOREST COVER (%) |url=http://climatechangeinturkey.com/effects-of-climate-change-forests.html |website=CLIMATE CHANGE IN TURKEY |access-date=24 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180517191309/http://climatechangeinturkey.com/effects-of-climate-change-forests.html |archive-date=17 May 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[NGO]]s such as the [[TEMA Foundation]] are encouraging reforestation and in 2015, the government stated that, by 2050, \u201cforests are envisioned to stretch across over four-fifths of the country's territory\u201d.<ref>{{cite news |title=What can Africa learn from Turkey's reforestation? |url=https://www.weforum.org/agenda/2015/10/what-can-africa-learn-from-turkeys-reforestation/ |publisher=World Economic Forum |date=29 October 2015 |access-date=24 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190122192832/https://www.weforum.org/agenda/2015/10/what-can-africa-learn-from-turkeys-reforestation/ |archive-date=22 January 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, according to [[Ege University]] Associate Professor Serdar G\u00f6khan Senol, sometimes the government is too focused on the economics and the [[Ministry of Agriculture and Forestry (Turkey)|Ministry of Agriculture and Forestry]] replants when sometimes it should just wait for regrowth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.youris.com/environment/biodiversity/wildfires-in-izmir-a-green-plan-for-the-city-an-urban-plan-for-the-forests.kl|title=Wildfires in Izmir: a green plan for the city, an urban plan for the forests|website=www.youris.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref>\n\nThree quarters of the land is deficient in [[Soil organic matter|soil organic carbon]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkish soil at risk as worldwide desertification spreads |url=https://www.dailysabah.com/life/2018/06/19/turkish-soil-at-risk-as-worldwide-desertification-spreads |work=Daily Sabah |date=19 June 2018 |access-date=24 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330005959/https://www.dailysabah.com/life/2018/06/19/turkish-soil-at-risk-as-worldwide-desertification-spreads |archive-date=30 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and this is being mapped to be added to Turkey's national soil database.<ref name=\"FAO\">{{cite journal |last1=SONMEZ |display-authors=et al |title=Turkey's National Geospatial Soil Organic Carbon Information System |journal=Global Symposium on Soil Organic Carbon |date=March 2017 |url=http://www.fao.org/3/a-br972e.pdf |access-date=24 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181011172947/http://www.fao.org/3/a-br972e.pdf |archive-date=11 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Economics==\n\nIn the late 20th and early 21st centuries growth of the [[Economy of Turkey|Turkish economy]] and population caused increased emissions from electricity generation,{{sfnp|4th biennial report|2019|pages=10,11}} industry and construction.{{citation needed|date=November 2019}} However, when economic growth resumes after [[Turkish currency and debt crisis, 2018|Turkey's late 2010s recession]] it would be possible to further exploit the country's renewable energy potential and further invest in energy efficiency: so if the government implemented a suitable energy policy the economy could easily grow without increasing emissions.<ref name=\"Climate Action Tracker 2019 p. 63\"/>\n\nTurkey's [[social cost of carbon|carbon emissions]] cost Turkey money, even without [[carbon tariff]]s from other countries.<ref>{{cite news |title=New study finds incredibly high carbon pollution costs \u2013 especially for the US and India |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/climate-consensus-97-per-cent/2018/oct/01/new-study-finds-incredibly-high-carbon-pollution-costs-especially-for-the-us-and-india |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=1 October 2018 |access-date=24 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190208114443/https://www.theguardian.com/environment/climate-consensus-97-per-cent/2018/oct/01/new-study-finds-incredibly-high-carbon-pollution-costs-especially-for-the-us-and-india |archive-date=8 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The long-term impact of climate change on any economy is highly uncertain and very difficult to estimate.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Stoerk |first1=Thomas |last2=Wagner |first2=Gernot |last3=Ward |first3=Robert E T |title=Policy Brief\u2014Recommendations for Improving the Treatment of Risk and Uncertainty in Economic Estimates of Climate Impacts in the Sixth Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change Assessment Report |journal=Review of Environmental Economics and Policy |date=1 August 2018 |volume=12 |issue=2 |pages=371\u2013376 |doi=10.1093/reep/rey005 }}</ref> Although the short-term co-benefits of climate-change mitigation have been estimated at over US$50/tonne CO<sub>2</sub> abated for health alone for middle-income countries generally<ref>{{cite web |title=Multiple benefits from climate change mitigation: assessing the evidence |url=http://www.lse.ac.uk/GranthamInstitute/publication/multiple-benefits-from-climate-change-mitigation-assessing-the-evidence/ |publisher=[[London School of Economics]] |access-date=24 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190710222455/http://www.lse.ac.uk/GranthamInstitute/publication/multiple-benefits-from-climate-change-mitigation-assessing-the-evidence/ |archive-date=10 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=MONETIZING THE HEALTH CO-BENEFITS OF A CARBON TAX |url=https://niskanencenter.org/blog/notes/monetizing-the-health-co-benefits-of-a-carbon-tax/ |publisher=Niskanen Center |accessdate=1 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928201000/https://niskanencenter.org/blog/notes/monetizing-the-health-co-benefits-of-a-carbon-tax/ |archive-date=28 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> research to quantify them specifically for Turkey is still ongoing {{As of|2020||lc=y}}.<ref name=\":5\" /> \n\n[[Bo\u011fazi\u00e7i University]] have developed a decision support tool and [[Integrated assessment modelling|integrated assessment model]] for energy and environmental policy for Turkey.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Isik |first1=Mine |title=Development of the Bo\u011fazi\u00e7i University Energy Modeling System (BUEMS) and its Application on Economic and Technological Implications of Greenhouse Gas Emission Reductions in Turkey |url=https://www.researchgate.net/project/Development-of-the-Bogazici-University-Energy-Modeling-System-BUEMS-and-its-Application-on-Economic-and-Technological-Implications-of-Greenhouse-Gas-Emission-Reductions-in-Turkey |website=ResearchGate |accessdate=1 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181001182307/https://www.researchgate.net/project/Development-of-the-Bogazici-University-Energy-Modeling-System-BUEMS-and-its-Application-on-Economic-and-Technological-Implications-of-Greenhouse-Gas-Emission-Reductions-in-Turkey |archive-date=1 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Bo\u011fazi\u00e7i \u00dcniversitesi'nden T\u00fcrkiye'nin enerji politikalar\u0131na y\u00f6n verecek ara\u015ft\u0131rma |url=http://haberler.boun.edu.tr/tr/haber/bogazici-universitesinden-turkiyenin-enerji-politikalarina-yon-verecek-arastirma |publisher=Bo\u011fazi\u00e7i University |accessdate=1 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181001182935/http://haberler.boun.edu.tr/tr/haber/bogazici-universitesinden-turkiyenin-enerji-politikalarina-yon-verecek-arastirma |archive-date=1 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>  One study puts the health benefits at 2.9 \u2013 3.6 billion EUR per year<ref>Jenson (2014), p. 6</ref> due mainly to a substantial increase in GDP because of reduced PM 2.5 [[Air pollution in Turkey|air pollution in the country]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Air Pollution and Health in Turkey Facts, Figures and Recommendations |url=https://www.env-health.org/IMG/pdf/150220_factsheet_air_and_health_turkey_en_final.pdf |publisher=Health and Environment Alliance (HEAL) |accessdate=1 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822190726/http://env-health.org/IMG/pdf/150220_factsheet_air_and_health_turkey_en_final.pdf |archive-date=22 August 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Pant by numbers: the cities with the most dangerous air \u2013 listed |url=https://www.theguardian.com/cities/datablog/2017/feb/13/most-polluted-cities-world-listed-region |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=13 February 2017 |access-date=24 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190223235324/https://www.theguardian.com/cities/datablog/2017/feb/13/most-polluted-cities-world-listed-region |archive-date=23 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Another study estimated that by creating a national emissions trading market at a US$50/tonne carbon price the INDC commitment could be met at a cost of 0.8% of GDP by 2030. But it did not estimate how much the benefits would offset that cost or what the cost of not having a market would be.<ref>{{cite news|title=Researchers examine Turkey to assess the impact of 2015 Paris climate commitments on a national economy|url=https://phys.org/news/2018-07-turkey-impact-paris-climate-commitments_1.html|publisher=[[MIT]]|date=31 July 2018|access-date=24 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181001182352/https://phys.org/news/2018-07-turkey-impact-paris-climate-commitments_1.html|archive-date=1 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Currently there is only a voluntary market.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.climatescorecard.org/2020/03/a-voluntary-carbon-market-in-need-of-carbon-pricing-policy-in-turkey/|title=A Voluntary Carbon Market in need of Carbon Pricing Policy in Turkey|last=Duyan|first=\u00d6zlem|date=2020-03-19|website=Climate Scorecard|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> A revenue neutral carbon tax might be best for the economy,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bavbek |first1=G\u00f6k\u015fin |title=Assessing the Potential Effects of a Carbon Tax in Turkey |journal=Centre for Economics and Foreign Policy Studies (EDAM) Energy and Climate Change Climate Action Paper |date=October 2016 |issue=6 |url=http://edam.org.tr/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/EDAM_CarbonTaxEffects_October2016.pdf |access-date=24 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181002141946/http://edam.org.tr/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/EDAM_CarbonTaxEffects_October2016.pdf |archive-date=2 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> and without a carbon tax or emissions trading the country could be vulnerable to future carbon tariffs imposed by the EU,<ref>{{cite news |title=Carbon tariffs are EU's secret weapon in trade battle |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2018/06/05/carbon-tariffs-eus-secret-weapon-trade-battle/ |work=Daily Telegraph |date=5 June 2018 |access-date=24 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190506052457/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2018/06/05/carbon-tariffs-eus-secret-weapon-trade-battle/ |archive-date=6 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Pollution Costs at Decade High Squeeze Industry, Coal in Europe |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-08-24/pollution-costs-at-decade-high-squeeze-industry-coal-in-europe |work=Bloomberg |date=24 August 2018 |access-date=24 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190611051319/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-08-24/pollution-costs-at-decade-high-squeeze-industry-coal-in-europe |archive-date=11 June 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> the UK or other [[Economy of Turkey#External trade and investment|export partners]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Carbon Tariffs: A Climate Necessity? |url=http://regulatingforglobalization.com/2018/03/13/carbon-tariffs-climate-necessity/ |website=Kluwer Regulating for Globalization |accessdate=11 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181011172855/http://regulatingforglobalization.com/2018/03/13/carbon-tariffs-climate-necessity/ |archive-date=11 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2018}}, Turkey receives by far the most EU climate change financing<ref>{{cite news |title=Questions raised about EU climate financing as Turkey takes biggest share |url=https://www.devex.com/news/questions-raised-about-eu-climate-financing-as-turkey-takes-biggest-share-92562 |work=devex |date=18 April 2018 |access-date=24 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181002141838/https://www.devex.com/news/questions-raised-about-eu-climate-financing-as-turkey-takes-biggest-share-92562 |archive-date=2 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> and the [[EBRD]] is investing.<ref name=\"Climate Home\">{{cite web|title=Turkey: Notes from a state of (climatic) emergency|url=http://www.climatechangenews.com/2016/11/10/turkey-notes-from-a-state-of-climatic-emergency/|publisher=Climate Home|access-date=24 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181002141830/http://www.climatechangenews.com/2016/11/10/turkey-notes-from-a-state-of-climatic-emergency/|archive-date=2 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 the government forecast that GHG emissions were expected to increase in parallel to the GDP growth in the next decade. {{sfnp|7th communication v2|2019|p=30}} In 2015 less than half of Turkey's carbon emissions from energy use were priced.<ref>OECD (2019), page 32</ref> Taxes meet the social cost of road transport carbon, although not the social cost of [[Air pollution in Turkey|Turkey's local air pollution]], but all other sectors have a large gap between the actual price and the cost if this [[negative externality]] had been fully included, thus the [[external cost]] of most greenhouse gas emissions is not being borne by the emitters.<ref>{{cite web |title=Effective Carbon Rates 2018 |url=https://www.oecd.org/tax/effective-carbon-rates-2018-9789264305304-en.htm |publisher=[[OECD]] |date=18 September 2018 |access-date=5 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190106010542/https://www.oecd.org/tax/effective-carbon-rates-2018-9789264305304-en.htm |archive-date=6 January 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Thus the [[polluter pays principle]] is being violated.\n\nIn 2017, a tenth of Turkey's electricity was generated by renewables, which reduced gas import costs. But being mainly [[hydroelectricity]], this percentage is vulnerable to drought. According to H\u00fclya Sayg\u0131l\u0131, an economist at [[Central Bank of the Republic of Turkey|Turkey's central bank]], although imports of solar and wind power components accounted for 12 percent of import costs in 2017, in EU countries this is largely due to one-time setup costs. She said that compared with Italy and Greece, Turkey has not invested enough in solar and wind power.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sayg\u0131l\u0131 |first1=H\u00fclya |title=RENEWABLE ENERGY USE IN TURKEY |url=http://www.tcmb.gov.tr/wps/wcm/connect/blog/en/main+menu/analyses/renewable_energy_us_+in_turkey |website=CBRT blog |accessdate=17 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190218021333/http://www.tcmb.gov.tr/wps/wcm/connect/blog/en/main+menu/analyses/renewable_energy_us_+in_turkey |archive-date=18 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Co-benefits===\nAlthough improved health would be the primary benefit of cutting [[air pollution in Turkey]], because most of the air pollution is caused by burning fossil fuels a reduction of greenhouse gas emissions would be a co-benefit; for example of [[low emission zone]]s for city traffic, and replacing the distribution of free coal<ref>{{Cite journal|last=HAL\u0130S\u00c7EL\u0130K|first=Erg\u00fcl|date=2017|title=HOW TO DELIVER FREE COAL TO THE POOR FAMILIES? TURKEY CASE|url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Erguel_Haliscelik/publication/322207751_HOW_TO_DELIVER_FREE_COAL_TO_THE_POOR_FAMILIES_TURKEY_CASE/links/5c6c0be34585156b57080d92/HOW-TO-DELIVER-FREE-COAL-TO-THE-POOR-FAMILIES-TURKEY-CASE.pdf|journal=Y\u00f6netim ve Ekonomi Ara\u015ft\u0131rmalar\u0131 Dergisi / Journal of Management and Economics Research|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> with a different support for poor families. Increasing the share of renewable energy could make the country more energy independent and increase employment<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web |title=Cobenefits:Turkey |url=https://www.cobenefits.info/our-work/where-we-work/turkey/ |publisher=COBENEFITS |accessdate=28 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190301013425/https://www.cobenefits.info/our-work/where-we-work/turkey/ |archive-date=1 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> especially in [[solar power in Turkey|Turkey's solar PV and solar heating industries]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Renewable Energy and Jobs Annual Review 2018 |url=https://irena.org/-/media/Files/IRENA/Agency/Publication/2018/May/IRENA_RE_Jobs_Annual_Review_2018.pdf |publisher=[[International Renewable Energy Agency]] |accessdate=28 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121203527/https://irena.org/-/media/Files/IRENA/Agency/Publication/2018/May/IRENA_RE_Jobs_Annual_Review_2018.pdf |archive-date=21 January 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\n\nThe [[Climate Change and Air Management Coordination Board (Turkey)|Climate Change and Air Management Coordination Board]] is responsible for coordination across government departments. It also includes three business organizations.<ref>{{cite web |title=Te\u015fkilat Yap\u0131s\u0131 |url=https://iklim.csb.gov.tr/teskilat-yapisi-i-4368 |publisher=[[Ministry of Environment and Urban Planning (Turkey)]] |accessdate=30 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422073732/https://iklim.csb.gov.tr/teskilat-yapisi-i-4368 |archive-date=22 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAccording to \u00dcmit \u015eahin, who teaches climate change at [[Sabanc\u0131 University]], Turkey sees industrialized Western countries as solely responsible.<ref>\u015eahin (2019), p. 24</ref> When limiting their actions on climate change, Turkey and some other countries have cited the [[United States withdrawal from the Paris Agreement]] promised by [[Donald Trump|President Trump]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Climate change: 'Trump effect' threatens Paris pact |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-46384828 |work=[[BBC]] |date=3 December 2018 |access-date=24 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190424174404/https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-46384828 |archive-date=24 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIt has been suggested that, although limiting emissions through directives to the state owned gas and electricity companies would be less effective than a carbon price or tax, it would be more politically acceptable.<ref>{{cite web |title=How to Talk to a Populist About Climate Change |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/03/29/how-to-talk-to-a-populist-about-climate-change/ |website=Foreign Policy |accessdate=31 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330162418/https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/03/29/how-to-talk-to-a-populist-about-climate-change/ |archive-date=30 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to former Economy Minister Kemal Dervish, the gains from the green transition will be spread across large parts of the population; while the losses will be concentrated on specific groups, making them more visible and politically disruptive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.globaltimes.cn/content/1163546.shtml|title=Distributional issues hurt fight to curb climate change - Global Times|website=www.globaltimes.cn|access-date=2019-09-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190904143541/http://www.globaltimes.cn/content/1163546.shtml|archive-date=4 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> People in Turkey taking [[individual and political action on climate change]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.middleeasteye.net/news/activists-turkey-demonstrate-call-unite-behind-science-climate-change|title=Activists in Turkey demonstrate with call to 'unite behind the science' on climate change|website=Middle East Eye|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> include children demanding action<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ahvalnews.com/climate-crisis/turkeys-11-year-old-activist-demands-grown-action-climate-change|title=Turkey's 11-year-old activist demands grown-up action on climate change|website=Ahval|language=en|access-date=2019-09-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190904141307/https://ahvalnews.com/climate-crisis/turkeys-11-year-old-activist-demands-grown-action-climate-change|archive-date=4 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and petitioning the UN.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://grist.org/article/what-the-climate-petition-filed-by-16-kids-at-the-u-n-really-means/|title=What the climate petition filed by 16 kids at the U.N. really means|date=2019-09-25|website=Grist|language=en|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref>\n\n===Ratification of the Paris agreement===\nAccording to [[Ministry of Energy and Natural Resources (Turkey)|Turkey's Ministry of Energy and Natural Resources]], climate change is one of the world's biggest problems.<ref>{{cite web |title=Climate Change and International Negotiations |url=http://www.enerji.gov.tr/en-US/Pages/Climate-Change-and-International-Negotiations |publisher=[[Ministry of Energy and Natural Resources (Turkey)]] |accessdate=28 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928200850/http://www.enerji.gov.tr/en-US/Pages/Climate-Change-and-International-Negotiations |archive-date=28 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Like neighboring Iran and Iraq, Turkey is one of the few [[List of parties to the Paris Agreement#Signatories|countries that have not ratified the Paris agreement on climate change]], and has said it will not ratify until it is given more access to international loans for emission reduction and renewable energy investments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iklimhaber.org/chief-climate-negotiator-turkey-does-not-have-a-luxury-to-be-a-laggard-in-terms-of-climate-action/|title=Chief Climate Negotiator: Turkey Does Not Have a Luxury to Be a Laggard in Terms of Climate Action|last=Bagat\u0131r|first=Bulut|date=2018-12-13|website=\u0130klim Haber|language=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref>\n\n===Access to data===\nAbout 800 entities, including power plants over 20 MW, send measurements of their GHG emissions to the government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://icapcarbonaction.com/en/?option=com_etsmap&task=export&format=pdf&layout=list&systems%5B%5D=66|title=ETS Detailed Information: Turkey|website=International Carbon Action Partnership|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>  Unlike conditions under the [[European Union Emission Trading Scheme]], where data must be openly shared with the public, {{as of|2018|lc=y}}, monitoring, reporting and verification (MRV) data in Turkey is not open to public access,<ref>{{cite web |title=EU Emission Trading System Directive Preliminary Regulatory Impact Assessment (Pre-RIA) |url=http://www.lowcarbonturkey.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Annex-3_ETS-RIA-eng.pdf |access-date=30 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430095304/http://www.lowcarbonturkey.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Annex-3_ETS-RIA-eng.pdf |archive-date=30 April 2019 |url-status=live |page=26}}</ref> although some companies report voluntarily. Quantitative estimates of the impacts of individual government policies on greenhouse gas emissions either have not been made or are not publicly available {{sfnp|Tech review 7th communication|2019|p=20}} and neither are projections of long-term (to 2050) policy impacts.{{sfnp|Tech review 7th communication|2019|p=21}} Up to date GDP and population growth forecasts have not been incorporated into models and assumptions such as future energy intensity, energy demand and electricity consumption are not known.{{sfnp|Tech review 7th communication|2019|p=23}} Whether [[sensitivity analysis]] of ghg scenarios has been done is also not known.{{sfnp|Tech review 7th communication|2019|p=23}} Turkey has told the UNFCCC that many details needed to understand GHG past trends and future projections \"could not be provided for confidentiality reasons.\"{{sfnp|Tech review 7th communication|2019|pages=27-28}}\n\n===Children's rights complaint===\nIn 2019 environmental activist [[Greta Thunberg]] and 15 other children made an official complaint against five nations that are not on track to meet the emission reduction targets they committed to in their Paris Agreement pledges: Argentina, Brazil, France, Germany, and Turkey.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.unicef.org/press-releases/16-children-including-greta-thunberg-file-landmark-complaint-united-nations |title=16 children, including Greta Thunberg, file landmark complaint to the United Nations Committee on the Rights of the Child |website=www.unicef.org |language=en|access-date=25 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190925123907/https://www.unicef.org/press-releases/16-children-including-greta-thunberg-file-landmark-complaint-united-nations|archive-date=25 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.un.org/en/story/2019/09/1047292 |title=Countries violate rights over climate change, argue youth activists in landmark UN complaint |date=24 September 2019 |website=UN News |language=en|access-date=25 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190925105953/https://news.un.org/en/story/2019/09/1047292|archive-date=25 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The complaint challenges these five countries under the Third Optional Protocol to the [[Convention on the Rights of the Child]]. The Protocol is a quasi-judicial mechanism which allows children or their representatives, who believe their rights have been violated to bring a complaint before the relevant \u2018treaty body\u2019, the Committee on the Rights of the Child.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.childrightsconnect.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/CRC_OP3_info_pack_web.pdf |title=Information Pack about the Optional Protocol to the Convention on theRights of the Child on a Communications Procedure (OP3 CRC) |access-date=13 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191013184521/https://www.childrightsconnect.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/CRC_OP3_info_pack_web.pdf |archive-date=13 October 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> If the complaint is successful, the countries will be asked to respond, but any suggestions are not legally binding.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://earther.gizmodo.com/its-kids-vs-the-world-in-a-landmark-new-climate-lawsui-1838343565 |title=It's Kids vs. the World in a Landmark New Climate Lawsuit |first=Brian |last=Kahn |date=23 September 2019 |accessdate=23 September 2019 |work=[[Gizmodo]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190923170617/https://earther.gizmodo.com/its-kids-vs-the-world-in-a-landmark-new-climate-lawsui-1838343565 | archive-date = 23 September 2019 | url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.bloombergenvironment.com/environment-and-energy/greta-thunberg-leads-young-people-in-climate-complaint-to-un |title=Greta Thunberg Leads Young People in Climate Complaint to UN |date=23 September 2019 |accessdate=23 September 2019 |work=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190924041649/https://news.bloombergenvironment.com/environment-and-energy/greta-thunberg-leads-young-people-in-climate-complaint-to-un?utm_medium=ehsdesk&utm_campaign=530399D8-DE13-11E9-B270-A91350017A06&utm_source=twitter | archive-date = 24 September 2019 | url-status = live}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\n\nAccording to journalist Pelin Cengiz, the mainstream [[media of Turkey]] tends to cover newly opened [[List of coal-fired power stations in Turkey|coal-fired power stations in Turkey]] as increasing employment rather than causing climate change, and almost all owners have financial interests in fossil fuels.<ref>Cengiz (2019), p. 17,20</ref> According to \u00dcmit \u015eahin, who teaches climate change at Sabanc\u0131 University, the media covers climate change only in times of extreme weather events, but does not include sufficient perspectives from civil society or expert opinion.<ref>\u015eahin (2019), p. 28</ref> Some construction companies have been accused of [[greenwashing]] by advertising their buildings as environmentally friendly without actually obtaining any green building certificates.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Erden|first=O\u011fulkan|last2=Erkartal|first2=P\u0131nar \u00d6KTEM|date=2019-09-02|title=Greenwashing in Turkey: Sustainability as an Advertising Strategy in Architecture|url=https://dergipark.org.tr/en/pub/aarch/613890|journal=A+Arch Design International Journal of Architecture and Design|language=en|volume=5|issue=1|pages=1\u201313|issn=2149-5904}}</ref>\n\n==Research and history==\nResearch is done at the [https://ipc.sabanciuniv.edu/category/climate-change/index916b.html?lang=en&post_type=objective Istanbul Policy Center] and [https://www.shura.org.tr/eng/ Shura Energy Transition Center], both at [[Sabanc\u0131 University]]. \n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Turkey|Global Warming}}\n\n*[[Climate change in Turkey]]\n*[[Energy policy of Turkey]]\n*[[Greenhouse gas inventory]]\n*[[List of countries by carbon dioxide emissions]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n\n====UNFCCC====\n*{{cite web  \n |work=Ministry of Environment and Urbanization\n |title=Seventh National Communication (version 2) of Turkey under the UNFCCC (this is also the third biennial report)\n |date=August 2019   \n |url=https://unfccc.int/sites/default/files/resource/14936285_Turkey-NC7-2-Seventh%20National%20Communication%20of%20Turkey.pdf\n |ref={{harvid|7th communication v2|2019}}  \n }}\n*{{cite web  \n |work=UNFCCC\n |title=Report on the technical review of the seventh national communication of Turkey\n |date=June 2019\n |url=https://unfccc.int/sites/default/files/resource/idr7_TUR.pdf\n |ref={{harvid|